[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "2"]

1. e4 c6 {Hello, dear reader! My name is Volen Dyulgerov from Bulgaria. I started playing chess when I was 10, as my brother started first, and I really liked the game. I played seriously until I was 17, then I quit chess to follow education. I came back to chess as a chess streamer on September 13, 2022. My plan for streaming is to share my love for chess as well as the things that I have learned over the years with anyone ready to listen and make people laugh. When I make people laugh, I am happy. :) Here are my current accomplishments: Blitz Chess champion of Bulgaria Under 20 (2015) Chess champion of Bulgaria under 18 (2017) Chess champion of Bulgaria under 20 (2018) FIDE Candidate Master since 2023. Inventor of the Alien Gambit (Sep 25, 2023) Inventor of the Martian Gambit (Jul 7, 2024) My goal for this course is to teach people how to attack, spot tactics, think creatively, and enjoy chess like the chess giants did in the romantic area of chess. The Alien and Martian Gambits are perfect gambits to teach them that. I have always found it effortless and incredibly rewarding to walk people through how to do something and help them break down how to learn and improve in whatever it is that they are trying to accomplish. For me, it's about igniting a passion, igniting love, igniting motivation for the sport, and developing a deep, enduring understanding of aggressive thinking and tactical decision-making. And it is about giving students the necessary chess abilities and skills that they can make use of in every single game they play my gambits. Overall, my gambits will teach them how to think, how to attack, and how to spot tactics.} ({The Alien & Martian Gambits have given me so much joy in chess. Every time someone plays} 1... c6 {, I feel butterflies. I am absolutely happy when I get one of my gambits. I have an emotional relationship with those gambits. They have been there for many beautiful attacking victories and some heartbreaking defeats. One of the beautiful things about choosing a chess opening is they are always there for you as a kind of friend, and they can play a large role in shaping your chess identity, as it's shaped mine. Nowadays, people always say that gambits are bad, that engines refuted them long ago, thus 'play-by-the-book' chess only. False! As long as chess is played by humans, gambits will always live. Of course, maybe not at the professional level, but in club chess, amateur chess, and online chess, you can have fun with whatever your heart desires! Please know that you are on this course because you are tired of boring chess. You are tired of textbook chess. You want to have fun. You want to play out-of-this-world gambits and win beautifully and flex to your friends. Please, my dear reader, remember that by best play, Black is winning. I have tried my best with all my heart to produce practical moves, moves that I have faced, and show practical ways to win. The reason I even made this course, the reason even Chessable allowed me to make this course, is because my gambits work. Out of 15 games, I win 14 and lose 1 with the Alien and Martian Gambits. It's a free win. It's just rarer than AG. Not because I said so, but because they have been fact-checked with so many games, and Black almost always goes wrong. Please don't think that Chessable or I would ever teach something ineffective. Give it time, learn the ideas, and you'll be surprised at how many games you'll win – quite easily, actually. Remember one very important thing. Do NOT memorize lines. Learn ideas, learn patterns, learn tactics, learn pattern recognition, but (almost) never memorize complete lines. Use this course as a blueprint. A template. Whenever you get in the Alien Gambit or the Martian Gambit, a move you have not faced before, feel free to go to this course (I am sure I have shown and explained the move), learn the move, and then next time destroy your opponent with beautiful tactics. Remember that chess is to be enjoyed. To have fun and to produce fun for others who watch your games. Good luck, have fun, Godspeed.}) *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Alien Gambit 4...Nf6 - 7...e6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B15"]
[PlyCount "29"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 ({ This is considered the main line of the Caro-Kann Defense and the most popular move.  With} 4... Nf6 {, Black immediately challenges White's central pony, aiming to provoke exchanges that can help simplify the position and alleviate White's early pressure. It's remarkably trendy these days.}) 5. Ng5 ( {This move initializes the Alien Gambit! At least in chess.com! For my dear viewers and me, Alien Gambit starts after h6 , and Nxf7!! So, to state that this move is already bringing us to the Alien Gambit is wrong. Here, you can even transpose to the Martian Gambit if Black plays Bf5} 5. Nf3 {Bg6 Bc4} h6 { and Ne6!! Chess.com told me that the decision is based on the following: if you go Ng5 , you plan to sacrifice, but Black is not forced to go ... h6 , even though 90% of the people play ... h6 . The idea of Ng5 is simple. Play for the Alien Gambit! When you play this move, don't ever think of going back with the pony.}) (5. Nxf6+ {is the most common move and the move I used to play a lot before I invented the Alien Gambit. Korchnoi (or Tartakower) Variation, Black's} exf6 {, is regarded as sounder than gxf6!? , the Bronstein-Larsen Variation, which offers Black rapid development, though also ceding White the superior pawn structure and long-term prospects (Black has to be cautious that the d-pawn is now a potential passed pawn in the endgame).}) ( {Since we won't play Nxf6 but hop with the pony on g5 , we stop the lines here. } 5. Ng3 {is a move I played a lot, with bad results after} h5 $1) 5... h6 ({ This move occurs 85-90% of the time. It used to be more often, but since the Alien Gambit is so OP, they try to avoid it by playing moves like} 5... Bf5 { , Bg4 or c5 . Do not lose heart; I will teach you how to face those moves. Black is probably like, what the heck!? What is this move? Just kick the pony and gain vital tempi. But here comes...}) 6. Nxf7 {Alieeeeeeeeen Gambiiiiiiiiiiiiiiit!! If you don't scream it, it won't work! :D Obviously, the move is a blunder according to the engine, but practically speaking, this is such a good move for Bullet, Blitz, and even Rapid (judging by rapid results from people). Trust me, guys, I would never preach something that sucks or is really bad. Do not lose heart; the analysis and practical games below will prove how OP the gambit is. I have played the Alien Gambit 1000 games so far. And my win rate is 73%. THIS IS A HUGE WIN RATE!! The Alien Gambit is such an OP gambit if you are willing to learn it. Do you want to have fun? This is the type of stuff you want to play. The purpose of the move is to take a pawn (the critical f7 -pawn) and to disallow the king from castling.} Kxf7 {White has LONG-term positional compensation. When I say LONG term, I mean it. The point for white here is NOT to attack right away, but to develop their kingside and then attack. That is why the Alien Gambit (AG) is so dangerous because your opponent usually laughs at how we play so calmly while being a FULL piece down. Black will forever have weaknesses on the light squares, especially the b1 - h7 diagonal as well as the h5 - e8 diagonal. Also, the e5 -square is critical for White, but we don't jump with the pony right away (this is very important to know) , as we will see. When you play the Alien Gambit, you need to be practical-centered, not engine-centered, as engines just beat the gambit with ease, but we play against humans, and we use the element of surprise to our advantage. Another reason why the gambit is so good is because your opponent is human. They see they are a piece up and will go for the artificial castle defense and then just be a piece up. As we will see, White almost always wins against this defense, if they know what they are doing.} 7. Nf3 {This move is critical. Controlling the e5 -square, postponing the development of the light-squared bishop, and setting up a deadly trap.} (7. Bc4+ $6 {is the most common move by people who have not studied the gambit. A lone bishop can never do anything, and MOST of the time, the light-squared bishop belongs on the d3 -square.} e6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Nd5 ({ IM yoseph2013 (3017) vs. GM Vladimirovich9000 (3134), Jul 27, 2024 continued:} 10... Re8 11. Ne5+ Bxe5 $2 {Everybody plays this. The pony on e5 is very strong, so they want to exchange it. Even Dmitry Andreikin wants to.} (11... Kg8 12. Qf3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 {, and we can see how the bishop belongs on d3 .} ) 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Bxh6 $3 {Sacrifice the bishop to open the king. } gxh6 15. Qg6+ Kf8 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17. Re4 $1 {The rookie joins the attack, and the game is pretty much over despite being two pieces down.} Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf6 19. Rg5+ Kf7 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Rg8# {.}) 11. Ne5+ Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bc7 {, and we can see that the bishop on c4 is hitting the rock on d5 , so it needs to go back to d3 .}) 7... e6 (7... e6 {and Nbd7 are THE most popular moves, as they are the most human ones. Black sees that their king is weak, so their main idea is to make an artificial castle, then develop their pieces and win the game being a piece up. But actually, this is what we are hoping for!}) 8. Bd3 { The right square for the bishop! Aiming at the critical b1 - h7 diagonal.} Nbd7 {Black avoids immediate danger by stopping Ne5 +, but in the long run, the queenside might never develop, as the following examples will show.} 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 {Gaining the critical e5 -square and preparing Ne5 +!} Qc7 {To stop Ne5 . That is a very strong move; I have faced this move rarely, ONLY with people who have looked at the engine.} 11. Qe2 {Supporting the pony jump to e5 .} Re8 12. Ne5+ Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Qh5+ {Usually, if the white queen goes to h5 with check, White is winning.} Kg8 (14... Ke7 15. Bg6 $1 {Now Qh4 + will not be met with ... g5 .} Rf8 16. Qh4+ {.}) 15. Qxe8+ {And White is winning.} *

