just be a piece up. As we will see, White almost always wins against this defense, if they know what they are doing.} 7. Nf3 {This move is critical. Controlling the e5 -square, postponing the development of the light-squared bishop, and setting up a deadly trap.} (7. Bc4+ $6 {is the most common move by people who have not studied the gambit. A lone bishop can never do anything, and MOST of the time, the light-squared bishop belongs on the d3 -square.} e6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Nd5 ({ IM yoseph2013 (3017) vs. GM Vladimirovich9000 (3134), Jul 27, 2024 continued:} 10... Re8 11. Ne5+ Bxe5 $2 {Everybody plays this. The pony on e5 is very strong, so they want to exchange it. Even Dmitry Andreikin wants to.} (11... Kg8 12. Qf3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 {, and we can see how the bishop belongs on d3 .} ) 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Bxh6 $3 {Sacrifice the bishop to open the king. } gxh6 15. Qg6+ Kf8 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17. Re4 $1 {The rookie joins the attack, and the game is pretty much over despite being two pieces down.} Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf6 19. Rg5+ Kf7 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Rg8# {.}) 11. Ne5+ Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bc7 {, and we can see that the bishop on c4 is hitting the rock on d5 , so it needs to go back to d3 .}) 7... c5 {THE REFUTATION OF THE ALIEN GAMBIT. JUST ON PAPER THO. This is also the RAREST move I have faced too. The reason it's so rare is because it's so counterintuitive. Nobody, absolutely nobody, will play this move if THEY ARE NOT IN HOME PREPERATION!} ({Please think for a second if you are Black before} 7... c5 {. Hmm, I am a piece up. White has only one pawn for it, but my king is weak. I need to play e6 , ... Bd6 , ... Re8 / f8 , and ... Kg8 , then open the game and win as I am a full piece up. Oh, and it's imperative for me not to open the game before I improve my king.}) (7... c5 { does NONE of that though. I remember watching a clip of Hikaru when he was making Alien Gambit arenas and how shocked he was to find out that} 8. dxc5 { is the best move. He always played the} e6 {and ... Nbd7 plan. After thinking for a bit, Hikaru said: 'You know, c5 makes a lot of sense now because you need to develop the knight on c6 rather than d7 .' The reason why c5 is so good is that it frees the c6 -square for the pony and puts pressure on the d4 -pawn, so White doesn't have the time to go Bd3 , O-O , Re1 , and Ne5 +. Black's king is safe, as White's pieces are not developed. I hear people saying: 'Nowadays, we have strong engines that ring the alarm bell when something is not quite kosher. With their help, you can even analyze certain position types until you reach a final verdict. This means the end of an era and the inevitable decline of all incorrect gambits.' This is true and false. True, because the Alien Gambit is NOT recommended for classical chess and Fide Candidates level, it's for club chess, online chess, and romance. :) When we play chess, we play for fun. We are not professionals. If aggressive style is your style, go for it! Have fun! :)}) 8. Ne5+ {A good move, changing gears right away, realizing there is no time for Bd3 , O-O , and Re1 . White has to do something fast.} ({It's imperative for you, dear reader, to learn this line, too, as when your opponent starts defending against} 8. d5 $1 {, you can play yet another amazing move, and top engine one too. This move is good, as Black's last move did not develop a piece, so we try to attack right away.}) ( 8. Bd3 $6 {is a very tricky move, but not the one I recommend. The idea is to defend the d4 -pawn with tactics, but it's fragile.} Nc6 (8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 { , White is using tactics.} Qxd4 $4 {( e5–+ and Black controls the center while being a piece up. Therefore, they are winning.)} 10. Bg6+ $3 Kxg6 11. Qxd4 {, White is not winning, as Black has many pieces for the queen, but we have an amazing position.}) 9. Ne5+ Nxe5 $2 {is the most popular and natural move. Black should have played ... Kg8 .} 10. dxe5 Nd5 ({After} 10... Ng4 11. Bg6+ $3 Kxg6 12. Qxd8 {, White is winning, as they are a queen up.}) 11. c4 $1 {Kicking the pony to clear the d-file for a nasty trick.} Nb6 12. Bg6+ $3 { Don't Boo – SPAM THE BRILLIANT EMOTE‼️} Kxg6 13. Qxd8 {with a winning game, as White is a queen up.}) 8... Kg8 9. Bc4+ e6 (9... Kh7 $4 {blunders mate:} 10. Qd3+ g6 11. Qxg6# {.}) 10. O-O ({A very, very difficult to move to make, but imperative to be done. You have to sac the d4 -pawn for lead in development. Holding on the pawn is too slow.} 10. c3 $6 Nc6 11. Ng6 cxd4 12. cxd4 Bb4+ 13. Bd2 Qxd4 {with a win for Black, as everything is hanging for White.}) 10... cxd4 {Too greedy. Black has to develop their queenside ASAP.} 11. Ng6 Nc6 {A very nice move. They know that the rookie on h8 is not as important as the strong pony on g6 . If White takes the rookie, then Black will have two minor pieces and an amazing center.} 12. Re1 {Super duper important moment here. It's IMPERATIVE to understand that we take the rookie on h8 as a LAST resort, as the pony is almost always stronger than the rookie on h8 . In the words of Hikaru: 'And that, my friends, is why the Alien Gambit is a good opening; you end up with a dead rook on the corner very quickly, and it is very, very hard to play.' Black's king is bugged on g8 and the rookie is super duper passive and helps Black's king get mated.} Qe8 {Protecting the e6 -pawn from rookie sacrifices and attacking the pony on g6 ; a very human move.} 13. Nf4 {Super duper strong move. Once again, the pony is stronger than the rookie on h8 , so now all eyes are on the e6 -pawn.} Nd8 14. Qxd4 {And it is a very complex position where Black is a piece up, but their king is weak and lacks development. White is pieced down but has amazing pieces and a lead in development.} ({The game between CM Witty_Alien (2457) vs. sakthi09 (2438), Feb 2, 2025 continued a6} 14. b4 $2 {( Bd2! )} b5 $2 {( Bxb4! )} 15. Bb3 Rb8 16. Bb2 Rb7 {Rad1 . Amazingly, White already has a winning position, thanks to their well-placed pieces. Please note how good the decision was not to take the rookie on h8 . The pony on f4 is big-time stronger than the h8 rookie. Rd7 Qc3 Rxd1 Rxd1 Bd7 Qc7 , Black has no good move. They will lose a piece. Be7 Bxf6 Bxf6 Rxd7 g5 Rxd8!! Bxd8} ({Qxd8 Bxe6+ Kf8} 16... Qf7) 17. Bxe6+ {Kf8 Ng6+!! Qxg6 Qxd8+ Kg7 Qe7+} Qf7 {Qxf7# . It's a perfect game to illustrate how important it is to note that we take on h8 only if it works best for us. After Qe8 , Nf4 was perfect, keeping the tension on the board and playing against the king on g8 and the rookie on h8 .}) *

