o OP, they try to avoid it by playing moves like} 5... Bf5 { , Bg4 or c5 . Do not lose heart; I will teach you how to face those moves. Black is probably like, what the heck!? What is this move? Just kick the pony and gain vital tempi. But here comes...}) 6. Nxf7 {Alieeeeeeeeen Gambiiiiiiiiiiiiiiit!! If you don't scream it, it won't work! :D Obviously, the move is a blunder according to the engine, but practically speaking, this is such a good move for Bullet, Blitz, and even Rapid (judging by rapid results from people). Trust me, guys, I would never preach something that sucks or is really bad. Do not lose heart; the analysis and practical games below will prove how OP the gambit is. I have played the Alien Gambit 1000 games so far. And my win rate is 73%. THIS IS A HUGE WIN RATE!! The Alien Gambit is such an OP gambit if you are willing to learn it. Do you want to have fun? This is the type of stuff you want to play. The purpose of the move is to take a pawn (the critical f7 -pawn) and to disallow the king from castling.} Kxf7 {White has LONG-term positional compensation. When I say LONG term, I mean it. The point for white here is NOT to attack right away, but to develop their kingside and then attack. That is why the Alien Gambit (AG) is so dangerous because your opponent usually laughs at how we play so calmly while being a FULL piece down. Black will forever have weaknesses on the light squares, especially the b1 - h7 diagonal as well as the h5 - e8 diagonal. Also, the e5 -square is critical for White, but we don't jump with the pony right away (this is very important to know) , as we will see. When you play the Alien Gambit, you need to be practical-centered, not engine-centered, as engines just beat the gambit with ease, but we play against humans, and we use the element of surprise to our advantage. Another reason why the gambit is so good is because your opponent is human. They see they are a piece up and will go for the artificial castle defense and then just be a piece up. As we will see, White almost always wins against this defense, if they know what they are doing.} 7. Nf3 {This move is critical. Controlling the e5 -square, postponing the development of the light-squared bishop, and setting up a deadly trap.} (7. Bc4+ $6 {is the most common move by people who have not studied the gambit. A lone bishop can never do anything, and MOST of the time, the light-squared bishop belongs on the d3 -square.} e6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Nd5 ({ IM yoseph2013 (3017) vs. GM Vladimirovich9000 (3134), Jul 27, 2024 continued:} 10... Re8 11. Ne5+ Bxe5 $2 {Everybody plays this. The pony on e5 is very strong, so they want to exchange it. Even Dmitry Andreikin wants to.} (11... Kg8 12. Qf3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 {, and we can see how the bishop belongs on d3 .} ) 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Bxh6 $3 {Sacrifice the bishop to open the king. } gxh6 15. Qg6+ Kf8 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17. Re4 $1 {The rookie joins the attack, and the game is pretty much over despite being two pieces down.} Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf6 19. Rg5+ Kf7 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Rg8# {.}) 11. Ne5+ Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bc7 {, and we can see that the bishop on c4 is hitting the rock on d5 , so it needs to go back to d3 .}) 7... Bf5 {This is a super duper popular move and very human too. The bishop is developed to protect the light squares, and now Black is preparing to go ... e6 . What more can Black ask? All good, but now the bishop has become a target.} 8. Ne5+ {It's imperative to have a change of mindset and go straight for the attack. Black is playing actively with ... Bf5 , so there is just no time for Bd3 , O-O , and Re1 .} Ke8 {An interesting move but not very popular, mainly played by professional players. The idea is not to hide the king on the kingside but rather in the center.} 9. Bc4 {Threatening mate in 1 always feels good. :D} e6 10. g4 {It's imperative to go for the attack right away. If Black is given time to develop, White will be just a piece down. That is what I meant that the bishop will be a target.} Be4 11. f3 Bd5 { The most popular move. I have faced ... Bh7 only by cheaters who got banned afterwards. Maybe in blitz and rapid, ... Bh7 will be found, but in bullet, everyone makes the mistake ... Bd5 , which is good for us. :) The reason why this move is bad is because it leaves the b1 - h7 diagonal undefended, especially the g6 -square.} 12. Qd3 {A very strong move, exploring the weakened light squares. The game between CM Koncheto (2713) vs. IM NurgyulSalimova (2819), Sep 9, 2024, continued:} Bxc4 {The most common move in this position, but it is losing by force.} 13. Qg6+ {White prefers the attack on the king over recapturing the piece on c4 ; also, Black is forced to go out in the open with the king.} Ke7 14. Qf7+ Kd6 15. Nxc4+ (15. Bf4 $2 {was played in the game.} Kd5 $4 {( Be7!⩲ , only engines play this.)} 16. b3 Qa5+ 17. Bd2 Bb4 18. bxc4+ {and White is completely winning. Black's king will either get mated or will follow a huge loss of material.}) 15... Kd5 16. Ne3+ ({A dear friend of mine, Busara5000, showed me this nice move. :) I used to play always } 16. Qxb7 $3 {, but I like this move more as it's forcing, and a brilliant pony sac will occur.}) (16. Qxb7 $3 {Stop it bebe!! Sacrificing the pony while destroying any run-up with the king on the queenside.} Kxc4 17. Qb3+ Kxd4 18. Qd3+ {, Black loses the queen.} Kc5 (18... Ke5 19. f4# {is a beautiful checkmate in the center of the board. Instead, Qxd8?? Bb4+! and Black is winning!! Staying focused till the very end is very important in chess. Qd2 Bxd2+ Bxd2 Kd6–+ and Black is winning because they are ahead in material.}) 19. Qxd8 {.}) 16... Kd6 17. Nf5+ {Stop it bebe! Clearance sacrifice. Never forget that tactics come in a position of strength.} Kd5 (17... exf5 18. Bf4# { is another beautiful central checkmate.}) 18. b3 {Preparing c4 #.} b5 19. Bf4 c5 20. Qb7+ Nc6 21. c4+ bxc4 22. bxc4+ Kxc4 23. Qb3# {The Hobbit-type of journey for the queen it was. :)))} *

