ition on move 10!} b5 {The most popular move, gaining space on the queenside while attacking the bishop on c4 .} 11. Bb3 Be4 12. Bxe6+ Kh7 13. g5 {A beautiful move! Sacrificing the rookie on h1 to decoy the bishop on e4 protecting the critical g6 -square. Remember, the main idea is to checkmate on g6 . By playing this move so so many times, my opponents think the idea is to attack the pony on f6 . So they almost always take the rookie on h1 .} Qe7 {It's imperative for Black to avoid Nf7 with tempi on the queen after ... hxg5 .} 14. Bf7 {A very deadly move and the move I recommend, threating g6 #.} hxg5 15. Qd2 {In the midst of chaos, White has the audacity of hoping to go Qd2 !! What a multifunctional move. I have played this move many times, and NOBODY has found the only move for Black to save themselves. You can try to find it yourself before moving forward. :)} Nbd7 16. Qxg5 g6 (16... Bxh1 17. Qg6# {, Bf3 Qg6# , Nxe5 Qh4+ Nh5 Qxh5# . As we can see, if the queen goes to g5 , Black's king is doomed.}) (16... Qxf7 17. Nxf7 Bxh1 18. Qh4+ Kg8 19. Nxh8 Be4 20. Bg5 {and White is winning, as they are a queen up.}) 17. Bxg6+ Bxg6 18. Qxg6# *

