just be a piece up. As we will see, White almost always wins against this defense, if they know what they are doing.} 7. Nf3 {This move is critical. Controlling the e5 -square, postponing the development of the light-squared bishop, and setting up a deadly trap.} (7. Bc4+ $6 {is the most common move by people who have not studied the gambit. A lone bishop can never do anything, and MOST of the time, the light-squared bishop belongs on the d3 -square.} e6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Nd5 ({ IM yoseph2013 (3017) vs. GM Vladimirovich9000 (3134), Jul 27, 2024 continued:} 10... Re8 11. Ne5+ Bxe5 $2 {Everybody plays this. The pony on e5 is very strong, so they want to exchange it. Even Dmitry Andreikin wants to.} (11... Kg8 12. Qf3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 {, and we can see how the bishop belongs on d3 .} ) 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Bxh6 $3 {Sacrifice the bishop to open the king. } gxh6 15. Qg6+ Kf8 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17. Re4 $1 {The rookie joins the attack, and the game is pretty much over despite being two pieces down.} Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf6 19. Rg5+ Kf7 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Rg8# {.}) 11. Ne5+ Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bc7 {, and we can see that the bishop on c4 is hitting the rock on d5 , so it needs to go back to d3 .}) 7... Bf5 {This is a super duper popular move and very human too. The bishop is developed to protect the light squares, and now Black is preparing to go ... e6 . What more can Black ask? All good, but now the bishop has become a target.} 8. Ne5+ {It's imperative to have a change of mindset and go straight for the attack. Black is playing actively with ... Bf5 , so there is just no time for Bd3 , O-O , and Re1 .} Kg8 9. Bc4+ {A very good move; the bishop cannot go on d3 , as we, being a piece down, should avoid exchanges.} Nd5 {A super duper rare move but interesting. The idea is to block with the pony, and now g4 won't hang e6 .} 10. Qh5 {This is the move I recommend, aiming at the critical f7 ! Learn this move, and you can forget about other alternatives.} Be6 11. Bd3 {A very smart move. The bishop is hitting at a rock on d5 , so it's imperative to switch it to the b1 - h7 diagonal.} Nd7 (11... Nf6 $1 {is a very, very difficult move to make that I have not faced, for the only reason that the pony landed on d5 a few moves back and now has to return. But the queen on h5 is way too strong to be ignored.} 12. Qe2 Qxd4 (12... Nbd7 $4 13. Nxc6 $3 {Beautiful clearance sacrifice. Now the e6 -bishop is under attack.} bxc6 14. Qxe6# {.}) 13. O-O Qc5 {and Black is much better, as they are a piece up and there is no clear plan how White can attack the black king. Instead, Nbd7??} 14. Nf3 $1 Qd6 15. Bf4 $3 Qxf4 16. Qxe6# {.}) 12. Bf5 Bxf5 13. Qf7+ {A very nice move, so you can take on f5 with vital check tempi.} Kh7 14. Qxf5+ Kg8 15. Nxd7 {White is up material and attacking for free.} *

