 gain the vital tempo we need with 8.Ne5 ! I do not recommend this move, but you can play it until ur opponent plays} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {followed by ... Qf5 .}) ({To recap,} 8. Bd3 Bxd3 (8... Bf7 9. Ne5 $1 {White's trick with Bd3 has worked! Now they don't have to worry about ... Bf5 - e4 - h7 and face this very good for White 8...Bf7 . We get a transposition.}) 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {( Nd7?? Qg6# )} 10. Bd2 Qf5 $1 {That's it! Black's queen is perfectly placed on f5 , when White has little compensation.} 11. Qb3 Nd7 12. Qxb7 Qe4+ 13. Be3 Rb8 14. Qxa7 g5 {and Black does not have any problems, like with their kingside development with 8.Ne5 ! The queen on e4 is very strong.}) 8... Be4 9. Bc4 {I consider this move to be the refutation of Black's 8...Be4 . The bishop attacks the e6 -pawn.} (9. f3 Bf5 10. g4 Bh7 11. Bd3 {is a transposition to} Bf5 {g4} 12. Be4 {f3} Bh7 13. Bd3 {.}) 9... Nd7 { As I have said before, this is Black's main plan and a good one. White has to stop it, but it's difficult to do that if Black's bishop stays on the b1 - h7 diagonal.} 10. Qe2 {The critical move, getting out of the d-file (very important so that we don't exchange queens) and attacking the bishop on e4 .} Bf5 (10... Bd5 $4 11. Qh5+ g6 12. Qxg6#) 11. g4 ({Setting up a deadly trap. In the corresponding chapter , we also look at} 11. Bxe6 $1) 11... Bh7 12. Nf7 { Sacrificing the pony to attack the e6 -pawn with mate. If Black doesn't take, they lose material.} *

