 at all costs, and this move does just that. You have no idea how many people miss that the e6 -pawn is indirectly attacked and play Nbd7?} 10. O-O $2 {This move is too slow and does nothing to stop Black's main counterplay with} Nbd7 $1 {and Black has almost no problems. That is why it is imperative to stop ... Nbd7 .} 11. Nxf7 $2 Kxf7 12. Qe2 Nd5 13. Qf3+ N7f6 {and Black is a piece up with no problems.}) 10... Nbd7 ({THE most common move here, and it is a blunder. Black completely misses the point of White's last move. As facts always speak louder than words, I will mention that some very strong players (including 2600+ on chess.com) have played the blunder} 10... Nbd7 $4) 11. Nxf7 Kxf7 12. Qxe6+ Kg6 (12... Ke8 13. Qf7#) 13. Bd3+ Kh5 14. Qh3# {A very, very popular checkmate; I am sure you will get it too.❤} *

