1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 { The Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense, also known as the Capablanca Variation.  4...Bf5 , developing the bishop outside the pawn chain, is a key strategy in the Caro-Kann. This variation presents a solid and highly flexible structure for Black, aiming to withstand White's central pressure while preparing a counterattack. White has several plans to choose from, such as playing Ng3 to attack the bishop on f5 and potentially gain the bishop pair after an exchange. Another plan involves playing Bd3 , offering a trade of bishops and potentially doubling Black's pawns on the f-file. White can also opt for a more aggressive setup with f4 and Nf3 , aiming for a kingside attack. Overall, the Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense is a solid and reliable choice for Black, offering a balanced position with chances for both sides. Popular among players of all levels, from club players to grandmasters, this opening is valued for its flexibility and adaptability. This move was played most notably in Game 2, Vishy Anand vs Magnus Carlsen – 2013 World Chess Championship, which gave Magnus an easy draw with Black (because Vishy didn't play Ng5! :-))} 5. Ng5 {After everything has been said for 4...Bf5 , this move comes with shock to people, and if you know what you are doing, you can win VERY easily. When attacking, never go back! Still preparing to sacrifice on f7 after ... h6 . I am sure after this move, Black is out of home prep.} (5. Ng3 {is THE most popular move, but with good play, Black is doing more than OK.}) 5... Bg6 {The most popular move, at least from personal experience. I get this move most often, as there is no Alien Gambit anymore. Also, it's often pre-moved as everyone plays 5.Ng3 attacking the bishop on f5 . Now Black is ready to kick the pony with ... h6 .} 6. N1f3 h6 {Time to go back on h3 , right? Hmmm...} 7. Ne6 {Martian Gambit!!  I am also the inventor of the Martian Gambit. This is how you beat 4...Bf5 . At first sight, this looks like: uh, duh? What the heck is this move? Excuse me, but your pony is hanging. } ({The first time I played} 7. Ne6 {was on April 15, 2024, against superknight112, and I won. I got so tired of going back to h3 and playing boring chess that I decided to go for romance.❤ But it was accidental. Then I started playing it again and with amazing results. On Jul 7, 2024, I officially named the gambit. It's indeed very special.}) ({The Martian Gambit is} 7. Ne6 $3 {, and it was invented on 7/7/2024. Also, one of my grandmothers, whom I love so much, was born on the 7th of July. 7 is also my favorite digit. Amen.  The idea of this move is to create chaos on the board on just move 7! It weakens the h5 - e8 diagonal, but it allows us to get super duper important tempi with Ne5 's next move, as it attacks the undefended bishop on e6 . The last point of this move is the long, long (when I say long, I mean it) positional advantage of Black's lack of development on the kingside. The g6 -pawn makes it very, very hard for Black to develop their f8 and h8 -pieces. Don't worry, with the examples I will show, you will see what I mean. To summarize, it's better for Black not to have this e6 -pawn. If you remove it, Black is easily winning, as they will go ... e6 and develop their kingside. So the e6 -pawn, after ... fxe6 , is working for us! Isn't that amazing? That's a very important thing to remember.}) 7... fxe6 8. Ne5 {Gaining a vital tempo against the bishop on g6 . After the bishop moves, it will have spent 3 moves in the opening!} (8. Bd3 $6 {is not a good move, but only if Black knows how to counter it because we don't gain the vital tempo we need with 8.Ne5 ! I do not recommend this move, but you can play it until ur opponent plays} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {followed by ... Qf5 .}) ({To recap,} 8. Bd3 Bxd3 (8... Bf7 9. Ne5 $1 {White's trick with Bd3 has worked! Now they don't have to worry about ... Bf5 - e4 - h7 and face this very good for White 8...Bf7 . We get a transposition.}) 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {( Nd7?? Qg6# )} 10. Bd2 Qf5 $1 {That's it! Black's queen is perfectly placed on f5 , when White has little compensation.} 11. Qb3 Nd7 12. Qxb7 Qe4+ 13. Be3 Rb8 14. Qxa7 g5 {and Black does not have any problems, like with their kingside development with 8.Ne5 ! The queen on e4 is very strong.}) 8... Bf7 9. Bc4 {THE critical move. This is the move that will win you thousands of games. This move seems to only threaten Bxe6 !!, but in fact, it stops the most natural move ... Nbd7 (a move which should always be stopped in MG) and many other ideas, as we will see.} (9. Bd3 $5 {Not a bad move, but it's not the move I would recommend. The bishop belongs on the c4 -square against the f7 -bishop. Still, it's a dangerous move. It stops ... Nbd7 and sacrifices the d4 -pawn.} Nd7 $4 (9... Qxd4 $4 10. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 11. Bg6+ $3 {Sacrificing the bishop to clear the attack on Black's queen.} Kxg6 12. Qxd4 {and White is winning, as they are a queen up.}) (9... Nf6 {, now preparing ... Nbd7 .} 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Ng6 {is the plus of 9.Bd3 !? as ... Nbd7 can be met with Ng6 ! But as you will see, in 9.Bc4 we don't allow Black ever to go ... Nbd7 .} Rg8 12. Re1 {with a very nice positional bind. White is doing more than OK. Plans like c4 and d5 will come at the right moment.}) 10. Nxf7 Kxf7 11. Qh5+ Kf6 12. Qg6# {.}) 9... Nf6 {Now, this is the critical moment. Black's last move develops a piece, protects the h5 and g4 -squares, and prepares the move that needs to be stopped at all costs, ... Nbd7 , to exchange our best piece. As White, what would you play to stop that?} 10. Qd3 ( {A very, very strong move. I guarantee you, you can get a winning position against 2600+ FIDE GMs with it coz everyone misses White's main idea of this move. They think White's idea is to go Bxe6 !! and then Qg6 . They see that Nbd7 counters this move and immediately play it. But that is not the point of} 10. Qd3 $1 {The whole idea is the f5 -square!!!! O-O? is too slow and does nothing to stop Black's main counterplay with} Nbd7 $1 {Black has almost no problems. That is why it is imperative to stop ... Nbd7 .} 11. Nxf7 $2 Kxf7 12. Qe2 Nd5 13. Qf3+ N7f6 {and Black is a piece up with no problems.}) 10... Nbd7 ( {THE most natural and common move in this position. But it is a blunder. That is why the Martian Gambit is such an OP gambit. Natural moves lose so fast for Black. Since facts always speak louder than words, I am just going to mention that many people have played this} 10... Nbd7 {blunder, including IMs and 2900+ rated players on chess.com! This is just shocking. I won't be surprised even if Hikaru or King Magnus play this move. :))))}) 11. Nxf7 {As always the case against Bf7 , we take on f7 ONLY if it wins us the game or gives us an advantage.} Kxf7 12. Qf5 {That was the idea behind Qd3! Black is losing; there is no way to protect the e6 -pawn. Isn't this beautiful?! On move 12, we see this position, and Black is lost! This is THE most popular way to win in the Martian Gambit, at least what I have seen from my dear community games in our Martian Gambit channel in discord.} Qb6 (12... g6 13. Qxe6+ Kg7 14. Qf7#) 13. Bxe6+ {It's imperative to take with the bishop so you keep the bind on the kingside and then open the center and checkmate Black's king.} (13. Qxe6+ $4 { is the most common blunder here and the most natural move. Taking with the queen with check and then check on f7 looks very pleasing to the eye, but it misses the whole concept of the Martian Gambit, which states: You ONLY take with the queen on e6 , in this position and others, if you deliver checkmate or win material. Otherwise, you always take with the bishop so you can bind the f8 and h8 -pieces. They can never develop as you have a bishop on e6 − protected by the rookie on e1 and queen on g6 . How is Black gonna ever gonna develop their kingside?} Ke8 14. O-O Kd8 15. Bf4 Nd5 16. Bg3 h5 $1 17. h4 Qxd4 {and Black is completely winning. White has no attack, and they are a piece down.}) 13... Ke8 14. O-O Qb5 15. Qg6+ Kd8 16. Re1 Qh5 17. Qd3 {Of course, White avoids queen exchanges.} Nd5 18. c4 {As you can see, White is ALWAYS keeping Black busy, so they don't develop their kingside and they never manage to. White is completely winning, Black's king is getting mated, and please take notice how, as usual in MG, the bishop on f8 and the rookie on h8 are doing nothing.} *

