{Hello there! :) How are you? Please make sure you have learned the previous chapters before learning this one. It is imperative to know the Alien and Martian Gambits before this. Here, we will learn what to do if Black does NOT play ... h6 to allow AG and MG. As you will see, letting the pony stay on g5 gives White amazing, amazing tactical opportunities.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 {The Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense, also known as the Capablanca Variation. 4...Bf5 , developing the bishop outside the pawn chain, is a key strategy in the Caro-Kann. This variation presents a solid and highly flexible structure for Black, aiming to withstand White's central pressure while preparing a counterattack. White has several plans to choose from, such as playing Ng3 to attack the bishop on f5 and potentially gain the bishop pair after an exchange. Another plan involves playing Bd3 , offering a trade of bishops and potentially doubling Black's pawns on the f-file. White can also opt for a more aggressive setup with f4 and Nf3 , aiming for a kingside attack. Overall, the Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense is a solid and reliable choice for Black, offering a balanced position with chances for both sides. Popular among players of all levels, from club players to grandmasters, this opening is valued for its flexibility and adaptability. This move was played most notably in Game 2, Vishy Anand vs Magnus Carlsen – 2013 World Chess Championship, which gave Magnus an easy draw with Black (because Vishy didn't play Ng5! :-))} 5. Ng5 {After everything has been said for 4...Bf5 , this move comes with shock to people, and if you know what you are doing, you can win VERY easily. When attacking, never go back! Still preparing to sacrifice on f7 after ... h6 . I am sure after this move, Black is out of home prep.} (5. Ng3 { is THE most popular move, but with good play, Black is doing more than OK.}) 5... e6 ({This is not such a rare move, but I face} 5... Bg6 {way more often. The idea is simple. They don't want to go into the Alien Gambit with h6 or Martian Gambit with Bg6 , so they make just a good developing move. After this, with all due respect, boring move, you can never get MG. :((( But behold! You can still get AG. :))) The idea of this is to play boring... I am sorry, I don't like facing this move. Okay, for real, the idea of this move is to play boring. Nothing more to say. They develop their bishop on f8 .}) 6. N1f3 { A very good move. I still have high hopes for an Alien Gambit transposition.} Bd6 7. Nh4 {A very strong move. White can no longer transpose to AG or MG, so they go for the positional advantage, which is the bishop pair.} Nf6 8. Nxf5 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 Qxf5 10. Bd3 Qd5 11. Nf3 {A very difficult move to make but the best one! The lone pony on g5 can't do much so it goes back to protect the d4 -pawn and prepare the strong c4 move!} O-O 12. c4 {White is much, much better as they have the bishop pair and a very strong center.} *

