{If Black defends actively with c5 or Bf5 , you no longer have the time for Bd3 , O-O , and Re1 , but you need to attack right away with Bc4 + followed by Ne5 +. Remember, light squares are critical. My Five Lifelines: A. Develop quickly, usually Bd3 , O-O , and Re1 followed by Ne5 +. B. After development is finished, harass and constantly create threats whenever possible. After Ne5 +, Black goes to g8 with the king, then we should transfer the queen ASAP to the kingside with Qf3 - g3 . C. If Black plays aggressive-looking moves early on, do NOT be patient. It's imperative to push them back right away with tempo. D. Try to play on the kingside and remember the ultimate Alien Gambit attack: queen, bishops, and rookies coming over. E. Do not memorize lines. Focus on ideas, patterns, and common tactics. See the Alien Gambit Intro   on YouTube. } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Ng5 ({This move initializes the Alien Gambit! At least in chess.com! For my dear viewers and me, Alien Gambit starts after h6 , and Nxf7!! So, to state that this move is already bringing us to the Alien Gambit is wrong. Here, you can even transpose to the Martian Gambit if Black plays Bf5} 5. Nf3 {Bg6 Bc4} h6 {and Ne6!! Chess.com told me that the decision is based on the following: if you go Ng5 , you plan to sacrifice, but Black is not forced to go ... h6 , even though 90% of the people play ... h6 . The idea of Ng5 is simple. Play for the Alien Gambit! When you play this move, don't ever think of going back with the pony.}) (5. Nxf6+ {is the most common move and the move I used to play a lot before I invented the Alien Gambit. Korchnoi (or Tartakower) Variation, Black's} exf6 { , is regarded as sounder than gxf6!? , the Bronstein-Larsen Variation, which offers Black rapid development, though also ceding White the superior pawn structure and long-term prospects (Black has to be cautious that the d-pawn is now a potential passed pawn in the endgame).}) ({Since we won't play Nxf6 but hop with the pony on g5 , we stop the lines here.} 5. Ng3 {is a move I played a lot, with bad results after} h5 $1) 5... h6 6. Nxf7 Kxf7 7. Nf3 {Welcome to the Alien Gambit, a gambit that is indeed out of this world! White's main plan is to go Bd3 , O-O , Re1 followed by Ne5 +, and then the critical moment will arrive, which Black usually blunders, as you will learn through this chapter.} *

