o OP, they try to avoid it by playing moves like} 5... Bf5 { , Bg4 or c5 . Do not lose heart; I will teach you how to face those moves. Black is probably like, what the heck!? What is this move? Just kick the pony and gain vital tempi. But here comes...}) 6. Nxf7 {Alieeeeeeeeen Gambiiiiiiiiiiiiiiit!! If you don't scream it, it won't work! :D Obviously, the move is a blunder according to the engine, but practically speaking, this is such a good move for Bullet, Blitz, and even Rapid (judging by rapid results from people). Trust me, guys, I would never preach something that sucks or is really bad. Do not lose heart; the analysis and practical games below will prove how OP the gambit is. I have played the Alien Gambit 1000 games so far. And my win rate is 73%. THIS IS A HUGE WIN RATE!! The Alien Gambit is such an OP gambit if you are willing to learn it. Do you want to have fun? This is the type of stuff you want to play. The purpose of the move is to take a pawn (the critical f7 -pawn) and to disallow the king from castling.} Kxf7 {White has LONG-term positional compensation. When I say LONG term, I mean it. The point for white here is NOT to attack right away, but to develop their kingside and then attack. That is why the Alien Gambit (AG) is so dangerous because your opponent usually laughs at how we play so calmly while being a FULL piece down. Black will forever have weaknesses on the light squares, especially the b1 - h7 diagonal as well as the h5 - e8 diagonal. Also, the e5 -square is critical for White, but we don't jump with the pony right away (this is very important to know) , as we will see. When you play the Alien Gambit, you need to be practical-centered, not engine-centered, as engines just beat the gambit with ease, but we play against humans, and we use the element of surprise to our advantage. Another reason why the gambit is so good is because your opponent is human. They see they are a piece up and will go for the artificial castle defense and then just be a piece up. As we will see, White almost always wins against this defense, if they know what they are doing.} 7. Nf3 {This move is critical. Controlling the e5 -square, postponing the development of the light-squared bishop, and setting up a deadly trap.} (7. Bc4+ $6 {is the most common move by people who have not studied the gambit. A lone bishop can never do anything, and MOST of the time, the light-squared bishop belongs on the d3 -square.} e6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Nd5 ({ IM yoseph2013 (3017) vs. GM Vladimirovich9000 (3134), Jul 27, 2024 continued:} 10... Re8 11. Ne5+ Bxe5 $2 {Everybody plays this. The pony on e5 is very strong, so they want to exchange it. Even Dmitry Andreikin wants to.} (11... Kg8 12. Qf3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 {, and we can see how the bishop belongs on d3 .} ) 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Bxh6 $3 {Sacrifice the bishop to open the king. } gxh6 15. Qg6+ Kf8 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17. Re4 $1 {The rookie joins the attack, and the game is pretty much over despite being two pieces down.} Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf6 19. Rg5+ Kf7 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Rg8# {.}) 11. Ne5+ Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bc7 {, and we can see that the bishop on c4 is hitting the rock on d5 , so it needs to go back to d3 .}) 7... g6 {This is an interesting move. I have won all my games when faced with this move. The idea is to hide the king on g7 and control the f5 -square. Here, White has three good moves I recommend, and they are Bc4+ , Ne5+ , and Bd3 .} 8. Ne5+ ({The aggressive way, immediately going for the attack.} 8. Bc4+ Kg7 9. Ne5 e6 {transposes to 8.Ne5+ first .}) 8... Kg7 9. Bc4 e6 {The game between CM Witty_Alien (2383) vs. GM Gabuzyan_Chessmood (2870), Nov 16, 2023 continued...} (9... c5 $1 {Most of the ... c5 pushes in the Alien Gambit just give Black easy play. The reason this move is super-duper rarely played is because the pawn is already on c6 and the kingside and queenside lack development. After} 10. c3 Nc6 11. Nf7 Qc7 12. Nxh8 Kxh8 {, White has a rookie for two minor pieces, but Black's king is safe, and they have easy play. }) 10. Qd3 Qe8 ({This is the only move not to lose:} 10... Nbd7 $4 11. Qxg6# {. }) 11. Qg3 {A very smart way to transfer the queen to the kingside ( Qd3 - g3 ) .} Nbd7 12. h4 Bd6 {This move is the most natural one. Black completed their kingside development and pins the pony on e5 .} (12... Ne4 $1 {Active defense is usually the best. Black attacks the white queen and prepares ... Nd6 .} 13. Qf4 Nd6 14. Bd3 Nf5 $1 {Those moves are very difficult to make; they are very engine-like. Humans all they think about is how to complete their development. Moves like ... Ne4 - d6 - f5 are not easy to make.} 15. g4 Nxh4 $3 {Brilliant! Sacrificing the pony for the fork on g5 . Exchanges favor Black, as they are a piece up.} 16. Rxh4 g5 {.}) 13. h5 g5 14. Bxg5 {Sacrificing another piece to weaken the king even more.} hxg5 15. Qxg5+ Kf8 16. h6 {The position is dark forest. :) Practically speaking, it's easier to play for White, especially in faster time controls, as there are so many mating threats, and Black's queenside is still yet to be developed.} *

