1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 ({ This is considered the main line of the Caro-Kann Defense and the most popular move.  With} 4... Nf6 {, Black immediately challenges White's central pony, aiming to provoke exchanges that can help simplify the position and alleviate White's early pressure. It's remarkably trendy these days.}) 5. Ng5 ( {This move initializes the Alien Gambit! At least in chess.com! For my dear viewers and me, Alien Gambit starts after h6 , and Nxf7!! So, to state that this move is already bringing us to the Alien Gambit is wrong. Here, you can even transpose to the Martian Gambit if Black plays Bf5} 5. Nf3 {Bg6 Bc4} h6 { and Ne6!! Chess.com told me that the decision is based on the following: if you go Ng5 , you plan to sacrifice, but Black is not forced to go ... h6 , even though 90% of the people play ... h6 . The idea of Ng5 is simple. Play for the Alien Gambit! When you play this move, don't ever think of going back with the pony.}) (5. Nxf6+ {is the most common move and the move I used to play a lot before I invented the Alien Gambit. Korchnoi (or Tartakower) Variation, Black's} exf6 {, is regarded as sounder than gxf6!? , the Bronstein-Larsen Variation, which offers Black rapid development, though also ceding White the superior pawn structure and long-term prospects (Black has to be cautious that the d-pawn is now a potential passed pawn in the endgame).}) ( {Since we won't play Nxf6 but hop with the pony on g5 , we stop the lines here. } 5. Ng3 {is a move I played a lot, with bad results after} h5 $1) 5... h6 ({ This move occurs 85-90% of the time. It used to be more often, but since the Alien Gambit is so OP, they try to avoid it by playing moves like} 5... Bf5 { , Bg4 or c5 . Do not lose heart; I will teach you how to face those moves. Black is probably like, what the heck!? What is this move? Just kick the pony and gain vital tempi. But here comes...}) 6. Nxf7 {Alieeeeeeeeen Gambiiiiiiiiiiiiiiit!! If you don't scream it, it won't work! :D Obviously, the move is a blunder according to the engine, but practically speaking, this is such a good move for Bullet, Blitz, and even Rapid (judging by rapid results from people). Trust me, guys, I would never preach something that sucks or is really bad. Do not lose heart; the analysis and practical games below will prove how OP the gambit is. I have played the Alien Gambit 1000 games so far. And my win rate is 73%. THIS IS A HUGE WIN RATE!! The Alien Gambit is such an OP gambit if you are willing to learn it. Do you want to have fun? This is the type of stuff you want to play. The purpose of the move is to take a pawn (the critical f7 -pawn) and to disallow the king from castling.} Kxf7 {White has LONG-term positional compensation. When I say LONG term, I mean it. The point for white here is NOT to attack right away, but to develop their kingside and then attack. That is why the Alien Gambit (AG) is so dangerous because your opponent usually laughs at how we play so calmly while being a FULL piece down. Black will forever have weaknesses on the light squares, especially the b1 - h7 diagonal as well as the h5 - e8 diagonal. Also, the e5 -square is critical for White, but we don't jump with the pony right away (this is very important to know) , as we will see. When you play the Alien Gambit, you need to be practical-centered, not engine-centered, as engines just beat the gambit with ease, but we play against humans, and we use the element of surprise to our advantage. Another reason why the gambit is so good is because your opponent is human. They see they are a piece up and will go for the artificial castle defense and then just be a piece up. As we will see, White almost always wins against this defense, if they know what they are doing.} 7. Nf3 {This move is critical. Controlling the e5 -square, postponing the development of the light-squared bishop, and setting up a deadly trap.} (7. Bc4+ $6 {is the most common move by people who have not studied the gambit. A lone bishop can never do anything, and MOST of the time, the light-squared bishop belongs on the d3 -square.} e6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Nd5 ({ IM yoseph2013 (3017) vs. GM Vladimirovich9000 (3134), Jul 27, 2024 continued:} 10... Re8 11. Ne5+ Bxe5 $2 {Everybody plays this. The pony on e5 is very strong, so they want to exchange it. Even Dmitry Andreikin wants to.} (11... Kg8 12. Qf3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 {, and we can see how the bishop belongs on d3 .} ) 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Bxh6 $3 {Sacrifice the bishop to open the king. } gxh6 15. Qg6+ Kf8 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17. Re4 $1 {The rookie joins the attack, and the game is pretty much over despite being two pieces down.} Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf6 19. Rg5+ Kf7 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Rg8# {.}) 11. Ne5+ Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bc7 {, and we can see that the bishop on c4 is hitting the rock on d5 , so it needs to go back to d3 .}) 7... Be6 {A very nice move, defending against Bc4 + and with the idea to build up the ... Kg8 and ... Bf7 setup.} 8. Bd3 Kg8 9. O-O Bf7 10. Re1 Nbd7 11. Ne5 {A critical moment for Black here.} Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. e6 Be8 14. Qf3 {A very interesting position. Black is a piece up, but the king is weak, White has a very strong pawn on e6 , and the rook is bugged on h8 .} Qd6 ({The game between CM Witty_Alien (2386) vs. Playchess_VN (2407), Nov 6, 2024, continued:} 14... Nf6 15. Re5 Qc7 16. Bf4 Qb6 17. Rae1 Qxb2 18. g4 $1 {As you can see, White is all in. But all their pieces are active, and Black's king looks so weak.} Qd4 19. c3 Qd8 20. h4 Nd5 21. Bg3 Qb6 $4 (21... g6 $1 {was needed, with idea ... Bg7 ASAP, with chances for both sides.}) 22. Rf5 $1 { The black king is doomed:} Nf6 23. g5 $1 hxg5 24. hxg5 Bh5 25. gxf6 $3 Bxf3 26. f7+ Kh7 27. Rh5# {. What a beautiful, angelic checkmate. Feel free to see the game reaction on YouTube – Brilliant Queen Sacrifice with Alien Gambit .}) 15. c4 Nf6 16. Bf4 Qc5 17. b4 Qxb4 18. Reb1 (18. Rab1 $6 Qa5 {and the rook on e1 is hanging.}) 18... Qa5 19. Rxb7 {With chaos on the board. The engine says it's 0.00, haha. :D} *

