just be a piece up. As we will see, White almost always wins against this defense, if they know what they are doing.} 7. Nf3 {This move is critical. Controlling the e5 -square, postponing the development of the light-squared bishop, and setting up a deadly trap.} (7. Bc4+ $6 {is the most common move by people who have not studied the gambit. A lone bishop can never do anything, and MOST of the time, the light-squared bishop belongs on the d3 -square.} e6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Nd5 ({ IM yoseph2013 (3017) vs. GM Vladimirovich9000 (3134), Jul 27, 2024 continued:} 10... Re8 11. Ne5+ Bxe5 $2 {Everybody plays this. The pony on e5 is very strong, so they want to exchange it. Even Dmitry Andreikin wants to.} (11... Kg8 12. Qf3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 {, and we can see how the bishop belongs on d3 .} ) 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Bxh6 $3 {Sacrifice the bishop to open the king. } gxh6 15. Qg6+ Kf8 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17. Re4 $1 {The rookie joins the attack, and the game is pretty much over despite being two pieces down.} Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf6 19. Rg5+ Kf7 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Rg8# {.}) 11. Ne5+ Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bc7 {, and we can see that the bishop on c4 is hitting the rock on d5 , so it needs to go back to d3 .}) 7... e6 (7... e6 {and Nbd7 are THE most popular moves, as they are the most human ones. Black sees that their king is weak, so their main idea is to make an artificial castle, then develop their pieces and win the game being a piece up. But actually, this is what we are hoping for!}) 8. Bd3 { The right square for the bishop! Aiming at the critical b1 - h7 diagonal.} Nbd7 {Black avoids immediate danger by stopping Ne5 +, but in the long run, the queenside might never develop, as the following examples will show.} 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 {Gaining the critical e5 -square and preparing Ne5 +!} Qc7 {To stop Ne5 . That is a very strong move; I have faced this move rarely, ONLY with people who have looked at the engine.} 11. Qe2 {Supporting the pony jump to e5 .} Re8 12. Ne5+ Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Qh5+ {Usually, if the white queen goes to h5 with check, White is winning.} Kf8 15. c4 {Once again, we see that this move. When perfectly timed, this is so powerful! The pony on d5 is very strong, so we kick it first before sacrificing on h6 .} (15. Bxh6 $3 {This move is good enough too but allows ... Nxe5 , and we don't have Bf4 , as the pony on d5 is controlling that square.} Nxe5 16. Rxe5 gxh6 17. c4 $1 {The only move for White, but a very good one.} (17. Qxh6+ $2 {Again, taking a pawn with check on h6 looks tasty, but it's a mistake, as now the queen joins the defense.} Qg7 $1 18. Qh5 Nf4 {, whose king is weaker now. xD}) 17... Nf6 18. Qxh6+ Qg7 19. Qh4 {, and now we see that the rookie on e5 is not hanging, so Qh4 is very good with a winning attack. For example:} Bd7 20. Rg5 Qf7 {( Qe7} 21. Qh8+ {Kf7 Qg7# ) Bg6 Qe7 Qh8+} Ng8 22. Rg3 $1 {, and there is no defense against Rf3 . White has an easy win.}) 15... Ne7 16. Bxh6 gxh6 17. Qxh6+ Kf7 18. Qf4+ {A very nice check, misplacing the king before the rookie swing.} Kg7 (18... Nf5 19. Bxf5 exf5 20. e6+ Rxe6 21. Qxc7 {is also winning for White.}) 19. Re3 Nf5 20. Bxf5 exf5 21. Rg3+ Kf7 22. Qxf5+ Ke7 23. Rg7+ Kd8 24. Rd1 { Black is either getting mated with Qf6 + or Rxd7 + if the queen moves.} *

