just be a piece up. As we will see, White almost always wins against this defense, if they know what they are doing.} 7. Nf3 {This move is critical. Controlling the e5 -square, postponing the development of the light-squared bishop, and setting up a deadly trap.} (7. Bc4+ $6 {is the most common move by people who have not studied the gambit. A lone bishop can never do anything, and MOST of the time, the light-squared bishop belongs on the d3 -square.} e6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Nd5 ({ IM yoseph2013 (3017) vs. GM Vladimirovich9000 (3134), Jul 27, 2024 continued:} 10... Re8 11. Ne5+ Bxe5 $2 {Everybody plays this. The pony on e5 is very strong, so they want to exchange it. Even Dmitry Andreikin wants to.} (11... Kg8 12. Qf3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 {, and we can see how the bishop belongs on d3 .} ) 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Bxh6 $3 {Sacrifice the bishop to open the king. } gxh6 15. Qg6+ Kf8 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17. Re4 $1 {The rookie joins the attack, and the game is pretty much over despite being two pieces down.} Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf6 19. Rg5+ Kf7 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Rg8# {.}) 11. Ne5+ Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bc7 {, and we can see that the bishop on c4 is hitting the rock on d5 , so it needs to go back to d3 .}) 7... e6 (7... e6 {and Nbd7 are THE most popular moves, as they are the most human ones. Black sees that their king is weak, so their main idea is to make an artificial castle, then develop their pieces and win the game being a piece up. But actually, this is what we are hoping for!}) 8. Bd3 { The right square for the bishop! Aiming at the critical b1 - h7 diagonal.} Nbd7 {Black avoids immediate danger by stopping Ne5 +, but in the long run, the queenside might never develop, as the following examples will show.} 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 {Gaining the critical e5 -square and preparing Ne5 +!} Rf8 {This is a very interesting move, putting the rookie on f8 to play on the f-file rather than e8 to protect the e6 -pawn. Now, in some lines, the queen on f3 (when placed there to transfer on g3 ), can be tactically vulnerable.} 11. Ne5+ Kg8 12. Qf3 {Of course, if they don't take on e5 , we move the queen to f3 right away to transfer it to the kingside.} Bxe5 {The most common move here! The pony on e5 is too strong and, most importantly, too annoying.} (12... Nxe5 $1 { This move has been played only once against me and by a 2700+ FM. I did even win the game. The idea is that the queen on f3 will be hanging after ... Nd7 .} 13. dxe5 Nd7 $1 14. Qg3 Nxe5 $1 (14... Bc5 $2 15. Re2 Qb6 16. Kh1 Bxf2 17. Qg6 Rf7 18. Qh7+ Kf8 19. Bxh6 $3 {Sacrificing the bishop to clean the seventh rank and to clear the f1 -square for the rookie. After} gxh6 20. Qxh6+ Ke8 21. Bg6 { , White is winning, as the f-file is critical, and the pin on f7 is devastating.}) 15. Rxe5 Bxe5 16. Qxe5 Qf6 $1 {, Black is up an exchange, and their king is safe, so they are better.}) 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Qg3 Nc5 15. Bxh6 Qe7 16. Rad1 {Amazing beautiful move! I always played Bf1 in this position, until I analyzed my games and saw the beauty of this move. The idea is to transfer the rookie via d4 - g4 . If Black doesn't take on d3 , we will follow with Bf1 . White is much better despite being a piece down, as they have a lead in development and an easy plan.} Nxd3 17. Rxd3 Rf7 18. Re4 {Since the pony is not on c5 to control the e4 -square, we go Re4 !} (18. Qg6 $2 {The game between CM Witty_Alien (2469) vs. TheKing3050 (2395), Dec 3, 2024, continued:} b6 $2 {( Bd7!= )} 19. Rh3 Bb7 20. Bg5 Qd7 21. Qh7+ Kf8 22. Qh8# {.}) 18... Bd7 19. Rg4 Raf8 20. Bg5 Qc5 21. Bf6 {Amazing multi-functional move, which defends the f2 -pawn and attacks the g7 -pawn.} Nxf6 22. exf6 {White is winning as there is no defense against Rxg7 .} *

