o OP, they try to avoid it by playing moves like} 5... Bf5 { , Bg4 or c5 . Do not lose heart; I will teach you how to face those moves. Black is probably like, what the heck!? What is this move? Just kick the pony and gain vital tempi. But here comes...}) 6. Nxf7 {Alieeeeeeeeen Gambiiiiiiiiiiiiiiit!! If you don't scream it, it won't work! :D Obviously, the move is a blunder according to the engine, but practically speaking, this is such a good move for Bullet, Blitz, and even Rapid (judging by rapid results from people). Trust me, guys, I would never preach something that sucks or is really bad. Do not lose heart; the analysis and practical games below will prove how OP the gambit is. I have played the Alien Gambit 1000 games so far. And my win rate is 73%. THIS IS A HUGE WIN RATE!! The Alien Gambit is such an OP gambit if you are willing to learn it. Do you want to have fun? This is the type of stuff you want to play. The purpose of the move is to take a pawn (the critical f7 -pawn) and to disallow the king from castling.} Kxf7 {White has LONG-term positional compensation. When I say LONG term, I mean it. The point for white here is NOT to attack right away, but to develop their kingside and then attack. That is why the Alien Gambit (AG) is so dangerous because your opponent usually laughs at how we play so calmly while being a FULL piece down. Black will forever have weaknesses on the light squares, especially the b1 - h7 diagonal as well as the h5 - e8 diagonal. Also, the e5 -square is critical for White, but we don't jump with the pony right away (this is very important to know) , as we will see. When you play the Alien Gambit, you need to be practical-centered, not engine-centered, as engines just beat the gambit with ease, but we play against humans, and we use the element of surprise to our advantage. Another reason why the gambit is so good is because your opponent is human. They see they are a piece up and will go for the artificial castle defense and then just be a piece up. As we will see, White almost always wins against this defense, if they know what they are doing.} 7. Nf3 {This move is critical. Controlling the e5 -square, postponing the development of the light-squared bishop, and setting up a deadly trap.} (7. Bc4+ $6 {is the most common move by people who have not studied the gambit. A lone bishop can never do anything, and MOST of the time, the light-squared bishop belongs on the d3 -square.} e6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Nd5 ({ IM yoseph2013 (3017) vs. GM Vladimirovich9000 (3134), Jul 27, 2024 continued:} 10... Re8 11. Ne5+ Bxe5 $2 {Everybody plays this. The pony on e5 is very strong, so they want to exchange it. Even Dmitry Andreikin wants to.} (11... Kg8 12. Qf3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 {, and we can see how the bishop belongs on d3 .} ) 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Bxh6 $3 {Sacrifice the bishop to open the king. } gxh6 15. Qg6+ Kf8 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17. Re4 $1 {The rookie joins the attack, and the game is pretty much over despite being two pieces down.} Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf6 19. Rg5+ Kf7 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Rg8# {.}) 11. Ne5+ Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bc7 {, and we can see that the bishop on c4 is hitting the rock on d5 , so it needs to go back to d3 .}) 7... e6 (7... e6 {and Nbd7 are THE most popular moves, as they are the most human ones. Black sees that their king is weak, so their main idea is to make an artificial castle, then develop their pieces and win the game being a piece up. But actually, this is what we are hoping for!}) 8. Bd3 { The right square for the bishop! Aiming at the critical b1 - h7 diagonal.} Nbd7 {Black avoids immediate danger by stopping Ne5 +, but in the long run, the queenside might never develop, as the following examples will show.} 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 {Gaining the critical e5 -square and preparing Ne5 +!} Re8 {The most human and most popular move. Black sees that White is taking a slow approach, so they follow up with their plan with the artificial castle.} 11. Ne5+ { The critical moment.} Kg8 {It's imperative for Black to leave the pony on e5 and not give the critical h5 -square for the queen.} 12. Qf3 {Super duper strong move! It's time to transfer the queen to the kingside. This move also threatens Bxh6 !! Remember this move. If your pony still resides on e5 , then you transfer the queen to the kingside.} Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 (13... Nh7 $1 { has never been played against me. The most common move here is ... Nd5 . The idea of this move is that after ... Ndf8 , Black is holding on.}) 14. Qg3 { Black's king is found in the crossfire. My experience in this position as White is that Black, 85% of the time, always goes wrong here and loses in a few moves. Practically speaking, it is very difficult to save this for Black. CM Witty_Alien (2310) vs. IM Polina Shuvalova (2739) Dec 9, 2023 continued:} Nf8 15. Bxh6 {The bishop cannot be taken due to the pin with the queen.} Qe7 16. Re4 Qf7 17. Bxg7 {Brilliant! Clearing the g-file.} Qxg7 18. Rg4 Re7 19. c4 Nb4 20. Re1 {White is completely winning, as they will win Black's queen whenever they want.} *

