just be a piece up. As we will see, White almost always wins against this defense, if they know what they are doing.} 7. Nf3 {This move is critical. Controlling the e5 -square, postponing the development of the light-squared bishop, and setting up a deadly trap.} (7. Bc4+ $6 {is the most common move by people who have not studied the gambit. A lone bishop can never do anything, and MOST of the time, the light-squared bishop belongs on the d3 -square.} e6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Nd5 ({ IM yoseph2013 (3017) vs. GM Vladimirovich9000 (3134), Jul 27, 2024 continued:} 10... Re8 11. Ne5+ Bxe5 $2 {Everybody plays this. The pony on e5 is very strong, so they want to exchange it. Even Dmitry Andreikin wants to.} (11... Kg8 12. Qf3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 {, and we can see how the bishop belongs on d3 .} ) 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Bxh6 $3 {Sacrifice the bishop to open the king. } gxh6 15. Qg6+ Kf8 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17. Re4 $1 {The rookie joins the attack, and the game is pretty much over despite being two pieces down.} Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf6 19. Rg5+ Kf7 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Rg8# {.}) 11. Ne5+ Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bc7 {, and we can see that the bishop on c4 is hitting the rock on d5 , so it needs to go back to d3 .}) 7... e6 (7... e6 {and Nbd7 are THE most popular moves, as they are the most human ones. Black sees that their king is weak, so their main idea is to make an artificial castle, then develop their pieces and win the game being a piece up. But actually, this is what we are hoping for!}) 8. Bd3 { The right square for the bishop! Aiming at the critical b1 - h7 diagonal.} Nbd7 {Black avoids immediate danger by stopping Ne5 +, but in the long run, the queenside might never develop, as the following examples will show.} 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 {Gaining the critical e5 -square and preparing Ne5 +!} Re8 {The most human and most popular move. Black sees that White is taking a slow approach, so they follow up with their plan with the artificial castle.} 11. Ne5+ { The critical moment.} Kg8 {It's imperative for Black to leave the pony on e5 and not give the critical h5 -square for the queen.} 12. Qf3 {Super duper strong move! It's time to transfer the queen to the kingside. This move also threatens Bxh6 !! Remember this move. If your pony still resides on e5 , then you transfer the queen to the kingside.} Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 (13... Nh7 $1 { has never been played against me. The most common move here is ... Nd5 . The idea of this move is that after ... Ndf8 , Black is holding on.}) 14. Qg3 { Black's king is found in the crossfire. My experience in this position as White is that Black, 85% of the time, always goes wrong here and loses in a few moves. Practically speaking, it is very difficult to save this for Black.} Kh8 15. Bxh6 {Don't Boo – SPAM THE BRILLIANT EMOTE‼️} gxh6 16. Qg6 Qe7 17. c4 {The whole idea of the sacrifice on h6 – kicking the pony away from the center and gaining the e3 -square for the rookie.} (17. Qxh6+ $2 {Imagine taking a free pawn with check can be a mistake. The queen is no longer attacking the rookie on e8 , and Black will sac one piece back to defend. This just shows how important concentration is in chess. Every move matters.} Kg8 18. Re4 (18. c4 {is played one move too late, and it costs White the game.} Qg7 $1 19. Qh5 Qxg2+ $3 {WOW!!!! Chess is beautiful. Look at this move. Sacrificing the queen so ... Nf4 comes with check! ( Nf4?? Qxe8++– )} 20. Kxg2 Nf4+ 21. Kf1 Nxh5 {and Black is two pieces up with an easy win.}) 18... Qg7 $1 19. Qh5 N7f6 $3 20. exf6 Nxf6 {.}) 17... Nb4 18. Qxh6+ Kg8 19. Re3 Qg7 ( 19... Nxd3 20. Rg3+ Kf7 21. Qg7#) 20. Rg3 {White wins the queen with a winning game, as the black king is very exposed.} Qxg3 21. Qh7+ Kf8 22. fxg3 Nxd3 23. Rf1+ Nf6 24. Rxf6# {After you learn the Alien and Martian Gambits, feel free to check the Other Extraterrestrial Gambits chapter, and you will see this EXACT mate from the Scandinavian and French Defense. I am sure you are already super duper excited. :)} *

