just be a piece up. As we will see, White almost always wins against this defense, if they know what they are doing.} 7. Nf3 {This move is critical. Controlling the e5 -square, postponing the development of the light-squared bishop, and setting up a deadly trap.} (7. Bc4+ $6 {is the most common move by people who have not studied the gambit. A lone bishop can never do anything, and MOST of the time, the light-squared bishop belongs on the d3 -square.} e6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Nd5 ({ IM yoseph2013 (3017) vs. GM Vladimirovich9000 (3134), Jul 27, 2024 continued:} 10... Re8 11. Ne5+ Bxe5 $2 {Everybody plays this. The pony on e5 is very strong, so they want to exchange it. Even Dmitry Andreikin wants to.} (11... Kg8 12. Qf3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 {, and we can see how the bishop belongs on d3 .} ) 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Bxh6 $3 {Sacrifice the bishop to open the king. } gxh6 15. Qg6+ Kf8 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17. Re4 $1 {The rookie joins the attack, and the game is pretty much over despite being two pieces down.} Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf6 19. Rg5+ Kf7 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Rg8# {.}) 11. Ne5+ Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bc7 {, and we can see that the bishop on c4 is hitting the rock on d5 , so it needs to go back to d3 .}) 7... c5 {THE REFUTATION OF THE ALIEN GAMBIT. JUST ON PAPER THO. This is also the RAREST move I have faced too. The reason it's so rare is because it's so counterintuitive. Nobody, absolutely nobody, will play this move if THEY ARE NOT IN HOME PREPERATION!} ({Please think for a second if you are Black before} 7... c5 {. Hmm, I am a piece up. White has only one pawn for it, but my king is weak. I need to play e6 , ... Bd6 , ... Re8 / f8 , and ... Kg8 , then open the game and win as I am a full piece up. Oh, and it's imperative for me not to open the game before I improve my king.}) (7... c5 { does NONE of that though. I remember watching a clip of Hikaru when he was making Alien Gambit arenas and how shocked he was to find out that} 8. dxc5 { is the best move. He always played the} e6 {and ... Nbd7 plan. After thinking for a bit, Hikaru said: 'You know, c5 makes a lot of sense now because you need to develop the knight on c6 rather than d7 .' The reason why c5 is so good is that it frees the c6 -square for the pony and puts pressure on the d4 -pawn, so White doesn't have the time to go Bd3 , O-O , Re1 , and Ne5 +. Black's king is safe, as White's pieces are not developed. I hear people saying: 'Nowadays, we have strong engines that ring the alarm bell when something is not quite kosher. With their help, you can even analyze certain position types until you reach a final verdict. This means the end of an era and the inevitable decline of all incorrect gambits.' This is true and false. True, because the Alien Gambit is NOT recommended for classical chess and Fide Candidates level, it's for club chess, online chess, and romance. :) When we play chess, we play for fun. We are not professionals. If aggressive style is your style, go for it! Have fun! :)}) 8. d5 ({Not the top engine move, but the move I recommend (while switching with} 8. Ne5+ {), and will win you thousand of games, I guarantee you. If I was not practical-chess-centered but rather engine-centered, I would have never invented the Alien Gambit.}) ({This move needs to be switched with} 8. Ne5+ {if you are playing a match with someone, as eventually they will defend with engine analysis. Amazingly enough, the pawn cannot be taken. White has gained space in the center, and the pony cannot be developed on c6 .}) (8. Bd3 $6 {is a very tricky move, but not the one I recommend. The idea is to defend the d4 -pawn with tactics, but it's fragile.} Nc6 (8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 {, White is using tactics.} Qxd4 $4 {( e5–+ and Black controls the center while being a piece up. Therefore, they are winning.)} 10. Bg6+ $3 Kxg6 11. Qxd4 {, White is not winning, as Black has many pieces for the queen, but we have an amazing position.}) 9. Ne5+ Nxe5 $2 { is the most popular and natural move. Black should have played ... Kg8 .} 10. dxe5 Nd5 ({After} 10... Ng4 11. Bg6+ $3 Kxg6 12. Qxd8 {, White is winning, as they are a queen up.}) 11. c4 $1 {Kicking the pony to clear the d-file for a nasty trick.} Nb6 12. Bg6+ $3 {Don't Boo – SPAM THE BRILLIANT EMOTE‼️} Kxg6 13. Qxd8 {with a winning game, as White is a queen up.}) 8... Qxd5 { THE MOST COMMON MOVE AFTER FACING d5 !! FOR THE FIRST TIME!! They play it so easily as they see ... Nxd5 is not working because of c4 , then they see the queen take is working, and they immediately do that, forgetting that their king is on f7 . One of the advantages of the Alien Gambit is that after move 6, your experience and pattern recognition with the Caro-Kann cannot help you. It's just chaos on the board.} 9. Bc4 ({ALIEN GAMBIT SO OP!! The idea is deflection. White deflects the queen to land on c4 , so the forky happens on e5 with the pony. I have a 100% win rate against} 9. Qxd5+ $4 {in the ladder. You will be shocked how many people fall for this.}) {Just like Bg4?? They forget their king is on f7 . I will list some games I have won like this. CM Witty_Alien (2575) vs. Y0urBunnyWrote (2538), Sep 25, 2024 CM Witty_Alien (2489) vs. Adost (2427), Aug 19, 2024  CM Witty_Alien (2488) vs. FM kreonx (2456), Apr 21, 2024 CM Witty_Alien (2228) vs. hackable (2134), Feb 13, 2024} 9... Qxc4 10. Ne5+ Kg8 11. Nxc4 {Queen up, White is winning.} *

