e played ... Kg8 .} 10. dxe5 Nd5 ({After} 10... Ng4 11. Bg6+ $3 Kxg6 12. Qxd8 {, White is winning, as they are a queen up.}) 11. c4 $1 {Kicking the pony to clear the d-file for a nasty trick.} Nb6 12. Bg6+ $3 {Don't Boo – SPAM THE BRILLIANT EMOTE‼️} Kxg6 13. Qxd8 {with a winning game, as White is a queen up.}) 8... Nbd7 9. a4 { A multifunctional move – stopping ... b5 and preparing Ra3 and Bc4 and, of course, stopping ... Nb6 because of a5 .} (9. Bc4 $2 b5 $1 10. Bxb5 {( Bd3} c4 {Bf5 g6 Be6+ Kg7–+ and Black is a piece up. White has failed to create any compensation for that piece.) Qa5} 11. Bd2 {Qxb5-+ . Black is winning, as they are a piece up, and White has no counterplay.}) 9... g5 10. Ra3 g4 11. Nh4 Bg7 12. Re3 Rf8 (12... Nb6 13. c4 e5 {, pure engine move, but a very good move. The idea is to control central squares and open the position for more exchanges to occur if White takes en passant on e6 .}) 13. Bd3 Kg8 14. c4 { White has a moderate advantage despite being a piece down because of the terrible weak light squares and no real way to develop their queenside.} *

