ey are a queen up.}) 11. c4 $1 {Kicking the pony to clear the d-file for a nasty trick.} Nb6 12. Bg6+ $3 { Don't Boo – SPAM THE BRILLIANT EMOTE‼️} Kxg6 13. Qxd8 {with a winning game, as White is a queen up.}) 8... Kg8 9. Bc4+ e6 (9... Kh7 $4 {blunders mate:} 10. Qd3+ g6 11. Qxg6# {.}) 10. O-O ({A very, very difficult to move to make, but imperative to be done. You have to sac the d4 -pawn for lead in development. Holding on the pawn is too slow.} 10. c3 $6 Nc6 11. Ng6 cxd4 12. cxd4 Bb4+ 13. Bd2 Qxd4 {with a win for Black, as everything is hanging for White.}) 10... Nc6 11. Ng6 Qe8 {This move is super-duper rare because it's not very human. Black can capture the pawn on d4 three times yet they attack the pony on g6 with the queen.} ({I have played so many Alien Gambit games and people usually play} 11... cxd4 {and} 12. Qxd4 {. And to be honest,} Qe8 { is a really annoying move, as it forces White to move the pony.}) 12. Nf4 { This is the move I recommend and the best practical choice. Since we are playing the Alien Gambit in bullet and blitz, White has amazing chances. That is why we don't play AG in classical chess, as ... Qe8 is just too strong and forces White to kinda take on h8 . Don't lose heart, my dear friends, Qe8 is almost never played against me. I have faced this move only in viewer arenas whose people have checked with the engine; I never faced this move in the ladder, I believe.} Nxd4 13. a4 {It is imperative to stop ... b5 from Black. Now, there are awesome ideas with Ra3 and swing with the rookie on the kingside.} Bd7 14. c3 Nc6 15. Re1 Nd8 16. Qf3 {We have to play this position. We are a full piece down, but our pieces are very active, and Black still has problems with the king on g8 and the rookie on h8 . This is the truth, my dear friends; if Black defends perfectly as they did in this game, we are a piece down. But once the engine lines are over, they have to play with what they got, and practically speaking, it is very difficult to play with Black here, especially in blitz or bullet.} *

