e} e6 {and ... Nbd7 plan. After thinking for a bit, Hikaru said: 'You know, c5 makes a lot of sense now because you need to develop the knight on c6 rather than d7 .' The reason why c5 is so good is that it frees the c6 -square for the pony and puts pressure on the d4 -pawn, so White doesn't have the time to go Bd3 , O-O , Re1 , and Ne5 +. Black's king is safe, as White's pieces are not developed. I hear people saying: 'Nowadays, we have strong engines that ring the alarm bell when something is not quite kosher. With their help, you can even analyze certain position types until you reach a final verdict. This means the end of an era and the inevitable decline of all incorrect gambits.' This is true and false. True, because the Alien Gambit is NOT recommended for classical chess and Fide Candidates level, it's for club chess, online chess, and romance. :) When we play chess, we play for fun. We are not professionals. If aggressive style is your style, go for it! Have fun! :)}) 8. Ne5+ {A good move, changing gears right away, realizing there is no time for Bd3 , O-O , and Re1 . White has to do something fast.} ({It's imperative for you, dear reader, to learn this line, too, as when your opponent starts defending against} 8. d5 $1 {, you can play yet another amazing move, and top engine one too. This move is good, as Black's last move did not develop a piece, so we try to attack right away.}) ( 8. Bd3 $6 {is a very tricky move, but not the one I recommend. The idea is to defend the d4 -pawn with tactics, but it's fragile.} Nc6 (8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 { , White is using tactics.} Qxd4 $4 {( e5–+ and Black controls the center while being a piece up. Therefore, they are winning.)} 10. Bg6+ $3 Kxg6 11. Qxd4 {, White is not winning, as Black has many pieces for the queen, but we have an amazing position.}) 9. Ne5+ Nxe5 $2 {is the most popular and natural move. Black should have played ... Kg8 .} 10. dxe5 Nd5 ({After} 10... Ng4 11. Bg6+ $3 Kxg6 12. Qxd8 {, White is winning, as they are a queen up.}) 11. c4 $1 {Kicking the pony to clear the d-file for a nasty trick.} Nb6 12. Bg6+ $3 { Don't Boo – SPAM THE BRILLIANT EMOTE‼️} Kxg6 13. Qxd8 {with a winning game, as White is a queen up.}) 8... Kg8 9. Bc4+ e6 (9... Kh7 $4 {blunders mate:} 10. Qd3+ g6 11. Qxg6# {.}) 10. O-O ({A very, very difficult to move to make, but imperative to be done. You have to sac the d4 -pawn for lead in development. Holding on the pawn is too slow.} 10. c3 $6 Nc6 11. Ng6 cxd4 12. cxd4 Bb4+ 13. Bd2 Qxd4 {with a win for Black, as everything is hanging for White.}) 10... Nc6 11. Ng6 Qe8 {This move is super-duper rare because it's not very human. Black can capture the pawn on d4 three times yet they attack the pony on g6 with the queen.} ({I have played so many Alien Gambit games and people usually play} 11... cxd4 {and} 12. Qxd4 {. And to be honest,} Qe8 { is a really annoying move, as it forces White to move the pony.}) 12. Nf4 { This is the move I recommend and the best practical choice. Since we are playing the Alien Gambit in bullet and blitz, White has amazing chances. That is why we don't play AG in classical chess, as ... Qe8 is just too strong and forces White to kinda take on h8 . Don't lose heart, my dear friends, Qe8 is almost never played against me. I have faced this move only in viewer arenas whose people have checked with the engine; I never faced this move in the ladder, I believe.} cxd4 {A very human and natural move but a mistake. The e6 -pawn is now White's main target.} 13. Re1 ({Now we get a transposition to cxd4 } 13. Ng6 {Nc6 Re1 Qe8 .}) *

