e} e6 {and ... Nbd7 plan. After thinking for a bit, Hikaru said: 'You know, c5 makes a lot of sense now because you need to develop the knight on c6 rather than d7 .' The reason why c5 is so good is that it frees the c6 -square for the pony and puts pressure on the d4 -pawn, so White doesn't have the time to go Bd3 , O-O , Re1 , and Ne5 +. Black's king is safe, as White's pieces are not developed. I hear people saying: 'Nowadays, we have strong engines that ring the alarm bell when something is not quite kosher. With their help, you can even analyze certain position types until you reach a final verdict. This means the end of an era and the inevitable decline of all incorrect gambits.' This is true and false. True, because the Alien Gambit is NOT recommended for classical chess and Fide Candidates level, it's for club chess, online chess, and romance. :) When we play chess, we play for fun. We are not professionals. If aggressive style is your style, go for it! Have fun! :)}) 8. Ne5+ {A good move, changing gears right away, realizing there is no time for Bd3 , O-O , and Re1 . White has to do something fast.} ({It's imperative for you, dear reader, to learn this line, too, as when your opponent starts defending against} 8. d5 $1 {, you can play yet another amazing move, and top engine one too. This move is good, as Black's last move did not develop a piece, so we try to attack right away.}) ( 8. Bd3 $6 {is a very tricky move, but not the one I recommend. The idea is to defend the d4 -pawn with tactics, but it's fragile.} Nc6 (8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 { , White is using tactics.} Qxd4 $4 {( e5–+ and Black controls the center while being a piece up. Therefore, they are winning.)} 10. Bg6+ $3 Kxg6 11. Qxd4 {, White is not winning, as Black has many pieces for the queen, but we have an amazing position.}) 9. Ne5+ Nxe5 $2 {is the most popular and natural move. Black should have played ... Kg8 .} 10. dxe5 Nd5 ({After} 10... Ng4 11. Bg6+ $3 Kxg6 12. Qxd8 {, White is winning, as they are a queen up.}) 11. c4 $1 {Kicking the pony to clear the d-file for a nasty trick.} Nb6 12. Bg6+ $3 { Don't Boo – SPAM THE BRILLIANT EMOTE‼️} Kxg6 13. Qxd8 {with a winning game, as White is a queen up.}) 8... Kg8 9. Bc4+ e6 (9... Kh7 $4 {blunders mate:} 10. Qd3+ g6 11. Qxg6# {.}) 10. O-O ({A very, very difficult to move to make, but imperative to be done. You have to sac the d4 -pawn for lead in development. Holding on the pawn is too slow.} 10. c3 $6 Nc6 11. Ng6 cxd4 12. cxd4 Bb4+ 13. Bd2 Qxd4 {with a win for Black, as everything is hanging for White.}) 10... Nc6 11. Ng6 Qxd4 12. Qe2 {It is amazing how White is a full piece down, yet they enjoy amazing coordination with their pieces.} Kh7 (12... Kh7 $2 {is an interesting move, thinking they just force White to take on h8 , and Black will have a winning game, as they will have two minor pieces for the rookie and a very safe king.}) 13. c3 {A fantastic move. The queen on d4 is too strongly placed, so it's time to kick her and use tactics on the b1 - h7 diagonal.} Qe4 14. Nxf8+ Rxf8 15. Bd3 {White wins the queen and the game.} *

