ey are a queen up.}) 11. c4 $1 {Kicking the pony to clear the d-file for a nasty trick.} Nb6 12. Bg6+ $3 { Don't Boo – SPAM THE BRILLIANT EMOTE‼️} Kxg6 13. Qxd8 {with a winning game, as White is a queen up.}) 8... Kg8 9. Bc4+ e6 (9... Kh7 $4 {blunders mate:} 10. Qd3+ g6 11. Qxg6# {.}) 10. O-O ({A very, very difficult to move to make, but imperative to be done. You have to sac the d4 -pawn for lead in development. Holding on the pawn is too slow.} 10. c3 $6 Nc6 11. Ng6 cxd4 12. cxd4 Bb4+ 13. Bd2 Qxd4 {with a win for Black, as everything is hanging for White.}) 10... Nc6 11. Ng6 Qxd4 12. Qe2 {It is amazing how White is a full piece down, yet they enjoy amazing coordination with their pieces.} Nd5 { A super rare move. It has been played once or twice by a full-time home prepper in my daily Alien Gambit arenas. The idea is to block the attack on e6 -pawn and allow the queen to go to f6 .} 13. c3 Qf6 14. Bd3 Bd6 15. Rd1 Bd7 16. Bc2 Re8 17. Qe4 {With chaos on the board. As a last resort, White will take the rookie on h8 and will have a rookie for two minor pieces.} *

