ey are a queen up.}) 11. c4 $1 {Kicking the pony to clear the d-file for a nasty trick.} Nb6 12. Bg6+ $3 { Don't Boo – SPAM THE BRILLIANT EMOTE‼️} Kxg6 13. Qxd8 {with a winning game, as White is a queen up.}) 8... Kg8 9. Bc4+ e6 (9... Kh7 $4 {blunders mate:} 10. Qd3+ g6 11. Qxg6# {.}) 10. O-O ({A very, very difficult to move to make, but imperative to be done. You have to sac the d4 -pawn for lead in development. Holding on the pawn is too slow.} 10. c3 $6 Nc6 11. Ng6 cxd4 12. cxd4 Bb4+ 13. Bd2 Qxd4 {with a win for Black, as everything is hanging for White.}) 10... Nc6 11. Ng6 Qxd4 12. Qe2 {It is amazing how White is a full piece down, yet they enjoy amazing coordination with their pieces.} Qe4 13. Qxe4 {Wow! What are you teaching?! White is a full piece down and is exchanging queens. This is good for White? Yes, it is! White's pieces are so active and will gain tempi against Black's pony on e4 .} Nxe4 14. Bf4 {A very good move, stopping ... Nd6 .} (14. Re1 $5 {is not a bad move, but I like Bf4 more, which gives more chances for Black to go wrong. CM Witty_Alien (2463) vs. IM Alex_Banzea (2653), Dec 26, 2023, continued:} Nf6 15. Bf4 Ne7 $2 16. Nxh8 Kxh8 17. Bxe6 Bxe6 18. Rxe6 Ned5 19. Be5 Kg8 20. c4 {with chances for both sides. Black has two minor pieces for a rookie, but White is very active, and most importantly, the d5 -square is controlled by the pawn on c4 .}) 14... Nd6 15. Bxd6 Bxd6 16. Rae1 {You might say: uh duh? What the heck is this move? Why not the other rook, so this rook goes to d1 in the future? Good question.} (16. Rfe1 $6 Be7 17. f4 Bf6 18. f5 b5 $1 {Beautiful move, deflecting the bishop from attacking e6 , and now ... Nd4 would come with vital tempi.} 19. Bxb5 Nd4 $1 {Now we can see that the rook should be on f1 to protect the f5 -pawn.} 20. Bd3 Nxf5 21. Nxh8 Kxh8 22. Bxf5 exf5 23. Re8+ Kh7 {and Black is winning. The two bishops are stronger than the rookie in this position.}) 16... Nd8 (16... Bd7 $4 17. Rd1 $1 {wins a bishop and the game, as the 