1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 ({ This is considered the main line of the Caro-Kann Defense and the most popular move.  With} 4... Nf6 {, Black immediately challenges White's central pony, aiming to provoke exchanges that can help simplify the position and alleviate White's early pressure. It's remarkably trendy these days.}) 5. Ng5 ( {This move initializes the Alien Gambit! At least in chess.com! For my dear viewers and me, Alien Gambit starts after h6 , and Nxf7!! So, to state that this move is already bringing us to the Alien Gambit is wrong. Here, you can even transpose to the Martian Gambit if Black plays Bf5} 5. Nf3 {Bg6 Bc4} h6 { and Ne6!! Chess.com told me that the decision is based on the following: if you go Ng5 , you plan to sacrifice, but Black is not forced to go ... h6 , even though 90% of the people play ... h6 . The idea of Ng5 is simple. Play for the Alien Gambit! When you play this move, don't ever think of going back with the pony.}) (5. Nxf6+ {is the most common move and the move I used to play a lot before I invented the Alien Gambit. Korchnoi (or Tartakower) Variation, Black's} exf6 {, is regarded as sounder than gxf6!? , the Bronstein-Larsen Variation, which offers Black rapid development, though also ceding White the superior pawn structure and long-term prospects (Black has to be cautious that the d-pawn is now a potential passed pawn in the endgame).}) ( {Since we won't play Nxf6 but hop with the pony on g5 , we stop the lines here. } 5. Ng3 {is a move I played a lot, with bad results after} h5 $1) 5... h6 ({ This move occurs 85-90% of the time. It used to be more often, but since the Alien Gambit is so OP, they try to avoid it by playing moves like} 5... Bf5 { , Bg4 or c5 . Do not lose heart; I will teach you how to face those moves. Black is probably like, what the heck!? What is this move? Just kick the pony and gain vital tempi. But here comes...}) 6. Nxf7 {Alieeeeeeeeen Gambiiiiiiiiiiiiiiit!! If you don't scream it, it won't work! :D Obviously, the move is a blunder according to the engine, but practically speaking, this is such a good move for Bullet, Blitz, and even Rapid (judging by rapid results from people). Trust me, guys, I would never preach something that sucks or is really bad. Do not lose heart; the analysis and practical games below will prove how OP the gambit is. I have played the Alien Gambit 1000 games so far. And my win rate is 73%. THIS IS A HUGE WIN RATE!! The Alien Gambit is such an OP gambit if you are willing to learn it. Do you want to have fun? This is the type of stuff you want to play. The purpose of the move is to take a pawn (the critical f7 -pawn) and to disallow the king from castling.} Kxf7 {White has LONG-term positional compensation. When I say LONG term, I mean it. The point for white here is NOT to attack right away, but to develop their kingside and then attack. That is why the Alien Gambit (AG) is so dangerous because your opponent usually laughs at how we play so calmly while being a FULL piece down. Black will forever have weaknesses on the light squares, especially the b1 - h7 diagonal as well as the h5 - e8 diagonal. Also, the e5 -square is critical for White, but we don't jump with the pony right away (this is very important to know) , as we will see. When you play the Alien Gambit, you need to be practical-centered, not engine-centered, as engines just beat the gambit with ease, but we play against humans, and we use the element of surprise to our advantage. Another reason why the gambit is so good is because your opponent is human. They see they are a piece up and will go for the artificial castle defense and then just be a piece up. As we will see, White almost always wins against this defense, if they know what they are doing.} 7. Nf3 {This move is critical. Controlling the e5 -square, postponing the development of the light-squared bishop, and setting up a deadly trap.} (7. Bc4+ $6 {is the most common move by people who have not studied the gambit. A lone bishop can never do anything, and MOST of the time, the light-squared bishop belongs on the d3 -square.} e6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Nd5 ({ IM yoseph2013 (3017) vs. GM Vladimirovich9000 (3134), Jul 27, 2024 continued:} 10... Re8 11. Ne5+ Bxe5 $2 {Everybody plays this. The pony on e5 is very strong, so they want to exchange it. Even Dmitry Andreikin wants to.} (11... Kg8 12. Qf3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 {, and we can see how the bishop belongs on d3 .} ) 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Bxh6 $3 {Sacrifice the bishop to open the king. } gxh6 15. Qg6+ Kf8 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17. Re4 $1 {The rookie joins the attack, and the game is pretty much over despite being two pieces down.} Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf6 19. Rg5+ Kf7 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Rg8# {.}) 11. Ne5+ Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bc7 {, and we can see that the bishop on c4 is hitting the rock on d5 , so it needs to go back to d3 .}) 7... Bf5 {This is a super duper popular move and very human too. The bishop is developed to protect the light squares, and now Black is preparing to go ... e6 . What more can Black ask? All good, but now the bishop has become a target.} 8. Ne5+ {It's imperative to have a change of mindset and go straight for the attack. Black is playing actively with ... Bf5 , so there is just no time for Bd3 , O-O , and Re1 .} Ke8 {An interesting move but not very popular, mainly played by professional players. The idea is not to hide the king on the kingside but rather in the center.} 9. Bc4 {Threatening mate in 1 always feels good. :D} e6 10. g4 {It's imperative to go for the attack right away. If Black is given time to develop, White will be just a piece down. That is what I meant that the bishop will be a target.} Be4 11. f3 Bd5 { The most popular move. I have faced ... Bh7 only by cheaters who got banned afterwards. Maybe in blitz and rapid, ... Bh7 will be found, but in bullet, everyone makes the mistake ... Bd5 , which is good for us. :) The reason why this move is bad is because it leaves the b1 - h7 diagonal undefended, especially the g6 -square.} 12. Qd3 {A very strong move, exploring the weakened light squares. The game between CM Koncheto (2713) vs. IM NurgyulSalimova (2819), Sep 9, 2024, continued:} Qe7 {The idea of this move is to allow the king to hide on d8 rather than e7 when the check on g6 comes.} 13. Qg6+ Kd8 {Witty_Alien (2241) vs. GM gurelediz (3201) Aug 9, 2024.  followed:} 14. Nf7+ {A weak move because the pony was much stronger on e5 than f7 , and we can't take on h8 , as the bishop on c4 would be hanging. You might say: but we win a rookie for a bishop! What are you talking about? Do not lose heart. We are already a piece down, so Black will have two minor pieces for a rookie with an easily winning game.} Kc8 15. Bxd5 ({After} 15. Nxh8 $2 Qb4+ $1 16. c3 Qxc4 {, Black has two minor pieces for a rookie with a winning position.}) 15... exd5+ 16. Kf2 Rg8 17. Re1 Qd7 (17... Qc7 $1 {was the ONLY move for Black. The difference is that that queen cannot be attacked in some lines with Ne5 , and the d7 -square is free for the pony.}) 18. Ne5 (18. Bf4) 18... Qe8 19. Qf5+ Nbd7 20. Bf4 (20. Ng6 $1 {attacks the queen and prepares Re6 with a very strong positional bind:} Qd8 21. Re6 {.}) 20... g6 21. Nxd7 Qxd7 (21... gxf5 22. Nxf6 Qd8 23. Nxg8 fxg4 24. Re6 {with a mess, but Black is better, as they are up material. White's pieces are not that coordinated but still, I would love to play with White here.}) 22. Qxf6 Bg7 23. Qe6 (23. Qxg6 $4 {is a bad blunder in a winning position. This was played in the game but just blunders the queen:} Bxd4+ $1 {0-1. :(}) 23... Bxd4+ 24. Kg2 Qxe6 25. Rxe6 Kd7 26. Rae1 {With a winning game; even if the material is even, Black will drop material.} Rae8 27. Rd6+ Kc8 28. Rxg6 {Stop it bebe. What a beautiful tactic. If Black takes one of White's rookies, the other will be left undefended.} Rxe1 ({After } 28... Rxg6 29. Rxe8+ Kd7 30. Rb8 {, White is a pawn up and more active.}) 29. Rxg8+ Kd7 30. c3 Bb6 31. Rg7+ Kd8 32. Bxh6 {The three kingside passers will decide the game in White's favor.} *

