osition. Even if the material is even, Black will drop material. For example,} Rae8 27. Rd6+ Kc8 28. Rxg6 $3 {Stop it bebe. What a beautiful tactic. If Black takes one of White's rookies, the other will be left undefended.} Rxe1 (28... Rxg6 29. Rxe8+ Kd7 30. Rb8 {White is a pawn up and more active.}) 29. Rxg8+ Kd7 30. c3 Bb6 31. Rg7+ Kd8 32. Bxh6 {and the three kingside passers will decide the game in White's favor.}) 14... exd5 15. O-O {White is much better after having exchanged Black's best piece on d5 and will use the e-file to win the game.} Kc7 16. Bf4 Kb6 17. Rfe1 Nbd7 18. Nf7 {White wins material, and Black's king is very weak, so White is easily winning.} *

