less, as the bishop controls the b1 - h7 diagonal, but behold! You are going to witness one of the most beautiful brilliants ever!} 11. Qf7+ Kh7 12. Bxh6 {Stop This Guy From Brillianting‼ What a beautiful move! At first glance, it looks like White does not have anything, but the more you look, the more brilliants you will see. The idea is to remove the defender of the king on the h-file and, most importantly, allow Rc1 !!!!!!!! Aaaaaa, this was the main idea aaaaa.} (12. Kd2 $4 Nb4) 12... Kxh6 13. g4 {Threatening mate in 1.} Kh7 (13... g6 14. g5+ Kxg5 15. Rg1+ Kh5 16. Be2+ Kh4 {( Kh6} 17. Rxg6 Bxg6 18. Qxg6 {) Rg4+} Kh3 {Qf3+ Kxh2 Kh5 Re4+ , a very nice move; now g6 would be mate. Kh6 ( Kg5 Qxg6# ) Qxg6# .} 19. Qg2+ {.}) 14. Rc1 {A perfect move. Now, the bishop has to move, as ... Nb4 is followed by Qh5 #.} Nd7 {Black is two pieces up, so they can give one back and hope to not get mated.} 15. Rxc2 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qa5+ 17. Rc3 {Self-pinning for immortality.} Nf4 ({Stopping Bd3 +, as} 17... Nxc3 18. Qh5# {.}) 18. Qxf4 g6 { Black finally managed to free their king, but not for long.} 19. Ke2 Bh6 20. Qf7+ Bg7 21. Rh3# {One of the most beautiful lines I have ever seen in chess. It was an honor to take you with me enjoying those lines.} *

