less, as the bishop controls the b1 - h7 diagonal, but behold! You are going to witness one of the most beautiful brilliants ever!} 11. Qf7+ Kh7 12. Bxh6 {Stop This Guy From Brillianting‼ What a beautiful move! At first glance, it looks like White does not have anything, but the more you look, the more brilliants you will see. The idea is to remove the defender of the king on the h-file and, most importantly, allow Rc1 !!!!!!!! Aaaaaa, this was the main idea aaaaa.} (12. Kd2 $4 Nb4) 12... Kxh6 13. g4 {Threatening mate in 1.} Kh7 (13... g6 14. g5+ Kxg5 15. Rg1+ Kh5 16. Be2+ Kh4 {( Kh6} 17. Rxg6 Bxg6 18. Qxg6 {) Rg4+} Kh3 {Qf3+ Kxh2 Kh5 Re4+ , a very nice move; now g6 would be mate. Kh6 ( Kg5 Qxg6# ) Qxg6# .} 19. Qg2+ {.}) 14. Rc1 {A perfect move. Now, the bishop has to move, as ... Nb4 is followed by Qh5 #.} Be4 15. Rc3 {BRILLIANT!!! What a beautiful move!! Sacrifice of BOTH rookies! 'I like to sacrifice so many pieces that my opponent can only take one per move.' – Mikhail Tal} Nxc3 (15... Bg2 16. Bd3+ Kh6 17. Qg6# {, and if Bxh1 Rh3# .}) (15... Qa5 16. Rg1 $3 {Stop it bebeee!!! The idea is simple! Rg3 - h3 mate! Black cannot do anything to stop it!! This is viral!!!} e6 17. Rgg3 $3 Nxc3 18. Rh3# {. Welcome to the Alien Gambit. You just made 4 brilliant moves!!}) 16. Qh5# {White is two minor pieces and one rookie down, but checkmates end the game! What a beautiful game chess is, indeed!} *

