ition on move 10!} b5 {The most popular move, gaining space on the queenside while attacking the bishop on c4 .} 11. Bb3 Be4 12. Bxe6+ Kh7 13. g5 {A beautiful move! Sacrificing the rookie on h1 to decoy the bishop on e4 protecting the critical g6 -square. Remember, the main idea is to checkmate on g6 . By playing this move so so many times, my opponents think the idea is to attack the pony on f6 . So they almost always take the rookie on h1 .} hxg5 {Blunder, but a very popular one. Many players play this (especially titled players) and forget that Nf7 just wins the game now.} 14. Nf7 {The freaky-deeky forky is way too strong. Now, the idea is not to take the rookie after the queen moves but to take on g5 with check, as the king cannot go back on g8 due to the bishop on e6 .} Qe7 15. Nxg5+ Kg6 16. Rg1 Rxh2 (16... Rh4 17. Nxe4+ Kh7 18. Nxf6+ Qxf6 19. Qe2 {with a winning game because White is not only ahead in material but Black's king is so weak, and Bg5 is threatened.}) 17. Nxe4+ Kh7 18. Ng5+ Kg6 19. Qd3+ ({With mate to follow. After Kh5 , an amusing and strong move is Kd1 , getting out of the pin and preparing B / Nf7 . Nbd7} 19. Nf7+ {Qxe6 Rg5+ Kh4 Qg3# .}) *

