ition on move 10!} b5 {The most popular move, gaining space on the queenside while attacking the bishop on c4 .} 11. Bb3 Be4 12. Bxe6+ Kh7 13. g5 {A beautiful move! Sacrificing the rookie on h1 to decoy the bishop on e4 protecting the critical g6 -square. Remember, the main idea is to checkmate on g6 . By playing this move so so many times, my opponents think the idea is to attack the pony on f6 . So they almost always take the rookie on h1 .} g6 {A rare move; the idea is to stop g6 # and is renewing the threat of ... Bxh1 .} 14. O-O {Fantastic move, defending the rookie and the king in just 1 move!} Qe7 15. Bb3 Nd5 16. Re1 {The rookie on e1 is very strong. Black's pieces on the e-file are hanging.} Bf5 17. Nxg6 { BRILLIANT! This move clears the attack on the queen on e7 with the rookie.} Bxg6 18. Rxe7+ Bxe7 19. Qe2 {A very strong move, threatening Bxd5 followed by Qxe7 .} (19. gxh6 $4 {Amazingly enough, the most natural move is a blunder. It opens the critical g-file, and suddenly, White's king is weaker than Black's!} Rg8 $1 {Black is better despite being material down. The white king is too weak, and Black's queenside is easily developed.}) 19... Re8 20. Bxd5 cxd5 21. Qxb5 {White is a queen up with a winning game.} *

