ition on move 10!} b5 {The most popular move, gaining space on the queenside while attacking the bishop on c4 .} 11. Bb3 Be4 12. Bxe6+ Kh7 13. g5 {A beautiful move! Sacrificing the rookie on h1 to decoy the bishop on e4 protecting the critical g6 -square. Remember, the main idea is to checkmate on g6 . By playing this move so so many times, my opponents think the idea is to attack the pony on f6 . So they almost always take the rookie on h1 .} Qe7 {It's imperative for Black to avoid Nf7 with tempi on the queen after ... hxg5 .} 14. Bf7 {A very deadly move and the move I recommend, threating g6 #.} hxg5 15. Qd2 {In the midst of chaos, White has the audacity of hoping to go Qd2 !! What a multifunctional move. I have played this move many times, and NOBODY has found the only move for Black to save themselves. You can try to find it yourself before moving forward. :)} Nfd7 { THE only move for Black to stay in the game and even be better. 'Better' is very relative, as in positions where 2+2=5, there is no such thing as 'better'. The queen protects the g5 -pawn, but most importantly, the pony challenges the pony on e5 .} 16. Qe2 g6 (16... Nf6 $4 17. Qe3 $1 {Beautiful staircase in chess. Again, Qh3 is threatened now.} Nfd7 18. Qh3# {, checkmates end the game. What a mindblowing reveal I just did. :)}) 17. Qxe4 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Qxf7 19. Bxg5 Be7 {This move is very common but is a blunder, as the queenside remains undeveloped.} 20. e6 Qe8 21. Bxe7 Qxe7 22. O-O-O {White is winning easily, as Black can never develop – Rd7 comes in.} *

