o OP, they try to avoid it by playing moves like} 5... Bf5 { , Bg4 or c5 . Do not lose heart; I will teach you how to face those moves. Black is probably like, what the heck!? What is this move? Just kick the pony and gain vital tempi. But here comes...}) 6. Nxf7 {Alieeeeeeeeen Gambiiiiiiiiiiiiiiit!! If you don't scream it, it won't work! :D Obviously, the move is a blunder according to the engine, but practically speaking, this is such a good move for Bullet, Blitz, and even Rapid (judging by rapid results from people). Trust me, guys, I would never preach something that sucks or is really bad. Do not lose heart; the analysis and practical games below will prove how OP the gambit is. I have played the Alien Gambit 1000 games so far. And my win rate is 73%. THIS IS A HUGE WIN RATE!! The Alien Gambit is such an OP gambit if you are willing to learn it. Do you want to have fun? This is the type of stuff you want to play. The purpose of the move is to take a pawn (the critical f7 -pawn) and to disallow the king from castling.} Kxf7 {White has LONG-term positional compensation. When I say LONG term, I mean it. The point for white here is NOT to attack right away, but to develop their kingside and then attack. That is why the Alien Gambit (AG) is so dangerous because your opponent usually laughs at how we play so calmly while being a FULL piece down. Black will forever have weaknesses on the light squares, especially the b1 - h7 diagonal as well as the h5 - e8 diagonal. Also, the e5 -square is critical for White, but we don't jump with the pony right away (this is very important to know) , as we will see. When you play the Alien Gambit, you need to be practical-centered, not engine-centered, as engines just beat the gambit with ease, but we play against humans, and we use the element of surprise to our advantage. Another reason why the gambit is so good is because your opponent is human. They see they are a piece up and will go for the artificial castle defense and then just be a piece up. As we will see, White almost always wins against this defense, if they know what they are doing.} 7. Nf3 {This move is critical. Controlling the e5 -square, postponing the development of the light-squared bishop, and setting up a deadly trap.} (7. Bc4+ $6 {is the most common move by people who have not studied the gambit. A lone bishop can never do anything, and MOST of the time, the light-squared bishop belongs on the d3 -square.} e6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Nd5 ({ IM yoseph2013 (3017) vs. GM Vladimirovich9000 (3134), Jul 27, 2024 continued:} 10... Re8 11. Ne5+ Bxe5 $2 {Everybody plays this. The pony on e5 is very strong, so they want to exchange it. Even Dmitry Andreikin wants to.} (11... Kg8 12. Qf3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 {, and we can see how the bishop belongs on d3 .} ) 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Bxh6 $3 {Sacrifice the bishop to open the king. } gxh6 15. Qg6+ Kf8 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17. Re4 $1 {The rookie joins the attack, and the game is pretty much over despite being two pieces down.} Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf6 19. Rg5+ Kf7 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Rg8# {.}) 11. Ne5+ Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bc7 {, and we can see that the bishop on c4 is hitting the rock on d5 , so it needs to go back to d3 .}) 7... Bf5 {This is a super duper popular move and very human too. The bishop is developed to protect the light squares, and now Black is preparing to go ... e6 . What more can Black ask? All good, but now the bishop has become a target.} 8. Ne5+ {It's imperative to have a change of mindset and go straight for the attack. Black is playing actively with ... Bf5 , so there is just no time for Bd3 , O-O , and Re1 .} Kg8 9. Bc4+ {A very good move; the bishop cannot go on d3 , as we, being a piece down, should avoid exchanges.} e6 10. g4 {The only move to stay in the game but very strong. The idea is to remove the defender of the e6 -pawn. With three forcing moves, White has created chaos on the board, and trust me, when you play the Caro-Kann as Black, you don't want to face this position on move 10!} b5 {The most popular move, gaining space on the queenside while attacking the bishop on c4 .} 11. Bb3 Be4 12. Bxe6+ Kh7 13. g5 {A beautiful move! Sacrificing the rookie on h1 to decoy the bishop on e4 protecting the critical g6 -square. Remember, the main idea is to checkmate on g6 . By playing this move so so many times, my opponents think the idea is to attack the pony on f6 . So they almost always take the rookie on h1 .} Qe7 {It's imperative for Black to avoid Nf7 with tempi on the queen after ... hxg5 .} 14. Bf7 {A very deadly move and the move I recommend, threating g6 #.} hxg5 15. Qd2 {In the midst of chaos, White has the audacity of hoping to go Qd2 !! What a multifunctional move. I have played this move many times, and NOBODY has found the only move for Black to save themselves. You can try to find it yourself before moving forward. :)} Nfd7 { THE only move for Black to stay in the game and even be better. 'Better' is very relative, as in positions where 2+2=5, there is no such thing as 'better'. The queen protects the g5 -pawn, but most importantly, the pony challenges the pony on e5 .} 16. Qe2 g6 (16... Nf6 $4 17. Qe3 $1 {Beautiful staircase in chess. Again, Qh3 is threatened now.} Nfd7 18. Qh3# {, checkmates end the game. What a mindblowing reveal I just did. :)}) 17. Qxe4 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Qxf7 19. Bxg5 Bh6 {This move is very human, as exchanges favor Black since they are a piece up. But the lack of devlopment on the queenside and the weak king is too much for Black to handle at once.} 20. Bxh6 Kxh6 21. O-O-O Na6 22. Rhg1 Rhg8 23. Qe3+ Kg7 24. e6 {White is completely winning. The rookie is coming to d7 with mate to follow, or Black loses the queen.} *

