o OP, they try to avoid it by playing moves like} 5... Bf5 { , Bg4 or c5 . Do not lose heart; I will teach you how to face those moves. Black is probably like, what the heck!? What is this move? Just kick the pony and gain vital tempi. But here comes...}) 6. Nxf7 {Alieeeeeeeeen Gambiiiiiiiiiiiiiiit!! If you don't scream it, it won't work! :D Obviously, the move is a blunder according to the engine, but practically speaking, this is such a good move for Bullet, Blitz, and even Rapid (judging by rapid results from people). Trust me, guys, I would never preach something that sucks or is really bad. Do not lose heart; the analysis and practical games below will prove how OP the gambit is. I have played the Alien Gambit 1000 games so far. And my win rate is 73%. THIS IS A HUGE WIN RATE!! The Alien Gambit is such an OP gambit if you are willing to learn it. Do you want to have fun? This is the type of stuff you want to play. The purpose of the move is to take a pawn (the critical f7 -pawn) and to disallow the king from castling.} Kxf7 {White has LONG-term positional compensation. When I say LONG term, I mean it. The point for white here is NOT to attack right away, but to develop their kingside and then attack. That is why the Alien Gambit (AG) is so dangerous because your opponent usually laughs at how we play so calmly while being a FULL piece down. Black will forever have weaknesses on the light squares, especially the b1 - h7 diagonal as well as the h5 - e8 diagonal. Also, the e5 -square is critical for White, but we don't jump with the pony right away (this is very important to know) , as we will see. When you play the Alien Gambit, you need to be practical-centered, not engine-centered, as engines just beat the gambit with ease, but we play against humans, and we use the element of surprise to our advantage. Another reason why the gambit is so good is because your opponent is human. They see they are a piece up and will go for the artificial castle defense and then just be a piece up. As we will see, White almost always wins against this defense, if they know what they are doing.} 7. Nf3 {This move is critical. Controlling the e5 -square, postponing the development of the light-squared bishop, and setting up a deadly trap.} (7. Bc4+ $6 {is the most common move by people who have not studied the gambit. A lone bishop can never do anything, and MOST of the time, the light-squared bishop belongs on the d3 -square.} e6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Nd5 ({ IM yoseph2013 (3017) vs. GM Vladimirovich9000 (3134), Jul 27, 2024 continued:} 10... Re8 11. Ne5+ Bxe5 $2 {Everybody plays this. The pony on e5 is very strong, so they want to exchange it. Even Dmitry Andreikin wants to.} (11... Kg8 12. Qf3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 {, and we can see how the bishop belongs on d3 .} ) 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Bxh6 $3 {Sacrifice the bishop to open the king. } gxh6 15. Qg6+ Kf8 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17. Re4 $1 {The rookie joins the attack, and the game is pretty much over despite being two pieces down.} Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf6 19. Rg5+ Kf7 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Rg8# {.}) 11. Ne5+ Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bc7 {, and we can see that the bishop on c4 is hitting the rock on d5 , so it needs to go back to d3 .}) 7... Bf5 {This is a super duper popular move and very human too. The bishop is developed to protect the light squares, and now Black is preparing to go ... e6 . What more can Black ask? All good, but now the bishop has become a target.} 8. Ne5+ {It's imperative to have a change of mindset and go straight for the attack. Black is playing actively with ... Bf5 , so there is just no time for Bd3 , O-O , and Re1 .} Kg8 9. Bc4+ {A very good move; the bishop cannot go on d3 , as we, being a piece down, should avoid exchanges.} e6 10. g4 {The only move to stay in the game but very strong. The idea is to remove the defender of the e6 -pawn. With three forcing moves, White has created chaos on the board, and trust me, when you play the Caro-Kann as Black, you don't want to face this position on move 10!} b5 {The most popular move, gaining space on the queenside while attacking the bishop on c4 .} 11. Bb3 Be4 12. Bxe6+ Kh7 13. g5 {A beautiful move! Sacrificing the rookie on h1 to decoy the bishop on e4 protecting the critical g6 -square. Remember, the main idea is to checkmate on g6 . By playing this move so so many times, my opponents think the idea is to attack the pony on f6 . So they almost always take the rookie on h1 .} Qe7 {It's imperative for Black to avoid Nf7 with tempi on the queen after ... hxg5 .} 14. Bb3 {This is the most common move and a very good move. The idea is simple: defending the bishop on e6 and renewing the threat of gxf6 .} hxg5 (14... Bxh1 15. g6#) 15. Bxg5 Nbd7 ({The only move, but good enough; not taking the rookie on h1 , but completing the queenside development.} 15... Bxh1 $4 {gives the d3 -square for the queen:} 16. Qd3+ Be4 17. Qh3+ {. A very popular and beautiful mate.}) 16. f4 Nxe5 17. fxe5 Bxh1 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Qd3+ f5 ({Sacrificing the pawn so there is no longer the check on g3 .} 19... Kg7 20. Qg3+ Kh7 21. Qd3+ f5 $1 {and it's a transposition.}) 20. Qxf5+ ({I will stop the lines here. White has enough compensation for the lack of material. The black king is very weak. I recommend} 20. Bf7 $1 {rather than Bb3 . Still, both moves give White amazing chances and romantic chess.}) *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Martian Gambit 4...Bf5 – I"]
[Black "Martian Gambit – Overview"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B18"]
[PlyCount "15"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng5 Bg6 6. N1f3 h6 7. Ne6 fxe6 8. Ne5 {Welcome to the Martian Gambit, a Gambit from Mars! My dear community says it's much better than AG, as you win much faster since Black always blunders. But it is less often seen compared to AG. I love both gambits, but they are right. You can checkmate much faster in MG than in AG. The main reason is that Black's king is bugged by their own pieces. In the Martian Gambit, it's all about the weak light squares and the lack of development of Black's kingside. The e6 -pawn is actually OUR pawn. You might say uh, duh? What the heck are you talking about? If you just take and remove the e6 -pawn from the board, Black would just go ... Bf7 , ... e6 , ... Bd6 and you can resign. With the pawn on e6 and the pony on e5 , have fun developing your kingside. My Five Lifelines: A. Develop quickly the light-squared bishop and the queen to avoid Black's main counterplay with ... Nd7 , exchanging your best piece on e5 . B. After the development of those pieces is finished, Black has usually blundered (as practice has shown) take on f7 and win the game accordingly. C. Please remember to take the bishop on f7 ONLY if it wins you the game or gives you an advantage. It's not worth exchanging your best piece for the bad bishop on f7 just to make sure the king does not castle. You are lost, as you have no pieces to attack the king. D. Try to play on the kingside mainly, but remember to play on the queenside, too, for that positional bind. Remember the thematic a4 - a5 and Ra3 play on the queenside. E. Do not memorize lines. Focus on ideas, patterns, and common tactics.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Martian Gambit 4...Bf5 – I"]
[Black "Martian Gambit 4...Bf5 - 7..."]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B18"]
[PlyCount "23"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 { The Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense, also known as the Capablanca Variation.  4...Bf5 , developing the bishop outside the pawn chain, is a key strategy in the Caro-Kann. This variation presents a solid and highly flexible structure for Black, aiming to withstand White's central pressure while preparing a counterattack. White has several plans to choose from, such as playing Ng3 to attack the bishop on f5 and potentially gain the bishop pair after an exchange. Another plan involves playing Bd3 , offering a trade of bishops and potentially doubling Black's pawns on the f-file. White can also opt for a more aggressive setup with f4 and Nf3 , aiming for a kingside attack. Overall, the Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense is a solid and reliable choice for Black, offering a balanced position with chances for both sides. Popular among players of all levels, from club players to grandmasters, this opening is valued for its flexibility and adaptability. This move was played most notably in Game 2, Vishy Anand vs Magnus Carlsen – 2013 World Chess Championship, which gave Magnus an easy draw with Black (because Vishy didn't play Ng5! :-))} 5. Ng5 {After everything has been said for 4...Bf5 , this move comes with shock to people, and if you know what you are doing, you can win VERY easily. When attacking, never go back! Still preparing to sacrifice on f7 after ... h6 . I am sure after this move, Black is out of home prep.} (5. Ng3 {is THE most popular move, but with good play, Black is doing more than OK.}) 5... Bg6 {The most popular move, at least from personal experience. I get this move most often, as there is no Alien Gambit anymore. Also, it's often pre-moved as everyone plays 5.Ng3 attacking the bishop on f5 . Now Black is ready to kick the pony with ... h6 .} 6. N1f3 h6 {Time to go back on h3 , right? Hmmm...} 7. Ne6 {Martian Gambit!!  I am also the inventor of the Martian Gambit. This is how you beat 4...Bf5 . At first sight, this looks like: uh, duh? What the heck is this move? Excuse me, but your pony is hanging. } ({The first time I played} 7. Ne6 {was on April 15, 2024, against superknight112, and I won. I got so tired of going back to h3 and playing boring chess that I decided to go for romance.❤ But it was accidental. Then I started playing it again and with amazing results. On Jul 7, 2024, I officially named the gambit. It's indeed very special.}) ({The Martian Gambit is} 7. Ne6 $3 {, and it was invented on 7/7/2024. Also, one of my grandmothers, whom I love so much, was born on the 7th of July. 7 is also my favorite digit. Amen.  The idea of this move is to create chaos on the board on just move 7! It weakens the h5 - e8 diagonal, but it allows us to get super duper important tempi with Ne5 's next move, as it attacks the undefended bishop on e6 . The last point of this move is the long, long (when I say long, I mean it) positional advantage of Black's lack of development on the kingside. The g6 -pawn makes it very, very hard for Black to develop their f8 and h8 -pieces. Don't worry, with the examples I will show, you will see what I mean. To summarize, it's better for Black not to have this e6 -pawn. If you remove it, Black is easily winning, as they will go ... e6 and develop their kingside. So the e6 -pawn, after ... fxe6 , is working for us! Isn't that amazing? That's a very important thing to remember.}) 7... Qb6 ({This move was played by a 2700 FM against me.} 7... Qd5 $4 {Believe it or not, this is a very popular move:} 8. Nc7+ Kd7 9. Nxd5 {.}) 8. Ne5 {Attacking the bishop on g6 while centralizing the pony on e5 . As you can see, White is already very active and winning according to the engines. It may not be obvious initially, but Nxg6 followed by Bd3 , and Nc4 with Nc7 + next, are threats that Black cannot meet satisfactorily.} Nd7 9. Nc4 Qb4+ 10. c3 Qb5 11. Nc7+ Kd8 12. Nxb5 {I ended up winning the game.} *

