1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 { The Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense, also known as the Capablanca Variation.  4...Bf5 , developing the bishop outside the pawn chain, is a key strategy in the Caro-Kann. This variation presents a solid and highly flexible structure for Black, aiming to withstand White's central pressure while preparing a counterattack. White has several plans to choose from, such as playing Ng3 to attack the bishop on f5 and potentially gain the bishop pair after an exchange. Another plan involves playing Bd3 , offering a trade of bishops and potentially doubling Black's pawns on the f-file. White can also opt for a more aggressive setup with f4 and Nf3 , aiming for a kingside attack. Overall, the Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense is a solid and reliable choice for Black, offering a balanced position with chances for both sides. Popular among players of all levels, from club players to grandmasters, this opening is valued for its flexibility and adaptability. This move was played most notably in Game 2, Vishy Anand vs Magnus Carlsen – 2013 World Chess Championship, which gave Magnus an easy draw with Black (because Vishy didn't play Ng5! :-))} 5. Ng5 {After everything has been said for 4...Bf5 , this move comes with shock to people, and if you know what you are doing, you can win VERY easily. When attacking, never go back! Still preparing to sacrifice on f7 after ... h6 . I am sure after this move, Black is out of home prep.} (5. Ng3 {is THE most popular move, but with good play, Black is doing more than OK.}) 5... Bg6 {The most popular move, at least from personal experience. I get this move most often, as there is no Alien Gambit anymore. Also, it's often pre-moved as everyone plays 5.Ng3 attacking the bishop on f5 . Now Black is ready to kick the pony with ... h6 .} 6. N1f3 h6 {Time to go back on h3 , right? Hmmm...} 7. Ne6 {Martian Gambit!!  I am also the inventor of the Martian Gambit. This is how you beat 4...Bf5 . At first sight, this looks like: uh, duh? What the heck is this move? Excuse me, but your pony is hanging. } ({The first time I played} 7. Ne6 {was on April 15, 2024, against superknight112, and I won. I got so tired of going back to h3 and playing boring chess that I decided to go for romance.❤ But it was accidental. Then I started playing it again and with amazing results. On Jul 7, 2024, I officially named the gambit. It's indeed very special.}) ({The Martian Gambit is} 7. Ne6 $3 {, and it was invented on 7/7/2024. Also, one of my grandmothers, whom I love so much, was born on the 7th of July. 7 is also my favorite digit. Amen.  The idea of this move is to create chaos on the board on just move 7! It weakens the h5 - e8 diagonal, but it allows us to get super duper important tempi with Ne5 's next move, as it attacks the undefended bishop on e6 . The last point of this move is the long, long (when I say long, I mean it) positional advantage of Black's lack of development on the kingside. The g6 -pawn makes it very, very hard for Black to develop their f8 and h8 -pieces. Don't worry, with the examples I will show, you will see what I mean. To summarize, it's better for Black not to have this e6 -pawn. If you remove it, Black is easily winning, as they will go ... e6 and develop their kingside. So the e6 -pawn, after ... fxe6 , is working for us! Isn't that amazing? That's a very important thing to remember.}) 7... Qd6 (7... Qd5 $4 {Believe it or not, this is a very popular move:} 8. Nc7+ Kd7 9. Nxd5 {.}) 8. Nxf8 Kxf8 9. Bd3 { A very strong move, exchanging Black's best piece. In the words of GM Boris Gelfand: 'If your opponent has few active pieces, try to exchange them so they are left only with inactive pieces.'} Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nf6 11. O-O e6 12. Re1 Nbd7 13. c4 g6 14. Qc3 Kg7 15. b3 Rhe8 16. Bb2 Rad8 17. Rad1 {White is much better, as they have an amazing battery on the a1 - h8 diagonal and an amazing center.} *

