move most often, as there is no Alien Gambit anymore. Also, it's often pre-moved as everyone plays 5.Ng3 attacking the bishop on f5 . Now Black is ready to kick the pony with ... h6 .} 6. N1f3 h6 {Time to go back on h3 , right? Hmmm...} 7. Ne6 {Martian Gambit!!  I am also the inventor of the Martian Gambit. This is how you beat 4...Bf5 . At first sight, this looks like: uh, duh? What the heck is this move? Excuse me, but your pony is hanging. } ({The first time I played} 7. Ne6 {was on April 15, 2024, against superknight112, and I won. I got so tired of going back to h3 and playing boring chess that I decided to go for romance.❤ But it was accidental. Then I started playing it again and with amazing results. On Jul 7, 2024, I officially named the gambit. It's indeed very special.}) ({The Martian Gambit is} 7. Ne6 $3 {, and it was invented on 7/7/2024. Also, one of my grandmothers, whom I love so much, was born on the 7th of July. 7 is also my favorite digit. Amen.  The idea of this move is to create chaos on the board on just move 7! It weakens the h5 - e8 diagonal, but it allows us to get super duper important tempi with Ne5 's next move, as it attacks the undefended bishop on e6 . The last point of this move is the long, long (when I say long, I mean it) positional advantage of Black's lack of development on the kingside. The g6 -pawn makes it very, very hard for Black to develop their f8 and h8 -pieces. Don't worry, with the examples I will show, you will see what I mean. To summarize, it's better for Black not to have this e6 -pawn. If you remove it, Black is easily winning, as they will go ... e6 and develop their kingside. So the e6 -pawn, after ... fxe6 , is working for us! Isn't that amazing? That's a very important thing to remember.}) 7... fxe6 8. Ne5 {Gaining a vital tempo against the bishop on g6 . After the bishop moves, it will have spent 3 moves in the opening!} (8. Bd3 $6 {is not a good move, but only if Black knows how to counter it because we don't gain the vital tempo we need with 8.Ne5 ! I do not recommend this move, but you can play it until ur opponent plays} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {followed by ... Qf5 .}) ({To recap,} 8. Bd3 Bxd3 (8... Bf7 9. Ne5 $1 {White's trick with Bd3 has worked! Now they don't have to worry about ... Bf5 - e4 - h7 and face this very good for White 8...Bf7 . We get a transposition.}) 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {( Nd7?? Qg6# )} 10. Bd2 Qf5 $1 {That's it! Black's queen is perfectly placed on f5 , when White has little compensation.} 11. Qb3 Nd7 12. Qxb7 Qe4+ 13. Be3 Rb8 14. Qxa7 g5 {and Black does not have any problems, like with their kingside development with 8.Ne5 ! The queen on e4 is very strong.}) 8... Be4 9. Bc4 {I consider this move to be the refutation of Black's 8...Be4 . The bishop attacks the e6 -pawn.} (9. f3 Bf5 10. g4 Bh7 11. Bd3 {is a transposition to} Bf5 {g4} 12. Be4 {f3} Bh7 13. Bd3 {.}) 9... Nd7 { As I have said before, this is Black's main plan and a good one. White has to stop it, but it's difficult to do that if Black's bishop stays on the b1 - h7 diagonal.} 10. Qe2 {The critical move, getting out of the d-file (very important so that we don't exchange queens) and attacking the bishop on e4 .} Ngf6 11. f3 {This is a very good move that has a nice tactical point – if the bishop leaves the b1 - h7 diagonal, Black is lost.} Bh7 (11... Bd5 $2 12. Bd3 $1 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd7 14. Bg6#) (11... Bf5 12. g4 Nxe5 13. dxe5 {, Black has two pieces attacked and can save only one.} Nd5 14. gxf5 exf5 15. f4 { with chances for both sides. Black is a pawn down, but their light squares are so weak, and White has the bishop pair.}) 12. Nf7 ({I can't do this anymore, my brothers and sisters. This gambit is just TOO OP!! It's all about the e6 -pawn, as mate will follow afterwards: Kxf7 Qxe6+ Kg6 Qf7+ Kf5} 12. g4 {.}) *

