 gain the vital tempo we need with 8.Ne5 ! I do not recommend this move, but you can play it until ur opponent plays} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {followed by ... Qf5 .}) ({To recap,} 8. Bd3 Bxd3 (8... Bf7 9. Ne5 $1 {White's trick with Bd3 has worked! Now they don't have to worry about ... Bf5 - e4 - h7 and face this very good for White 8...Bf7 . We get a transposition.}) 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {( Nd7?? Qg6# )} 10. Bd2 Qf5 $1 {That's it! Black's queen is perfectly placed on f5 , when White has little compensation.} 11. Qb3 Nd7 12. Qxb7 Qe4+ 13. Be3 Rb8 14. Qxa7 g5 {and Black does not have any problems, like with their kingside development with 8.Ne5 ! The queen on e4 is very strong.}) 8... Be4 9. Bc4 {I consider this move to be the refutation of Black's 8...Be4 . The bishop attacks the e6 -pawn.} (9. f3 Bf5 10. g4 Bh7 11. Bd3 {is a transposition to} Bf5 {g4} 12. Be4 {f3} Bh7 13. Bd3 {.}) 9... Nd7 { As I have said before, this is Black's main plan and a good one. White has to stop it, but it's difficult to do that if Black's bishop stays on the b1 - h7 diagonal.} 10. Qe2 {The critical move, getting out of the d-file (very important so that we don't exchange queens) and attacking the bishop on e4 .} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Qxe5 13. O-O-O ({Now f3 is threatened, and there is only one move for Black.} 13. f3 $2 {immediately fails to} Qxb2 14. O-O Bxc2 15. Qxe6 Qd4+ 16. Kh1 Qxd2 {.}) 13... Qf5 {Getting out of the pin and attacking the c2 -pawn.} (13... Nf6 $2 {is a very popular blunder, missing f3 : } 14. f3 $1 O-O-O 15. fxe4 Qxe4 16. Bxe6+ Kb8 17. Qxe4 Nxe4 18. Bf4+ Nd6 19. c4 {.}) 14. f3 Bxc2 15. g4 Qg6 16. Ba5 {Sacrificing the bishop for the long positional bind. In the words of GM Boris Gelfand: 'If your opponent has few active pieces, try to exchange them so they are left only with inactive pieces. ' Here, we sacrifice to remove the active pieces, but the idea is the same. The other rookie will just replace the sacrificed rookie on d1 and Black will have no developed pieces. It's important to put the bishop on a5 if the queen is on g6 and put the bishop on c3 if the queen is on h7 .} ({It's important to stop 17...Rd8 ! as we can't take on e6 in the variation when the queen is on h7 :} 16. Bc3 $4 Bxd1 17. Rxd1 Rd8 $1 18. Rxd8+ Kxd8 19. Qd2+ Ke8 20. Bxe6 Qxe6 {. That is why when the queen is on g6 , the bishop is put on a5 to stop ... Rd8 !}) 16... Bxd1 17. Rxd1 e5 18. Bd3 Qf6 19. f4 e4 20. Qxe4 Kf7 (20... e6 21. Bc4 $1 Ke7 22. Bc3 Qf7 23. Bb4+ Ke8 24. Bxe6 {, and if e5 fxe5 Qg5+ Bd2} Qe7 { Bb4!! Qg5+} 25. Bd2 {Qe7 Bb4!!} Qb4 26. Bc4+ $1 {Ke7 Qf4+– .}) 21. Bc3 Qd6 22. Bc4+ {White is winning the queen, and checkmate will be delivered soon. Easy win. :)} *

