1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 { The Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense, also known as the Capablanca Variation.  4...Bf5 , developing the bishop outside the pawn chain, is a key strategy in the Caro-Kann. This variation presents a solid and highly flexible structure for Black, aiming to withstand White's central pressure while preparing a counterattack. White has several plans to choose from, such as playing Ng3 to attack the bishop on f5 and potentially gain the bishop pair after an exchange. Another plan involves playing Bd3 , offering a trade of bishops and potentially doubling Black's pawns on the f-file. White can also opt for a more aggressive setup with f4 and Nf3 , aiming for a kingside attack. Overall, the Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense is a solid and reliable choice for Black, offering a balanced position with chances for both sides. Popular among players of all levels, from club players to grandmasters, this opening is valued for its flexibility and adaptability. This move was played most notably in Game 2, Vishy Anand vs Magnus Carlsen – 2013 World Chess Championship, which gave Magnus an easy draw with Black (because Vishy didn't play Ng5! :-))} 5. Ng5 {After everything has been said for 4...Bf5 , this move comes with shock to people, and if you know what you are doing, you can win VERY easily. When attacking, never go back! Still preparing to sacrifice on f7 after ... h6 . I am sure after this move, Black is out of home prep.} (5. Ng3 {is THE most popular move, but with good play, Black is doing more than OK.}) 5... Bg6 {The most popular move, at least from personal experience. I get this move most often, as there is no Alien Gambit anymore. Also, it's often pre-moved as everyone plays 5.Ng3 attacking the bishop on f5 . Now Black is ready to kick the pony with ... h6 .} 6. N1f3 h6 {Time to go back on h3 , right? Hmmm...} 7. Ne6 {Martian Gambit!!  I am also the inventor of the Martian Gambit. This is how you beat 4...Bf5 . At first sight, this looks like: uh, duh? What the heck is this move? Excuse me, but your pony is hanging. } ({The first time I played} 7. Ne6 {was on April 15, 2024, against superknight112, and I won. I got so tired of going back to h3 and playing boring chess that I decided to go for romance.❤ But it was accidental. Then I started playing it again and with amazing results. On Jul 7, 2024, I officially named the gambit. It's indeed very special.}) ({The Martian Gambit is} 7. Ne6 $3 {, and it was invented on 7/7/2024. Also, one of my grandmothers, whom I love so much, was born on the 7th of July. 7 is also my favorite digit. Amen.  The idea of this move is to create chaos on the board on just move 7! It weakens the h5 - e8 diagonal, but it allows us to get super duper important tempi with Ne5 's next move, as it attacks the undefended bishop on e6 . The last point of this move is the long, long (when I say long, I mean it) positional advantage of Black's lack of development on the kingside. The g6 -pawn makes it very, very hard for Black to develop their f8 and h8 -pieces. Don't worry, with the examples I will show, you will see what I mean. To summarize, it's better for Black not to have this e6 -pawn. If you remove it, Black is easily winning, as they will go ... e6 and develop their kingside. So the e6 -pawn, after ... fxe6 , is working for us! Isn't that amazing? That's a very important thing to remember.}) 7... fxe6 8. Ne5 {Gaining a vital tempo against the bishop on g6 . After the bishop moves, it will have spent 3 moves in the opening!} (8. Bd3 $6 {is not a good move, but only if Black knows how to counter it because we don't gain the vital tempo we need with 8.Ne5 ! I do not recommend this move, but you can play it until ur opponent plays} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {followed by ... Qf5 .}) ({To recap,} 8. Bd3 Bxd3 (8... Bf7 9. Ne5 $1 {White's trick with Bd3 has worked! Now they don't have to worry about ... Bf5 - e4 - h7 and face this very good for White 8...Bf7 . We get a transposition.}) 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {( Nd7?? Qg6# )} 10. Bd2 Qf5 $1 {That's it! Black's queen is perfectly placed on f5 , when White has little compensation.} 11. Qb3 Nd7 12. Qxb7 Qe4+ 13. Be3 Rb8 14. Qxa7 g5 {and Black does not have any problems, like with their kingside development with 8.Ne5 ! The queen on e4 is very strong.}) 8... Be4 9. Bc4 {I consider this move to be the refutation of Black's 8...Be4 . The bishop attacks the e6 -pawn.} (9. f3 Bf5 10. g4 Bh7 11. Bd3 {is a transposition to} Bf5 {g4} 12. Be4 {f3} Bh7 13. Bd3 {.}) 9... Nd7 { As I have said before, this is Black's main plan and a good one. White has to stop it, but it's difficult to do that if Black's bishop stays on the b1 - h7 diagonal.} 10. Qe2 {The critical move, getting out of the d-file (very important so that we don't exchange queens) and attacking the bishop on e4 .} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Qxe5 13. O-O-O ({Now f3 is threatened, and there is only one move for Black.} 13. f3 $2 {immediately fails to} Qxb2 14. O-O Bxc2 15. Qxe6 Qd4+ 16. Kh1 Qxd2 {.}) 13... Qf5 {Getting out of the pin and attacking the c2 -pawn.} (13... Nf6 $2 {is a very popular blunder, missing f3 : } 14. f3 $1 O-O-O 15. fxe4 Qxe4 16. Bxe6+ Kb8 17. Qxe4 Nxe4 18. Bf4+ Nd6 19. c4 {.}) 14. f3 Bxc2 15. g4 Qg6 16. Ba5 {Sacrificing the bishop for the long positional bind. In the words of GM Boris Gelfand: 'If your opponent has few active pieces, try to exchange them so they are left only with inactive pieces. ' Here, we sacrifice to remove the active pieces, but the idea is the same. The other rookie will just replace the sacrificed rookie on d1 and Black will have no developed pieces. It's important to put the bishop on a5 if the queen is on g6 and put the bishop on c3 if the queen is on h7 .} ({It's important to stop 17...Rd8 ! as we can't take on e6 in the variation when the queen is on h7 :} 16. Bc3 $4 Bxd1 17. Rxd1 Rd8 $1 18. Rxd8+ Kxd8 19. Qd2+ Ke8 20. Bxe6 Qxe6 {. That is why when the queen is on g6 , the bishop is put on a5 to stop ... Rd8 !}) 16... Bxd1 17. Rxd1 Nf6 {The most natural move is a mistake as the queen becomes very strong on e6 . Still, White has to play very precisely.} 18. Qxe6 h5 19. g5 {WOW! Sacrificing a pawn with check! The idea is to remove the defender of the f7 -square.} Qxg5+ 20. f4 ({Oops! We did it again!} 20. Kb1 $4 Qg6+ $1 21. Ka1 h4 {and White lacks pieces to create more threats.}) 20... Qxf4+ (20... Qxa5 21. Qf7#) 21. Bd2 (21. Kb1 Qe4+) 21... Qg4 22. Qf7+ ({ It was all about this check: Kd7} 22. Bf4 {Kc8 Be6+} Nd7 {Qe8 .}) *

