{Kc8 Qf5= with a romantic draw. Do not lose heart; drawing is OK if Black defends like a lion. Practice shows it almost never happens, the margin of error for Black is quite big.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 {The Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense, also known as the Capablanca Variation.  4...Bf5 , developing the bishop outside the pawn chain, is a key strategy in the Caro-Kann. This variation presents a solid and highly flexible structure for Black, aiming to withstand White's central pressure while preparing a counterattack. White has several plans to choose from, such as playing Ng3 to attack the bishop on f5 and potentially gain the bishop pair after an exchange. Another plan involves playing Bd3 , offering a trade of bishops and potentially doubling Black's pawns on the f-file. White can also opt for a more aggressive setup with f4 and Nf3 , aiming for a kingside attack.  Overall, the Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense is a solid and reliable choice for Black, offering a balanced position with chances for both sides. Popular among players of all levels, from club players to grandmasters, this opening is valued for its flexibility and adaptability. This move was played most notably in Game 2, Vishy Anand vs Magnus Carlsen – 2013 World Chess Championship, which gave Magnus an easy draw with Black (because Vishy didn't play Ng5! :-))} 5. Ng5 { After everything has been said for 4...Bf5 , this move comes with shock to people, and if you know what you are doing, you can win VERY easily. When attacking, never go back! Still preparing to sacrifice on f7 after ... h6 . I am sure after this move, Black is out of home prep.} (5. Ng3 {is THE most popular move, but with good play, Black is doing more than OK.}) 5... Bg6 { The most popular move, at least from personal experience. I get this move most often, as there is no Alien Gambit anymore. Also, it's often pre-moved as everyone plays 5.Ng3 attacking the bishop on f5 . Now Black is ready to kick the pony with ... h6 .} 6. N1f3 h6 {Time to go back on h3 , right? Hmmm...} 7. Ne6 {Martian Gambit!!  I am also the inventor of the Martian Gambit. This is how you beat 4...Bf5 . At first sight, this looks like: uh, duh? What the heck is this move? Excuse me, but your pony is hanging.} ({The first time I played} 7. Ne6 {was on April 15, 2024, against superknight112, and I won. I got so tired of going back to h3 and playing boring chess that I decided to go for romance.❤ But it was accidental. Then I started playing it again and with amazing results. On Jul 7, 2024, I officially named the gambit. It's indeed very special.}) ({The Martian Gambit is} 7. Ne6 $3 {, and it was invented on 7/ 7/2024. Also, one of my grandmothers, whom I love so much, was born on the 7th of July. 7 is also my favorite digit. Amen.  The idea of this move is to create chaos on the board on just move 7! It weakens the h5 - e8 diagonal, but it allows us to get super duper important tempi with Ne5 's next move, as it attacks the undefended bishop on e6 . The last point of this move is the long, long (when I say long, I mean it) positional advantage of Black's lack of development on the kingside. The g6 -pawn makes it very, very hard for Black to develop their f8 and h8 -pieces. Don't worry, with the examples I will show, you will see what I mean. To summarize, it's better for Black not to have this e6 -pawn. If you remove it, Black is easily winning, as they will go ... e6 and develop their kingside. So the e6 -pawn, after ... fxe6 , is working for us! Isn't that amazing? That's a very important thing to remember.}) 7... fxe6 8. Ne5 {Gaining a vital tempo against the bishop on g6 . After the bishop moves, it will have spent 3 moves in the opening!} (8. Bd3 $6 {is not a good move, but only if Black knows how to counter it because we don't gain the vital tempo we need with 8.Ne5 ! I do not recommend this move, but you can play it until ur opponent plays} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {followed by ... Qf5 .}) ({To recap,} 8. Bd3 Bxd3 (8... Bf7 9. Ne5 $1 {White's trick with Bd3 has worked! Now they don't have to worry about ... Bf5 - e4 - h7 and face this very good for White 8...Bf7 . We get a transposition.}) 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 { ( Nd7?? Qg6# )} 10. Bd2 Qf5 $1 {That's it! Black's queen is perfectly placed on f5 , when White has little compensation.} 11. Qb3 Nd7 12. Qxb7 Qe4+ 13. Be3 Rb8 14. Qxa7 g5 {and Black does not have any problems, like with their kingside development with 8.Ne5 ! The queen on e4 is very strong.}) 8... Bh7 9. Bd3 {This is the move I recommend. Usually, we put the bishop on c4 , but here, on d3 , since the bishop is on h7 because we are forcing Black to find an only move; they almost never do.} (9. Bc4 $5 Nd7 10. f4 Nxe5 11. fxe5 Qd7 12. O-O O-O-O 13. c3 g5 14. Qb3 Kb8 15. Bxe6 Qc7 16. a4 {with chaos on the board. White is a piece down but cannot find a good way to develop their kingside.}) 9... Nf6 {Only move not to lose the game. Everything else loses. Black will allow the queen to go to g6 with hopes to run on the queenside. It's quite amazing that Black had to find only one move not to lose on move 9! Practice shows that Black has a hard time finding it, especially in faster time controls.} 10. Bxh7 Rxh7 11. Qd3 Qd5 {Again, the only move for Black. The queen is very active on d5 and threatens... Qe4 +, exchanging queens. Black will try to run to the queenside.} (11... Rh8 $4 {is a popular move. :)} 12. Qg6# {, as is Nbd7?? Qg6# .}) (11... g5 $4 {is also a popular move. :)} 12. Qg6+ Rf7 13. Qxf7# {.}) 12. Qg6+ Kd8 13. O-O Nbd7 14. Re1 {This is a critical moment. Black has only one move not to lose the game.} Qxd4 (14... Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nd7 16. Qxh7) 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 {This seems like a natural move, but it's a mistake because the queen was needed on the active, yet dangerous, d4 -square.} 16. Bf4 {Now, Rad1 is a deadly threat.} Qe8 17. Rad1+ Kc8 18. Qd3 g5 19. Rxe6 { Brilliant!!! Sacrificing the bishop to use the h3 - c8 diagonal to create a devastating discovery check.} gxf4 20. Qf5 Kc7 21. Qxf4+ Kb6 22. Qb4+ Kc7 23. Qf4+ Kc8 24. Qf5 Kc7 ({If Black tries to play for a win with} 24... Nd7 $6 { , they might lose easily.} 25. Qxh7 {and White is better, as Black cannot develop their pieces.}) 25. Qf4+ *

