 at all costs, and this move does just that. You have no idea how many people miss that the e6 -pawn is indirectly attacked and play Nbd7?} 10. O-O $2 {This move is too slow and does nothing to stop Black's main counterplay with} Nbd7 $1 {and Black has almost no problems. That is why it is imperative to stop ... Nbd7 .} 11. Nxf7 $2 Kxf7 12. Qe2 Nd5 13. Qf3+ N7f6 {and Black is a piece up with no problems.}) 10... Qd6 {The idea is to defend the e6 -pawn with the queen. This is a very rare move, as it is difficult to make when Bf4 looks very strong.} 11. Nxf7 Kxf7 12. Bf4 {What a move !! Oh, I forgot to scream. BRILLIANT!! The idea is to remove the defender of the e6 -square. Also, of course, White gains a vital tempo.} Qd7 13. h4 { A fantastic move! White realizes that Black has survived all the tricks and checkmate ideas, so it's time to move to the positional bind! You might say, uh, duh? What the heck? You are a FULL piece down, which positional bind are you talking about? Well, as you can see, Black's f8 and h8 -pieces won't be developed anytime soon.} Na6 14. h5 Nc7 {It is very rare to see that this natural move (completing the idea of ... Na6 - c7 to protect the e6 -pawn) is a mistake. Now Black will be super duper passive and with NO way to develop their kingisde.} (14... Nb4 $1 {Stopping Bd3 and preparing ... b5 !} 15. c3 b5 16. Bb3 Nbd5 17. Be5 {and Black is better, as they are a piece up, but still, there is no clear way to develop their kingside. White's positional bind is very strong.}) 15. Bd3 {White is smart enough to realize that the bishop now belongs on the b1 - h7 diagonal.} Ncd5 16. Bg6+ Kg8 17. Be5 {Despite being a full piece down, White is almost winning. Black cannot develop their kingside pieces. This is the beauty of the Martian Gambit.} *

