y important thing to remember.}) 7... fxe6 8. Ne5 {Gaining a vital tempo against the bishop on g6 . After the bishop moves, it will have spent 3 moves in the opening!} (8. Bd3 $6 {is not a good move, but only if Black knows how to counter it because we don't gain the vital tempo we need with 8.Ne5 ! I do not recommend this move, but you can play it until ur opponent plays} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {followed by ... Qf5 .}) ({To recap,} 8. Bd3 Bxd3 (8... Bf7 9. Ne5 $1 {White's trick with Bd3 has worked! Now they don't have to worry about ... Bf5 - e4 - h7 and face this very good for White 8...Bf7 . We get a transposition.}) 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 { ( Nd7?? Qg6# )} 10. Bd2 Qf5 $1 {That's it! Black's queen is perfectly placed on f5 , when White has little compensation.} 11. Qb3 Nd7 12. Qxb7 Qe4+ 13. Be3 Rb8 14. Qxa7 g5 {and Black does not have any problems, like with their kingside development with 8.Ne5 ! The queen on e4 is very strong.}) 8... Bf7 9. Bc4 {THE critical move. This is the move that will win you thousands of games. This move seems to only threaten Bxe6 !!, but in fact, it stops the most natural move ... Nbd7 (a move which should always be stopped in MG) and many other ideas, as we will see.} (9. Bd3 $5 {Not a bad move, but it's not the move I would recommend. The bishop belongs on the c4 -square against the f7 -bishop. Still, it's a dangerous move. It stops ... Nbd7 and sacrifices the d4 -pawn.} Nd7 $4 (9... Qxd4 $4 10. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 11. Bg6+ $3 {Sacrificing the bishop to clear the attack on Black's queen.} Kxg6 12. Qxd4 {and White is winning, as they are a queen up.}) (9... Nf6 {, now preparing ... Nbd7 .} 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Ng6 {is the plus of 9.Bd3 !? as ... Nbd7 can be met with Ng6 ! But as you will see, in 9.Bc4 we don't allow Black ever to go ... Nbd7 .} Rg8 12. Re1 {with a very nice positional bind. White is doing more than OK. Plans like c4 and d5 will come at the right moment.}) 10. Nxf7 Kxf7 11. Qh5+ Kf6 12. Qg6# {.}) 9... Nf6 {Now, this is the critical moment