1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 { The Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense, also known as the Capablanca Variation.  4...Bf5 , developing the bishop outside the pawn chain, is a key strategy in the Caro-Kann. This variation presents a solid and highly flexible structure for Black, aiming to withstand White's central pressure while preparing a counterattack. White has several plans to choose from, such as playing Ng3 to attack the bishop on f5 and potentially gain the bishop pair after an exchange. Another plan involves playing Bd3 , offering a trade of bishops and potentially doubling Black's pawns on the f-file. White can also opt for a more aggressive setup with f4 and Nf3 , aiming for a kingside attack. Overall, the Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense is a solid and reliable choice for Black, offering a balanced position with chances for both sides. Popular among players of all levels, from club players to grandmasters, this opening is valued for its flexibility and adaptability. This move was played most notably in Game 2, Vishy Anand vs Magnus Carlsen – 2013 World Chess Championship, which gave Magnus an easy draw with Black (because Vishy didn't play Ng5! :-))} 5. Ng5 {After everything has been said for 4...Bf5 , this move comes with shock to people, and if you know what you are doing, you can win VERY easily. When attacking, never go back! Still preparing to sacrifice on f7 after ... h6 . I am sure after this move, Black is out of home prep.} (5. Ng3 {is THE most popular move, but with good play, Black is doing more than OK.}) 5... Bg6 {The most popular move, at least from personal experience. I get this move most often, as there is no Alien Gambit anymore. Also, it's often pre-moved as everyone plays 5.Ng3 attacking the bishop on f5 . Now Black is ready to kick the pony with ... h6 .} 6. N1f3 h6 {Time to go back on h3 , right? Hmmm...} 7. Ne6 {Martian Gambit!!  I am also the inventor of the Martian Gambit. This is how you beat 4...Bf5 . At first sight, this looks like: uh, duh? What the heck is this move? Excuse me, but your pony is hanging. } ({The first time I played} 7. Ne6 {was on April 15, 2024, against superknight112, and I won. I got so tired of going back to h3 and playing boring chess that I decided to go for romance.❤ But it was accidental. Then I started playing it again and with amazing results. On Jul 7, 2024, I officially named the gambit. It's indeed very special.}) ({The Martian Gambit is} 7. Ne6 $3 {, and it was invented on 7/7/2024. Also, one of my grandmothers, whom I love so much, was born on the 7th of July. 7 is also my favorite digit. Amen.  The idea of this move is to create chaos on the board on just move 7! It weakens the h5 - e8 diagonal, but it allows us to get super duper important tempi with Ne5 's next move, as it attacks the undefended bishop on e6 . The last point of this move is the long, long (when I say long, I mean it) positional advantage of Black's lack of development on the kingside. The g6 -pawn makes it very, very hard for Black to develop their f8 and h8 -pieces. Don't worry, with the examples I will show, you will see what I mean. To summarize, it's better for Black not to have this e6 -pawn. If you remove it, Black is easily winning, as they will go ... e6 and develop their kingside. So the e6 -pawn, after ... fxe6 , is working for us! Isn't that amazing? That's a very important thing to remember.}) 7... fxe6 8. Ne5 {Gaining a vital tempo against the bishop on g6 . After the bishop moves, it will have spent 3 moves in the opening!} (8. Bd3 $6 {is not a good move, but only if Black knows how to counter it because we don't gain the vital tempo we need with 8.Ne5 ! I do not recommend this move, but you can play it until ur opponent plays} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {followed by ... Qf5 .}) ({To recap,} 8. Bd3 Bxd3 (8... Bf7 9. Ne5 $1 {White's trick with Bd3 has worked! Now they don't have to worry about ... Bf5 - e4 - h7 and face this very good for White 8...Bf7 . We get a transposition.}) 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {( Nd7?? Qg6# )} 10. Bd2 Qf5 $1 {That's it! Black's queen is perfectly placed on f5 , when White has little compensation.} 11. Qb3 Nd7 12. Qxb7 Qe4+ 13. Be3 Rb8 14. Qxa7 g5 {and Black does not have any problems, like with their kingside development with 8.Ne5 ! The queen on e4 is very strong.}) 8... Bf7 9. Bc4 {THE critical move. This is the move that will win you thousands of games. This move seems to only threaten Bxe6 !!, but in fact, it stops the most natural move ... Nbd7 (a move which should always be stopped in MG) and many other ideas, as we will see.} (9. Bd3 $5 {Not a bad move, but it's not the move I would recommend. The bishop belongs on the c4 -square against the f7 -bishop. Still, it's a dangerous move. It stops ... Nbd7 and sacrifices the d4 -pawn.} Nd7 $4 (9... Qxd4 $4 10. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 11. Bg6+ $3 {Sacrificing the bishop to clear the attack on Black's queen.} Kxg6 12. Qxd4 {and White is winning, as they are a queen up.}) (9... Nf6 {, now preparing ... Nbd7 .} 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Ng6 {is the plus of 9.Bd3 !? as ... Nbd7 can be met with Ng6 ! But as you will see, in 9.Bc4 we don't allow Black ever to go ... Nbd7 .} Rg8 12. Re1 {with a very nice positional bind. White is doing more than OK. Plans like c4 and d5 will come at the right moment.}) 10. Nxf7 Kxf7 11. Qh5+ Kf6 12. Qg6# {.}) 9... Nf6 {Now, this is the critical moment. Black's last move develops a piece, protects the h5 and g4 -squares, and prepares the move that needs to be stopped at all costs, ... Nbd7 , to exchange our best piece. As White, what would you play to stop that?} 10. Qe2 ( {It's imperative to stop ... Nbd7 at all costs, and this move does just that. You have no idea how many people miss that the e6 -pawn is indirectly attacked and play Nbd7?} 10. O-O $2 {This move is too slow and does nothing to stop Black's main counterplay with} Nbd7 $1 {and Black has almost no problems. That is why it is imperative to stop ... Nbd7 .} 11. Nxf7 $2 Kxf7 12. Qe2 Nd5 13. Qf3+ N7f6 {and Black is a piece up with no problems.}) 10... Nd5 {Not the best move, but a very, very popular move. Black blocks the attack on e6 and prepares their main counterplay with ... Nbd7 , but this move leaves Black's kingside very weak.} 11. Qf3 {A fantastic move! Immediately exploring the fact that the pony is no longer on f6 and the f7 -bishop is hanging. Still, as you can see, we never give Black the time to play ... Nbd7 . This is the main idea of the Martian Gambit.} Nf6 ({Black has to go back. All other moves lose.} 11... Bg8 $4 {I have faced this move very often in the ladder (pool):} 12. Qh5+ g6 13. Qxg6+ Bf7 14. Qxf7# {.}) 12. O-O ({Beautiful! Always play for a win!} 12. Qe2 Nd5 13. Qf3 Nf6 {with a boring draw.}) 12... Qxd4 13. Qb3 {Stop This Guy From Brillianting‼️ WHAT? White has the audacity of hoping to sacrifice another pony and still win the game! The Martian Gambit is SO OP! It's all about the b7 and e6 -pawns.} Qxe5 14. Qxb7 Bg6 15. Bf4 {LOL! What a shock! Brilliant! Sacrificing the bishop to deflect the queen on protecting the pawn on e6 . The Martian Gambit is truly amazing.} (15. Qxa8 $4 {Too greedy. Black's two minor pieces against White's rookie are much stronger.} Kf7 16. Qxa7 Bxc2 {and Black is better, as they are ahead in material and their king is safe.}) (15. Qc8+ $4 Kf7 16. Bf4 Nbd7 $3 {Brilliant!! Black gives some material back so they can take on f4 without getting mated with Bxe6 +. That is one of the drawbacks of attacking chess. When you sacrifice a lot, your opponent can give some material back and defend. This is a perfect example. After} 17. Qxa8 Qxf4 {, Black has three minor pieces for a rookie; they are winning.}) 15... Qxf4 16. Qc8+ Kf7 17. Bxe6# {Checkmate! Black is bugged by their own pieces, which is the main theme in the Martian Gambit. That was it, my brothers and sisters. You just learned a perfect new gambit! I hope you play it and have fun with it. Please do NOT memorize lines, but use this course as a blueprint, a template. When you get the Martian Gambit and they play a move you didn't see, there is 95% percent I cover this move and teach how to beat it. Godspeed.} *

