antee you, you can get a winning position against 2600+ FIDE GMs with it coz everyone misses White's main idea of this move. They think White's idea is to go Bxe6 !! and then Qg6 . They see that Nbd7 counters this move and immediately play it. But that is not the point of} 10. Qd3 $1 {The whole idea is the f5 -square!!!! O-O? is too slow and does nothing to stop Black's main counterplay with} Nbd7 $1 {Black has almost no problems. That is why it is imperative to stop ... Nbd7 .} 11. Nxf7 $2 Kxf7 12. Qe2 Nd5 13. Qf3+ N7f6 {and Black is a piece up with no problems.}) 10... Nbd7 ( {THE most natural and common move in this position. But it is a blunder. That is why the Martian Gambit is such an OP gambit. Natural moves lose so fast for Black. Since facts always speak louder than words, I am just going to mention that many people have played this} 10... Nbd7 {blunder, including IMs and 2900+ rated players on chess.com! This is just shocking. I won't be surprised even if Hikaru or King Magnus play this move. :))))}) 11. Nxf7 {As always the case against Bf7 , we take on f7 ONLY if it wins us the game or gives us an advantage.} Kxf7 12. Qf5 {That was the idea behind Qd3! Black is losing; there is no way to protect the e6 -pawn. Isn't this beautiful?! On move 12, we see this position, and Black is lost! This is THE most popular way to win in the Martian Gambit, at least what I have seen from my dear community games in our Martian Gambit channel in Discord.} Qb6 (12... g6 13. Qxe6+ Kg7 14. Qf7#) 13. Bxe6+ {It's imperative to take with the bishop so you keep the bind on the kingside and then open the center and checkmate Black's king.} (13. Qxe6+ $4 { is the most common blunder here and the most natural move. Taking with the queen with check and then check on f7 looks very pleasing to the eye, but it misses the whole concept of the Martian Gambit, which states: You ONLY take with the queen on e6 , in this position and others, if you deliver checkmate or win material. Otherwise, you always take with the bishop so you can bind the f8 and h8 -pieces. They can never develop as you have a bishop on e6 − protected by the rookie on e1 and queen on g6 . How is Black gonna ever gonna develop their kingside?} Ke8 14. O-O Kd8 15. Bf4 Nd5 16. Bg3 h5 $1 17. h4 Qxd4 {and Black is completely winning. White has no attack, and they are a piece down.}) 13... Ke8 14. O-O Qb5 15. Qg6+ Kd8 16. Re1 Qh5 17. Qd3 {Of course, White avoids queen exchanges.} Nd5 18. c4 {As you can see, White is ALWAYS keeping Black busy, so they don't develop their kingside and they never manage to. White is completely winning, Black's king is getting mated, and please take notice how, as usual in MG, the bishop on f8 and the rookie on h8 are doing nothing.} *

