[PlyCount "43"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 { The Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense, also known as the Capablanca Variation.  4...Bf5 , developing the bishop outside the pawn chain, is a key strategy in the Caro-Kann. This variation presents a solid and highly flexible structure for Black, aiming to withstand White's central pressure while preparing a counterattack. White has several plans to choose from, such as playing Ng3 to attack the bishop on f5 and potentially gain the bishop pair after an exchange. Another plan involves playing Bd3 , offering a trade of bishops and potentially doubling Black's pawns on the f-file. White can also opt for a more aggressive setup with f4 and Nf3 , aiming for a kingside attack. Overall, the Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense is a solid and reliable choice for Black, offering a balanced position with chances for both sides. Popular among players of all levels, from club players to grandmasters, this opening is valued for its flexibility and adaptability. This move was played most notably in Game 2, Vishy Anand vs Magnus Carlsen – 2013 World Chess Championship, which gave Magnus an easy draw with Black (because Vishy didn't play Ng5! :-))} 5. Ng5 {After everything has been said for 4...Bf5 , this move comes with shock to people, and if you know what you are doing, you can win VERY easily. When attacking, never go back! Still preparing to sacrifice on f7 after ... h6 . I am sure after this move, Black is out of home prep.} (5. Ng3 {is THE most popular move, but with good play, Black is doing more than OK.}) 5... Bg6 {The most popular move, at least from personal experience. I get this move most often, as there is no Alien Gambit anymore. Also, it's often pre-moved as everyone plays 5.Ng3 attacking the bishop on f5 . Now Black is ready to kick the pony with ... h6 .} 6. N1f3 h6 {Time to go back on h3 , right? Hmmm...} 7. Ne6 {Martian Gambit!!  I am also the inventor of the Martian Gambit. This is how you beat 4...Bf5 . At first sight, this looks like: uh, duh? What the heck is this move? Excuse me, but your pony is hanging. } ({The first time I played} 7. Ne6 {was on April 15, 2024, against superknight112, and I won. I got so tired of going back to h3 and playing boring chess that I decided to go for romance.❤ But it was accidental. Then I started playing it again and with amazing results. On Jul 7, 2024, I officially named the gambit. It's indeed very special.}) ({The Martian Gambit is} 7. Ne6 $3 {, and it was invented on 7/7/2024. Also, one of my grandmothers, whom I love so much, was born on the 7th of July. 7 is also my favorite digit. Amen.  The idea of this move is to create chaos on the board on just move 7! It weakens the h5 - e8 diagonal, but it allows us to get super duper important tempi with Ne5 's next move, as it attacks the undefended bishop on e6 . The last point of this move is the long, long (when I say long, I mean it) positional advantage of Black's lack of development on the kingside. The g6 -pawn makes it very, very hard for Black to develop their f8 and h8 -pieces. Don't worry, with the examples I will show, you will see what I mean. To summarize, it's better for Black not to have this e6 -pawn. If you remove it, Black is easily winning, as they will go ... e6 and develop their kingside. So the e6 -pawn, after ... fxe6 , is working for us! Isn't that amazing? That's a very important thing to remember.}) 7... fxe6 8. Ne5 {Gaining a vital tempo against the bishop on g6 . After the bishop moves, it will have spent 3 moves in the opening!} (8. Bd3 $6 {is not a good move, but only if Black knows how to counter it because we don't gain the vital tempo we need with 8.Ne5 ! I do not recommend this move, but you can play it until ur opponent plays} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {followed by ... Qf5 .}) ({To recap,} 8. Bd3 Bxd3 (8... Bf7 9. Ne5 $1 {White's trick with Bd3 has worked! Now they don't have to worry about ... Bf5 - e4 - h7 and face this very good for White 8...Bf7 . We get a transposition.}) 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {( Nd7?? Qg6# )} 10. Bd2 Qf5 $1 {That's it! Black's queen is perfectly placed on f5 , when White has little compensation.} 11. Qb3 Nd7 12. Qxb7 Qe4+ 13. Be3 Rb8 14. Qxa7 g5 {and Black does not have any problems, like with their kingside development with 8.Ne5 ! The queen on e4 is very strong.}) 8... Bf5 {This is the best move for Black and, on paper, the refutation of the Martian Gambit. The reason why this move is so good and so difficult to play against is because it protects the e6 -pawn, while the bishop stays active, unlike f7 , and prepares ... Nbd7 on the next move. It's difficult to play this move because it's not that natural. Your bishop was on f5 two moves ago, and the bishop can be vulnerable to attacks with g4 . Such things are almost impossible to notice in bullet and blitz. Even in rapid, most players play ... Bf7 . As we will see, if White knows what they are doing, they can win very easily.} 9. g4 {Removing the defender of the e6 -pawn at the expense of closing the d1 - h5 diagonal and weakening the kingside. With all that said, tactics save White.} Bh7 10. Bc4 {Attacking the e6 -pawn.} Nd7 11. Qe2 {A sneaky move that has a deadly trap prepared. Also, now dxe5 will not allow Black to exchange queens.} Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qb6 {A common move, sacrificing the e6 -pawn so that ... c5 would attack the bishop.} 13. O-O {Not taking on e6 to leave more chaos on the board and always leave Black calculating what happens after Bxe6 ..} Rd8 {The black king is actually safer on e8 than c8 .} 14. a4 Rd5 ({Rd8 rather than O-O-O , and now} 14... Rd5 $3 {You can guess it yourself; this is almost impossible to see during a practical game. The rookie is sacrificed to get two minor pieces in return.}) 15. a5 {Who said we need to take free pieces! The bishop, for the time being, is stronger than the rookie on d5 .} ({After} 15. Bxd5 $2 exd5 $1 16. a5 Qc7 17. f4 e6 {, Black will develop their kingside and will be much better.}) 15... Qc7 16. f4 {My dear friends, this line perfectly illustrates how important the e7 - e6 pawns are. They work against Black's kingside development. That is why we don't take the rookie on d5 , as ... exd5 will follow with a free game for Black.} g5 17. Qf2 Bg7 18. Qxa7 {What a shocking move! The queen suddenly grabs a very important pawn on a7 .} gxf4 19. Bxf4 Bxe5 20. Bxe5 Rxe5 21. Qa8+ Kd7 22. Rf8 {White is winning in this chaotic game. Black's king is way too weak, and the pony on g8 can never develop.} *

