 gain the vital tempo we need with 8.Ne5 ! I do not recommend this move, but you can play it until ur opponent plays} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {followed by ... Qf5 .}) ({To recap,} 8. Bd3 Bxd3 (8... Bf7 9. Ne5 $1 {White's trick with Bd3 has worked! Now they don't have to worry about ... Bf5 - e4 - h7 and face this very good for White 8...Bf7 . We get a transposition.}) 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {( Nd7?? Qg6# )} 10. Bd2 Qf5 $1 {That's it! Black's queen is perfectly placed on f5 , when White has little compensation.} 11. Qb3 Nd7 12. Qxb7 Qe4+ 13. Be3 Rb8 14. Qxa7 g5 {and Black does not have any problems, like with their kingside development with 8.Ne5 ! The queen on e4 is very strong.}) 8... Bf5 {This is the best move for Black and, on paper, the refutation of the Martian Gambit. The reason why this move is so good and so difficult to play against is because it protects the e6 -pawn, while the bishop stays active, unlike f7 , and prepares ... Nbd7 on the next move. It's difficult to play this move because it's not that natural. Your bishop was on f5 two moves ago, and the bishop can be vulnerable to attacks with g4 . Such things are almost impossible to notice in bullet and blitz. Even in rapid, most players play ... Bf7 . As we will see, if White knows what they are doing, they can win very easily.} 9. g4 {Removing the defender of the e6 -pawn at the expense of closing the d1 - h5 diagonal and weakening the kingside. With all that said, tactics save White.} Bh7 10. Bc4 {Attacking the e6 -pawn.} Nd7 11. Qe2 {A sneaky move that has a deadly trap prepared. Also, now dxe5 will not allow Black to exchange queens.} Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qb6 {A common move, sacrificing the e6 -pawn so that ... c5 would attack the bishop.} 13. O-O {Not taking on e6 to leave more chaos on the board and always leave Black calculating what happens after Bxe6 ..} O-O-O {The most common move. That was the idea of ... Qb6 if e6 is not taken, and then ... O-O-O . But this is a mistake, as Black's kindside won't participate in the defense of the king.} 14. Be3 c5 15. b4 { Perfecto! Sacrificing the b-pawn to open the deadly b-file.} Qxb4 16. Rab1 Qa5 17. Qf3 Qc7 18. Bxe6+ Kb8 19. Rfd1 {In the words of GM Boris Gelfand: 'If your opponent has few active pieces, try to exchange them so they are left only with inactive pieces.' This move does just that.} Rxd1+ 20. Rxd1 Nf6 {There was nothing else, the bishop on f8 was hanging.} 21. exf6 exf6 22. Bf4 { White wins the queen and the game.} *

