most popular move, at least from personal experience. I get this move most often, as there is no Alien Gambit anymore. Also, it's often pre-moved as everyone plays 5.Ng3 attacking the bishop on f5 . Now Black is ready to kick the pony with ... h6 .} 6. N1f3 h6 {Time to go back on h3 , right? Hmmm...} 7. Ne6 {Martian Gambit!!  I am also the inventor of the Martian Gambit. This is how you beat 4...Bf5 . At first sight, this looks like: uh, duh? What the heck is this move? Excuse me, but your pony is hanging. } ({The first time I played} 7. Ne6 {was on April 15, 2024, against superknight112, and I won. I got so tired of going back to h3 and playing boring chess that I decided to go for romance.❤ But it was accidental. Then I started playing it again and with amazing results. On Jul 7, 2024, I officially named the gambit. It's indeed very special.}) ({The Martian Gambit is} 7. Ne6 $3 {, and it was invented on 7/7/2024. Also, one of my grandmothers, whom I love so much, was born on the 7th of July. 7 is also my favorite digit. Amen.  The idea of this move is to create chaos on the board on just move 7! It weakens the h5 - e8 diagonal, but it allows us to get super duper important tempi with Ne5 's next move, as it attacks the undefended bishop on e6 . The last point of this move is the long, long (when I say long, I mean it) positional advantage of Black's lack of development on the kingside. The g6 -pawn makes it very, very hard for Black to develop their f8 and h8 -pieces. Don't worry, with the examples I will show, you will see what I mean. To summarize, it's better for Black not to have this e6 -pawn. If you remove it, Black is easily winning, as they will go ... e6 and develop their kingside. So the e6 -pawn, after ... fxe6 , is working for us! Isn't that amazing? That's a very important thing to remember.}) 7... fxe6 8. Ne5 {Gaining a vital tempo against the bishop on g6 . After the bishop moves, it will have spent 3 moves in the opening!} (8. Bd3 $6 {is not a good move, but only if Black knows how to counter it because we don't gain the vital tempo we need with 8.Ne5 ! I do not recommend this move, but you can play it until ur opponent plays} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {followed by ... Qf5 .}) ({To recap,} 8. Bd3 Bxd3 (8... Bf7 9. Ne5 $1 {White's trick with Bd3 has worked! Now they don't have to worry about ... Bf5 - e4 - h7 and face this very good for White 8...Bf7 . We get a transposition.}) 9. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 {( Nd7?? Qg6# )} 10. Bd2 Qf5 $1 {That's it! Black's queen is perfectly placed on f5 , when White has little compensation.} 11. Qb3 Nd7 12. Qxb7 Qe4+ 13. Be3 Rb8 14. Qxa7 g5 {and Black does not have any problems, like with their kingside development with 8.Ne5 ! The queen on e4 is very strong.}) 8... Bf5 {This is the best move for Black and, on paper, the refutation of the Martian Gambit. The reason why this move is so good and so difficult to play against is because it protects the e6 -pawn, while the bishop stays active, unlike f7 , and prepares ... Nbd7 on the next move. It's difficult to play this move because it's not that natural. Your bishop was on f5 two moves ago, and the bishop can be vulnerable to attacks with g4 . Such things are almost impossible to notice in bullet and blitz. Even in rapid, most players play ... Bf7 . As we will see, if White knows what they are doing, they can win very easily.} 9. g4 {Removing the defender of the e6 -pawn at the expense of closing the d1 - h5 diagonal and weakening the kingside. With all that said, tactics save White.} Bh7 10. Bc4 {Attacking the e6 -pawn.} Nd7 11. Qe2 {A sneaky move that has a deadly trap prepared. Also, now dxe5 will not allow Black to exchange queens.} Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qd4 13. f3 {Preparing c3 now to kick the queen from this active square.} Rd8 14. c3 Qc5 (14... Qd7 $1 {is a very difficult move to make, as the queen can get under attack on the d-file, but White doesn't have the time for that. People usually play Qc5?}) ({After} 14... Qd7 {, White should play} 15. Bb3 $1 {, which is a very important move, not allowing ... Bd3 to exchange pieces. Black is a piece up but still has to answer how are they going to develop their kingside. In the meantime, if White castles and plays Rd1 to exchange the rookie on d8 , they will be doing great.} ) 15. a4 {What a beautiful move shown at deep depth by Stockfish. The idea is to go a5 and trap the queen on c5 !! Welcome to the Martian Gambit, a truly out-of-this-world gambit!} ({The game between CM Witty_Alien (2364) vs. CM Schachkatze2000 (2740), Nov 20, 2024, continued:} 15. f4 $5 g5 $2 {It looks like a very good move, as it challenges the center, but opening the f-file favors White.} 16. Be3 Qa5 17. Bxe6 {, still, as you can see, Black just can't develop their kingside. That is the main idea of MG.} Bg7 18. O-O gxf4 19. g5 { , trying to sneak in with the queen on h5 .} fxe3 $4 20. Qh5+ Bg6 21. Qxg6# {.} ) 15... g5 16. a5 Bg7 17. f4 gxf4 18. Bxf4 b5 19. axb6 Qxb6 ({After} 19... axb6 $2 20. b4 $1 {, the queen is trapped! God save the queen!}) 20. Ra6 Qb7 21. O-O h5 22. Rxc6 {Sacrificing the rookie to deflect the queen on c6 for the winning skewer on b5 .} Qxc6 23. Bb5 *

