e is no ... Bd3 to exchange pieces.} c5 $1 17. O-O-O $3 { Engine says 0.00. :D Of course. White has the audacity of hope to sacrifice another piece!! The point of this move is that Black's kingside is out of the game.} cxd4 18. Rxd4 Qc6 19. Rxd8+ Kxd8 20. Rd1+ Kc8 (20... Kc7 {, the king is best placed on c7 so when Bb5 comes, the queen won't be trapped.} 21. Qd2 Qe8 22. Qd4 Bg7 23. Bb5 $3 {Brilliant! Sacrificing the bishop to decoy the queen from protecting the d8 -square.} Qf8 (23... Qxb5 24. Qd8+ Kc6 {Behold! There is a beautiful move here, feel free to find it!} 25. Rd6+ $3 {Brilliant!!!!!!} Kc5 (25... exd6 26. Qxd6#) 26. Qc7+ Qc6 27. Qa5+ b5 28. Qxa7+ Qb6 29. Qxb6+ Kc4 {30. Rd4#.Black's kingside pieces were just spectating the whole show. A common theme in Martian Gambit.}) 24. Qxa7 {and 0.00, of course. But it's chaos on the board. Black's king is very weak, but Black is up a lot of material. Enjoy the romance.}) 21. Qd2 Qe8 22. Bb5 $3 {Behold! The queen is 'trapped'.} Qxb5 23. Qd8# {.}) 16. Bd4 $1 {, and Black is much better as they are a piece up, but White is much more active, and still, Black is not developed on the kingside.}) 15. f4 Bg7 16. Be3 Qa5 17. O-O Be4 18. Bxe6 Bd5 19. Qc2 {In MG, the b1 - h7 diagonal is very important.} Bxe6 20. Qg6+ Kf8 21. fxg5+ {With mate to follow.} *

