ing a vital pawn.} Bd5 12. Qd3 {Sacrificing the rookie and the bishop on e6 for the mate on g6 . So romantic.} Ne4 (12... Bxe6 13. Qg6+ Bf7 14. Qxf7#) 13. Bxd5 (13. Qxe4 $2 {doesn't work in view of} Qa5+ {. }) 13... Qxd5 14. c4 {Black cannot hold on to the pony on e4 .} Qa5+ 15. Kf1 Nf6 16. Qg6+ {They saved the pony, but now the queen comes on g6 , and material will drop.} Kd8 17. Nf7+ Kc8 18. Nxh8 {White is winning. Not only are they ahead of material, but they have a much better position too. As you can see, many lines depend on White winning the rookie on h8 and, hence, the game.} *

