[White "7) Karpov Variation 4...Nd7"]
[Black "Karpov Variation – Overview"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B17"]
[PlyCount "9"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Ng5 {If you know the Alien Gambit, and if you know what you are doing, then 4...Nd7 should not be a problem. It's very, very tactical, and that suits us − the aliens. :D Be ready to always transpose to AG if they delay ... h6 , and you can't go Ne6 anymore. My Five Lifelines: A. Develop quickly the kingside, usually the pony on f3 and the bishop on d3 . B. After development is finished, you are most probably a piece down, try to use the weak diagonal h5 - e8 and make use of Black's lack of kingside development thanks to the double e-pawns. C. Be mindful of shenanigans like Ne2 !! or a skewer on the a5 - d8 diagonal. D. Try to play on the kingside mainly, but remember the thematic c4 and d5 central break if the king is on d7 or c7 . E. Always, always be tactical alert!} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Karpov Variation 4...Nd7"]
[Black "Karpov Variation 4...Nd7 5.Ng"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B17"]
[PlyCount "15"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 { This is the Caro-Kann Defense Karpov Variation. It is not a popular defense, but it can be a great surprise weapon since not many players with White will expect or know this variation of the Caro-Kann. Black aims to exchange the central pawns and then develop their pieces harmoniously, often with the intention of playing for a long-term advantage. The opening is known for its strategic depth and positional play, as both sides must carefully maneuver their pieces to exploit weaknesses in the opponent's position. One of the key ideas for Black in this opening is to challenge White's central pawn on e4 with their pawn on d5 . This leads to a pawn exchange, after which Black can develop their knight to d7 , supporting the pawn on c6 and preparing to recapture on e4 if necessary. White, on the other hand, must decide how to develop their pieces and maintain central control. The most common plan involves playing Nf3 , Be2 , and O-O , followed by a timely c4 pawn break to challenge Black's pawn structure. Since we study the Alien and Martian Gambits, Ng5 is the move I recommend!} 5. Ng5 {A very aggressive move that I recommend. It can transpose to the Alien Gambit very easily, and if the pony gets kicked right away, then we use tactics.} Ngf6 6. N1f3 ({A fantastic move, preparing to transpose to the Alien Gambit after ... h6 .} 6. Nxf7 $4 {I have seen so many new players sac on f7 before ... h6 and say it's Alien Gambit. You should NEVER take on f7 if Black has not played ... h6 . It's imperative for Black to weaken the h5 - g8 diagonal and the pawn on h6 to be a target for sacs.}) 6... h6 7. Nxf7 {ALIEN GAMBIT!! Its just a transposition, but better for us, as there is no ... c5 ! now.} Kxf7 8. Bd3 {Please check the Alien Gambit chapter. :)} *

