1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 { This is the Caro-Kann Defense Karpov Variation. It is not a popular defense, but it can be a great surprise weapon since not many players with White will expect or know this variation of the Caro-Kann. Black aims to exchange the central pawns and then develop their pieces harmoniously, often with the intention of playing for a long-term advantage. The opening is known for its strategic depth and positional play, as both sides must carefully maneuver their pieces to exploit weaknesses in the opponent's position. One of the key ideas for Black in this opening is to challenge White's central pawn on e4 with their pawn on d5 . This leads to a pawn exchange, after which Black can develop their knight to d7 , supporting the pawn on c6 and preparing to recapture on e4 if necessary. White, on the other hand, must decide how to develop their pieces and maintain central control. The most common plan involves playing Nf3 , Be2 , and O-O , followed by a timely c4 pawn break to challenge Black's pawn structure. Since we study the Alien and Martian Gambits, Ng5 is the move I recommend!} 5. Ng5 {A very aggressive move that I recommend. It can transpose to the Alien Gambit very easily, and if the pony gets kicked right away, then we use tactics.} h6 {The most common move here, kicking the pony and expecting to go back, but... WE NEVER GO BACK!!!} 6. Ne6 {Stop it bebe!! A beautiful brilliant move. Black cannot take, as mate will follow. Of course, Black can move the queen, but then the position will be difficult to defend since, at worst, White can take the bishop pair advantage with Nxf8 .} Qb6 7. Ne2 ({SACRIFICING THE INTEGRITY OF THE POSITION FOR THE POSITIONAL BIND!! I am sorry, but this is too beautiful! The idea of this move is that it stops Black well-timed ... e5 ! response when White plays} 7. Bd3 {, and there are a lot of checkmates with the pony on e6 , as you will see.}) (7. Bd3 $6 { looks amazing only if Black's defensive move did not exist.} fxe6 8. Bg6+ Kd8 9. Nf3 e5 $1 {That's it! Black sacrifices one of the doubled pawns so they can develop their kingside. In the Martian Gambit, we don't allow this thematic sacrifice as our pony is on e5 . After} 10. dxe5 e6 11. O-O Kc7 {, Black is better, as their king is safe and they are a piece up. Now imagine this position with another black pawn on e7 . White would have been winning.}) (7. Nf3 $2 fxe6 8. Bd3 e5 $1 {Very, very strong move! The doubled e-pawns work against Black so they try to sacrifice one back to develop their pieces:} 9. dxe5 e6 {.}) 7... c5 {This comes too early, as Black lacks development.} 8. Nxc5 Nxc5 9. dxc5 Qxc5 10. Be3 {Developing with tempi is always good. :)} Qc7 11. Nc3 Nf6 12. Nb5 Qb8 13. Qd4 a6 14. Bf4 {And the black queen is trapped.} *

