CING THE INTEGRITY OF THE POSITION FOR THE POSITIONAL BIND!! I am sorry, but this is too beautiful! The idea of this move is that it stops Black well-timed ... e5 ! response when White plays} 7. Bd3 {, and there are a lot of checkmates with the pony on e6 , as you will see.}) (7. Bd3 $6 { looks amazing only if Black's defensive move did not exist.} fxe6 8. Bg6+ Kd8 9. Nf3 e5 $1 {That's it! Black sacrifices one of the doubled pawns so they can develop their kingside. In the Martian Gambit, we don't allow this thematic sacrifice as our pony is on e5 . After} 10. dxe5 e6 11. O-O Kc7 {, Black is better, as their king is safe and they are a piece up. Now imagine this position with another black pawn on e7 . White would have been winning.}) (7. Nf3 $2 fxe6 8. Bd3 e5 $1 {Very, very strong move! The doubled e-pawns work against Black so they try to sacrifice one back to develop their pieces:} 9. dxe5 e6 {.}) 7... fxe6 8. Nf4 {The pony joins the play for the light squares and the d1 - h5 diagonal is freed.} Ndf6 (8... e5 {here does not work, as the pony can land on e6 after the check:} 9. Qh5+ Kd8 10. Ne6# {.}) 9. Ng6 Rh7 10. Bd3 Bd7 11. O-O O-O-O 12. Qe2 {A full piece down, but the rookie on h7 is doomed to be taken after Nxf8 followed by Bxh7 .} Be8 13. Nxf8 {White is winning since Black will lose more material.} Rh8 14. Nxe6 Rd6 15. c4 {Up material and completely winning position; c5 is threatened.} *

