1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... g6 {The Gurgenidze System is a solid and somewhat passive opening that aims to create a strong pawn structure and a flexible position for Black. It is named after the Georgian Grandmaster Bukhuti Gurgenidze, who was known for his creative and unorthodox style of play. This opening is a variation of the Caro-Kann Defense, which is a popular choice among players who prefer a solid and reliable opening repertoire. In the Gurgenidze System, Black aims to counter White's central pawn advance with a pawn on c6 and a fianchettoed kingside bishop. This setup allows Black to maintain a solid pawn structure while also preparing to challenge White's center with a timely ... d5 pawn break. The fianchettoed bishop on g7 can also exert pressure on the long diagonal, potentially creating tactical opportunities for Black. One of the main ideas behind this opening is to provoke White into overextending their pawn structure, which can create weaknesses that Black can later exploit. The Gurgenidze System is not as aggressive as some other variations of the Caro-Kann Defense, but it can lead to a rich and complex middlegame. This move usually is used by stronger chess players playing less strong opponents. And the worst part for White is that there is no Alien and Martian Gambits. :(((((} 4. e5 {Excellent move, gaining space, and the bishop on g7 will hit at a rock!} f6 {An interesting move, attacking the center right away. It is not a very popular move, as the idea of 3...g6 is not to attack the e5 -pawn but the d4 -pawn.} 5. f4 Bg7 6. Nb3 {Stopping the ... c5 break.} Nh6 7. a4 {A very nice move, gaining space on the queenside. The center is blocked, so there is no hurry yet to develop the kingside.} O-O 8. a5 {Even more space!} Nd7 9. Nf3 { White is much better, as they have space advantage, and there is no clear way for Black to break open the game.} *

