1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... g6 {The Gurgenidze System is a solid and somewhat passive opening that aims to create a strong pawn structure and a flexible position for Black. It is named after the Georgian Grandmaster Bukhuti Gurgenidze, who was known for his creative and unorthodox style of play. This opening is a variation of the Caro-Kann Defense, which is a popular choice among players who prefer a solid and reliable opening repertoire. In the Gurgenidze System, Black aims to counter White's central pawn advance with a pawn on c6 and a fianchettoed kingside bishop. This setup allows Black to maintain a solid pawn structure while also preparing to challenge White's center with a timely ... d5 pawn break. The fianchettoed bishop on g7 can also exert pressure on the long diagonal, potentially creating tactical opportunities for Black. One of the main ideas behind this opening is to provoke White into overextending their pawn structure, which can create weaknesses that Black can later exploit. The Gurgenidze System is not as aggressive as some other variations of the Caro-Kann Defense, but it can lead to a rich and complex middlegame. This move usually is used by stronger chess players playing less strong opponents. And the worst part for White is that there is no Alien and Martian Gambits. :(((((} 4. e5 {Excellent move, gaining space, and the bishop on g7 will hit at a rock!} Bg7 {The bishop is kinda hitting at a rock because ... c5 will be met by c3 (you can see the reason behind 3.Nd2 ) protecting the d4 -pawn.} 5. Nb3 { Now we see the use of the pony on d2 . It can go on b3 and stop ... c5 . Also, if Black played ... c5 last move, c3 would have been possible. It would have not been possible if we played 3.Nc3 . Chess is beautiful. Every single move matters.} a5 6. a4 {It's imperative to stop ... a4 from Black. That kicks our active pony and gives Black a space advantage.} Nh6 7. f4 Nf5 8. g4 Nh6 9. f5 { A beautiful move, sacrificing a pawn, so after g5 , the black pony won't land on f5 .} (9. g5 $2 Nf5 $1 {Black's pieces are excellently placed. That is not what you aim as White here. You need to obstruct the movement of your opponent's pieces when you have space advantage.}) 9... gxf5 10. g5 {Now there is no pony f5 .} Ng8 11. Ne2 e6 12. h4 Nd7 13. Nf4 {White is much better as they have a positional bind, Black has permanent weakness of dark squares, and the light-squared bishop is very, very passive.} ({To summarize, if you play} 13. Nd2 {and after g6 e5! you won't have that big of a problem. Good luck, have fun.❤}) *

