[PlyCount "33"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 { The Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense, also known as the Capablanca Variation.  4...Bf5 , developing the bishop outside the pawn chain, is a key strategy in the Caro-Kann. This variation presents a solid and highly flexible structure for Black, aiming to withstand White's central pressure while preparing a counterattack. White has several plans to choose from, such as playing Ng3 to attack the bishop on f5 and potentially gain the bishop pair after an exchange. Another plan involves playing Bd3 , offering a trade of bishops and potentially doubling Black's pawns on the f-file. White can also opt for a more aggressive setup with f4 and Nf3 , aiming for a kingside attack. Overall, the Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense is a solid and reliable choice for Black, offering a balanced position with chances for both sides. Popular among players of all levels, from club players to grandmasters, this opening is valued for its flexibility and adaptability. This move was played most notably in Game 2, Vishy Anand vs Magnus Carlsen – 2013 World Chess Championship, which gave Magnus an easy draw with Black (because Vishy didn't play Ng5! :-))} 5. Ng5 {After everything has been said for 4...Bf5 , this move comes with shock to people, and if you know what you are doing, you can win VERY easily. When attacking, never go back! Still preparing to sacrifice on f7 after ... h6 . I am sure after this move, Black is out of home prep.} (5. Ng3 {is THE most popular move, but with good play, Black is doing more than OK.}) 5... h6 6. Nxf7 {Alien Gambit!!! You need to know the Alien Gambit to play 5.Ng5 !} Kxf7 7. Nf3 {And now this is the critical moment.} Nd7 {A rare move, but tricky. Now we can never transpose to the main lines with Bf5 coz the pony is controlling the e5 -square.} 8. Nh4 {The pony can no longer hop on e5 so it goes on h4 .} e6 {Super duper rare move, but not bad at all. Now we switch play to the light squares.} 9. Nxf5 exf5 10. Bc4+ Kg6 ({ The black king is actually safe. The lack of a pony for White makes it difficult to attack. Instead,} 10... Ke8 {runs into} 11. Qh5+ Ke7 12. Qf7+ Kd6 13. Bf4+ Ne5 14. Bxe5# {.}) 11. g4 {Trying to open as many files as possible before Black develops.} Ne7 12. gxf5+ Nxf5 13. Qg4+ Kf6 14. Rg1 Qe8+ 15. Kf1 g5 16. Bxg5+ {BRILLIANT!!} hxg5 17. Qxg5# *

