1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 { The Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense, also known as the Capablanca Variation.  4...Bf5 , developing the bishop outside the pawn chain, is a key strategy in the Caro-Kann. This variation presents a solid and highly flexible structure for Black, aiming to withstand White's central pressure while preparing a counterattack. White has several plans to choose from, such as playing Ng3 to attack the bishop on f5 and potentially gain the bishop pair after an exchange. Another plan involves playing Bd3 , offering a trade of bishops and potentially doubling Black's pawns on the f-file. White can also opt for a more aggressive setup with f4 and Nf3 , aiming for a kingside attack. Overall, the Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense is a solid and reliable choice for Black, offering a balanced position with chances for both sides. Popular among players of all levels, from club players to grandmasters, this opening is valued for its flexibility and adaptability. This move was played most notably in Game 2, Vishy Anand vs Magnus Carlsen – 2013 World Chess Championship, which gave Magnus an easy draw with Black (because Vishy didn't play Ng5! :-))} 5. Ng5 {After everything has been said for 4...Bf5 , this move comes with shock to people, and if you know what you are doing, you can win VERY easily. When attacking, never go back! Still preparing to sacrifice on f7 after ... h6 . I am sure after this move, Black is out of home prep.} (5. Ng3 {is THE most popular move, but with good play, Black is doing more than OK.}) 5... e6 ({This is not such a rare move, but I face} 5... Bg6 { way more often. The idea is simple. They don't want to go into the Alien Gambit with h6 or Martian Gambit with Bg6 , so they make just a good developing move.}) 6. N1f3 {A very good reaction. I still have high hopes for the Alien Gambit transpositions.} h6 7. Nxf7 {Alieeeen Gambit!!!!} Kxf7 8. Bc4 {Wanting to transpose to the main lines of AG with 7...Bf5 .} Nd7 {A rare move, but we can no longer transpose to the main lines with Ne5 + followed by g4 ! Very annoying to be honest... Now, we cannot transpose to normal AG lines, :(} 9. O-O Ngf6 10. Nh4 Bh7 11. Re1 Nd5 12. Qh5+ {Forcing ... g6 to block the bishop on h7 .} g6 13. Qg4 Qf6 14. Nf3 Re8 15. h4 {With chaos on the board. White is super duper active and enjoys space advantage but lacks a piece. Black is a piece up but lacks space, and the bishop on h7 looks silly. Also, Black cannot develop their dark-squared bishop on the f8 - a3 diagonal because the h6 -pawn will hang.} ({Bg7} 15. Bd3 $1 {, a very good move. The bishop on d5 is hitting a rock, so we change the diagonal. Rhf8 c4} Ne7 $4 (15... N5b6 16. a4 {and Black is a piece up, but White has an amazing space advantage and easier play.}) 16. Bg5 $3 {WOW! Brilliant move out of nowhere, sacrificing the bishop to trap the queen!} hxg5 {( h5} 17. Qh3 {, the black queen is still trapped.) hxg5 , bye-bye Danya, bye-bye as Hikaru would say. The queen is trapped!}) *

