1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now} 2... g6 {(Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng5 Bg6 6. N1f3 e6 {There is nothing more boring than you are 1 move away from AG or MG, and Black plays a move that doesn't allow you to play them. :(( Practice has shown that if they leave the pony on g5 , White is doing absolutely fantastic. One mistake from Black, and they get destroyed tactically with Nxe6 !! or Nxf7 !! My Five Lifelines: A. Develop quickly, and always keep in mind that if Black plays ... h6 , you can still transpose to AG or MG. B. After development is finished, play h4 !! sacrificing your pony on g5 , as Black is castled short, so they will open your h-file for you. C. It's imperative to always be vigilant for sacrifices on f7 / e6 . Your pony on g5 is a super duper strong tactical piece. D. Try to play on the kingside and remember to use the power of the bishop pair. E. When Black castles kingside, play fast and furious, following my attacking rules as outlined in the chapter.} *

