pening is valued for its flexibility and adaptability. This move was played most notably in Game 2, Vishy Anand vs Magnus Carlsen – 2013 World Chess Championship, which gave Magnus an easy draw with Black (because Vishy didn't play Ng5! :-))} 5. Ng5 {After everything has been said for 4...Bf5 , this move comes with shock to people, and if you know what you are doing, you can win VERY easily. When attacking, never go back! Still preparing to sacrifice on f7 after ... h6 . I am sure after this move, Black is out of home prep.} (5. Ng3 {is THE most popular move, but with good play, Black is doing more than OK.}) 5... e6 ({This is not such a rare move, but I face} 5... Bg6 {way more often. The idea is simple. They don't want to go into the Alien Gambit with h6 or Martian Gambit with Bg6 , so they make just a good developing move. After this, with all due respect, boring move, you can never get MG. :((( But behold! You can still get AG. :))) The idea of this is to play boring... I am sorry, I don't like facing this move. Okay, for real, the idea of this move is to play boring. Nothing more to say. They develop their bishop on f8 .}) 6. N1f3 {A very good move. I still have high hopes for an Alien Gambit transposition.} Nd7 {After this move, we can not transpose to AG or MG. It's quite sad. Still, White is doing great if they find their next move!} 7. Nh4 {Fantastic move! White is trying to be less tactical and more focused on the long-term positional advantage, aka getting the bishop pair.} Be7 8. Nxf5 exf5 9. Nf3 {Time to go back. We've got the bishop pair and the better pawn structure.} Ngf6 10. g3 {A very nice move, the bishop belongs on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} O-O 11. Bg2 Re8 12. O-O Bf8 13. c3 {White is a bit better and long-term much better as they have the bishop pair and 4 vs. 3 on the queenside. And it is difficult to see how Black can create counterplay, as the ... c5 break will just open the game for White's bishops.} *

