pening is valued for its flexibility and adaptability. This move was played most notably in Game 2, Vishy Anand vs Magnus Carlsen – 2013 World Chess Championship, which gave Magnus an easy draw with Black (because Vishy didn't play Ng5! :-))} 5. Ng5 {After everything has been said for 4...Bf5 , this move comes with shock to people, and if you know what you are doing, you can win VERY easily. When attacking, never go back! Still preparing to sacrifice on f7 after ... h6 . I am sure after this move, Black is out of home prep.} (5. Ng3 {is THE most popular move, but with good play, Black is doing more than OK.}) 5... e6 ({This is not such a rare move, but I face} 5... Bg6 {way more often. The idea is simple. They don't want to go into the Alien Gambit with h6 or Martian Gambit with Bg6 , so they make just a good developing move. After this, with all due respect, boring move, you can never get MG. :((( But behold! You can still get AG. :))) The idea of this is to play boring... I am sorry, I don't like facing this move. Okay, for real, the idea of this move is to play boring. Nothing more to say. They develop their bishop on f8 .}) 6. N1f3 {A very good move. I still have high hopes for an Alien Gambit transposition.} Nf6 7. Ne5 {One of the drawbacks of keeping the pony on g5 . Now, f7 is lost, and with it, the game.} Bg6 8. Bd3 {A very nice move. White is now winning in just 8 moves! That is what happens if you leave the pony on g5 for too long. The f7 -pawn will be lost after bishops are exchanged.} Nbd7 (8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 {and f7 cannot be defended, which will cost Black the game.}) 9. Bxg6 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 hxg6 12. exf6 gxf6 13. Nf3 {White is a piece up with a winning game.} *

