{Hello there! :) How are you? Please make sure you have learned the previous chapters before learning this one. It is imperative to know the Alien and Martian Gambits before this. Here, we will learn what to do if Black does NOT play ... h6 to allow AG and MG. As you will see, letting the pony stay on g5 gives White amazing, amazing tactical opportunities.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 ({ Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now} 2... g6 {(Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3. Nd2 ({Playing the pony on d2 or c3 does not matter much at all. I personally like it on d2 , as if now g6 (Gurgenidze Variation) , Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn. Now after} 3. c3 {, the fianchettoed bishop has little to do because of the pawn chain on the dark squares.}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 g6 {A weird and boring move, with all due respect. Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7 , creating pressure against White's d4 -pawn.} 5. Nf3 Bg7 (5... Nf6 6. Neg5 h6 7. Nxf7 $3 {Alien Gambit!!!!!} Kxf7 8. Bd3 { and we get a transposition to the Alien Gambit – feel free to check the corresponding chapter.}) 6. Bd3 {Sacrificing the d4 -pawn.} Nf6 7. O-O O-O 8. Nxf6+ Bxf6 9. c3 {White has a stable advantage, as our center is defended, and we have the half-open e-file.} *

