ny.}) (5. Nxf6+ {is the most common move and the move I used to play a lot before I invented the Alien Gambit. Korchnoi (or Tartakower) Variation, Black's} exf6 {, is regarded as sounder than gxf6!? , the Bronstein-Larsen Variation, which offers Black rapid development, though also ceding White the superior pawn structure and long-term prospects (Black has to be cautious that the d-pawn is now a potential passed pawn in the endgame).}) ( {Since we won't play Nxf6 but hop with the pony on g5 , we stop the lines here. } 5. Ng3 {is a move I played a lot, with bad results after} h5 $1) 5... e6 { This move is very, very popular if Black has already lost against the Alien Gambit many, many times and they quit. Very often, it transposes to the Alien Gambit if Black plays ... h6 before castling. Black's main idea is to castle and only then play ... h6 , so they avoid AG. Trust me, this move is very popular, as AG is becoming so OP that people try to avoid it.} 6. N1f3 Bd6 ( 6... Be7 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 h6 10. Nxe6 $3 fxe6 11. Qxe6+ Rf7 12. Bg6 Qf8 13. Bg5 $3 hxg5 14. Nxg5 Ne5 15. Qxe5) 7. Bd3 {White develops in a way that after each move by Black, they can still transpose to AG. All that it takes is ... h6 . So White is following the right plan, putting the bishop on d3 .} O-O {That's it! You can never transpose to the Alien Gambit anymore. Black has castled. Now Black's next move is ... h6 (that happens all the time when they play that against me.), and we go... back? Right? Hmmmmm...} 8. Qe2 { A very strong move. This move does three things: 1. Stopping ... Nd7 , as Nxe6 will be brilliant. 2. It controls the e5 -square and gets out of potential queen exchanges along the d-file. 3. It prepares the big castle.} Nbd7 { A very common blunder I have faced, and here Black is just losing due to White's beautiful tactic.} 9. Nxe6 {BRILLIANT! Sacrificing the pony to make use of the undefended bishop on d6 .} fxe6 10. Qxe6+ Kh8 11. Qxd6 {White is two pawns up with an easy winning game.} *

