1. e4 e6 {This is the French Defense.} 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Ng5 h6 6. Nxf7 {The Alien Gambit Bonjour Variation!! Bonjour because it's against the French. It's super duper popular, and I have won against so many GMs with it. Still, it's less effective as the pawn is not on c6 , and there is already a pawn on e6 , reducing errors from Black. Feel free to learn it on YouTube – The Gambit That Shocked France - Alien Gambit Bonjour Variation .} Kxf7 7. Nf3 Bd6 8. Bd3 Nbd7 9. O-O Re8 10. Re1 {The plans are the same! It's all about hopping with the pony on the e5 -square.} Kg8 11. Ne5 Bxe5 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Qg4 {A very strong move. The queen joins the attack with the Bxh6 threat.} Kh8 14. Bxh6 {Brilliant! Sacrificing the bishop so that after ... gxh6 , the h6 -pawn will be hanging.} gxh6 15. Qg6 Qe7 (15... Nf8 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17. Re4 Kf7 18. Rg4 Ke7 19. Qg7#) 16. c4 {It's imperative to kick the pony on e5 , so there are no brilliant defense tactics with ... Ndf6 !!} (16. Qxh6+ $2 {Imagine taking a pawn with check is a blunder. The pony on d5 needs to be kicked first and only then swing with the rookie.} Kg8 17. Re4 Qg7 18. Qh5 N7f6 $3 19. exf6 Nxf6 20. Qh4 Nxe4 21. Qxe4 Bd7 {.}) 16... Nb4 17. Qxh6+ Kg8 18. Re3 ({Typical for the Alien Gambit − the rookies always come over to help with the attack:} 18. Qg7+ {Rg3 Qxg3 Qh7+ Kf8 fxg3 Nxd3 Rf1+ Nf6 Rxf6# .}) *

