1. e4 d5 {This is the Scandinavian Defense.} 2. Nc3 c6 3. d4 {YES!!! It's a transposition to the Caro-Kann! More Caro-Kanns = more AG, and MG = more happiness❤} dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 (4... Bf5 5. Ng5 Bg6 6. N1f3 h6 7. Ne6 $3 { is a transposition to the Martian Gambit .}) 5. Ng5 ({This move initializes the Alien Gambit! At least in chess.com! For my dear viewers and me, Alien Gambit starts after h6 , and Nxf7!! So, to state that this move is already bringing us to the Alien Gambit is wrong. Here, you can even transpose to the Martian Gambit if Black plays Bf5} 5. Nf3 {Bg6 Bc4} h6 {and Ne6!! Chess.com told me that the decision is based on the following: if you go Ng5 , you plan to sacrifice, but Black is not forced to go ... h6 , even though 90% of the people play ... h6 . The idea of Ng5 is simple. Play for the Alien Gambit! When you play this move, don't ever think of going back with the pony.}) (5. Nxf6+ {is the most common move and the move I used to play a lot before I invented the Alien Gambit. Korchnoi (or Tartakower) Variation, Black's} exf6 { , is regarded as sounder than gxf6!? , the Bronstein-Larsen Variation, which offers Black rapid development, though also ceding White the superior pawn structure and long-term prospects (Black has to be cautious that the d-pawn is now a potential passed pawn in the endgame).}) ({Since we won't play Nxf6 but hop with the pony on g5 , we stop the lines here.} 5. Ng3 {is a move I played a lot, with bad results after} h5 $1) 5... h6 6. Nxf7 Kxf7 7. Nf3 {And this is a transposition to the Alien Gambit .} *

