1. e4 d5 {This is the Scandinavian Defense.} 2. Nc3 dxe4 3. Nxe4 Bf5 4. Ng5 Bg6 5. N1f3 h6 6. Ne6 {The Martian Gambit Viking Variation!! Please play at your own risk. White is a critical tempo down, but do not lose heart. The knowledge learned can still be applied here.} fxe6 7. Ne5 Bf7 8. Qf3 ({Wait a second... What is the difference here and in the Caro? Well, our pawn is on d4 (so} 8. Bc4 {is gg, as Black almost never manages to defend). Here, the pawn is on d2 , and there is no pawn on c6 , so now Qf3 attacks the b7 -pawn!!}) 8... Nf6 9. Qxb7 Nbd7 (9... Qd5 $4 10. Qc8+ Qd8 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Nxf7+ Ke8 13. Nxh8 { and White is a rookie up with an easy win.}) 10. Qc6 ({This move is interesting if you don't want to go to an endgame with} 10. Nc6 {, where White has a rookie for two minor pieces. This move keeps the heat on.}) 10... g5 11. Bc4 {The threat is the very strong Nxf7 here followed by Qxe6 . White is already a little bit better, thanks to our active pieces.} Bg7 {A very common move; it's very easy to forget about Nxf7 followed by Qxe6 .} (11... Bg8 12. d4 Bg7 13. h4 Rb8 14. hxg5 hxg5 15. Rxh8 Bxh8 16. Bxg5 Rxb2 $6 {( Rb6} 17. Qf3 { ) Bb3± , and the rookie on b2 is trapped. Please note that the Martian Gambit positional bind is still applied here.}) 12. Nxf7 Kxf7 13. Qxe6+ Kg6 (13... Kf8 14. Qf7# {, and if Ke8 Qf7# .}) 14. Bd3+ Kh5 15. Qh3# *

