1. e4 d5 {This is the Scandinavian Defense.} 2. Nc3 dxe4 3. Nxe4 Bf5 4. Ng5 h6 ({Wait... Is} 4... h6 {marked as '?' This gotta be a mistake, right?}) 5. Nxf7 {THE ALIEN GAMBIT VIKING VARIATION IS BRILLIANT!!! Shocking right? The fact that the pawns are NOT on c6 and d4 is in White's favor, as we will see.} Kxf7 6. Qf3 {Tada!! Black will lose the bishop, has a weak king, and a worse pawn structure! In a normal Alien Gambit against the Caro-Kann, the black pawn is on c6 and the white pawn on d4 , so here there would be ... Qd5 ! For Black, that would just win the game!} ({e6 or g6 won't save the bishop due to} 6. g4 { .}) 6... Kg6 {The game between CM Witty_Alien (2603) vs. Chepakh (2662), Jan 30, 2025, continued: 6... Qd7 ? Protecting the bishop this way does not work, as g4 will win it back regardless.} ({g4!} 6... Nf6 {gxf5 and White is completely winning. We are a pawn up, and Black's light squares are so weak.}) {Qxf5? This bad move was played during the game, but I managed to win regardless, as White is still much better. Feel free to see my reactions on YouTube – Alien Gambit Viking Variation IS BRILLIANT!!} 7. Qxb7 {Okay, you might think the rookie on a8 is attacked, but after ... Nd7 , Black is just a piece up, no?} (7. g4 $2 Bxc2 $1 8. Qxb7 Nf6 $3 {Brilliant move. It's all about the e4 -square.} 9. Qxa8 Be4 {and Black is winning, as they will win back the rookie, with a piece up.}) 7... Nd7 {Now what?} 8. g4 {In the midst of chaos, White has the audacity of hope to go g4 !! This is the only move not to lose the game and the whole idea of Nxf7!! White is +1 here. Shockingly enough, the bishop is kinda trapped!} Be6 9. f4 {Amazing move. Now, f5 + cannot be stopped. Not very often do you see one player just play g4 , f4 , and win the game. In this position, it works, as Black's king is very weak on g6 , and there is no ... Qh4 +. Welcome to the out-of-this-world gambits.} Kf6 (9... Kh7 $2 10. Qe4+ {wins the bishop and the game.}) 10. Qe4 {A very strong move, centralizing the queen and preparing to put the bishop on the a1 - h8 diagonal.} g6 11. b3 Kg7 12. Bb2+ Ngf6 13. g5 hxg5 14. fxg5 Rh5 15. Bg2 { Another very strong move! White is not in a hurry to take on f6 , as that will release the tension, and Black will kinda develop their pieces. The threat is stronger than the execution.} Rb8 16. Qe3 {White is easily winning, as at the right moment we will take on f6 , but before that, we will develop our pieces and improve our position. It's not clear what Black can do to improve their position.} *

